INSERT INTO `page_drafts` VALUES (28,NULL,'','','',NULL,36,'2016-08-22 14:09:05','2016-08-22 14:09:05'),(35,28,'Resize a Hard Disk for a Virtual Machine','','<h1>Resize a Hard Disk for a Virtual Machine</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Our Virtual Machines are provisioned using Vagrant from a Linux base box to run using VirutalBox. If the Hard Disk space runs out and you cannot remove files to free-up space, you can resize the Hard Disk using some VirtualBox and Linux commands.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Some assumptions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The following steps assume you&#39;ve got a set-up where:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>you use a Linux command-line terminal on your host machine</li>\r\n	<li>the vagrant boxes live at the path&nbsp;<code>provisioning/boxes/mybox</code></li>\r\n	<li>VirtualBox creates new Virtual Machines in the default location&nbsp;<code>~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>Steps to resize the hard disk</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Stop the virtual machine using Vagrant.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd provisioning/boxes/mybox\r\n# vagrant halt\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Locate the VirtuaBox VM and the HDD attached to its IDE Controller. In this instance we&#39;re assuming the VM is located in the default location and is named&nbsp;<code>mybox_default_1382400620</code>.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd ~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/mybox_default_1382400620\r\n# VBoxManage showvminfo mybox_default_1382400620 | grep &quot;.vmdk&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p>The&nbsp;<code>showvminfo</code>&nbsp;command should show you the location on the file-system of the HDD of type VMDK along with the name of the Controller it is attached to - it will look something like this:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code>IDE Controller (0, 0): \\VirtualBox VMs\\mybox_default_1382400620\\box-disk1.vmdk (UUID: 2f79610e-6c06-46d5-becb-448386ea40ec)\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>clone the VMDK type disk to a VDI type disk so it can be resized.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd ~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/mybox_default_1382400620\r\n# VBoxManage clonehd &quot;box-disk1.vmdk&quot; &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot; --format vdi\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>NOTE: We do this because VMDK type disks cannot be resized by VirtualBox. It has the added benefit of allowing us to keep our original disk backed-up during the resize operation.</em></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out how big the disk is currently, to determine how large to make it when resized. The information will show the current size and the Format variant. If Dynamic Allocation was used to create the disk, the Format variant will be &quot;dynamic default&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage showhdinfo &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Resize the cloned disk to give it more space. The size argument below is given in Megabytes (1024 Bytes = 1 Megabyte). Because this disk was created using&nbsp;<em>dynamic allocation</em>&nbsp;I&#39;m going to resize it to 100 Gigabytes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage modifyhd &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot; --resize 102400\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>NOTE: If the disk was created using</em>&nbsp;dynamic allocation&nbsp;<em>(see previous step) then the</em>&nbsp;physical size&nbsp;<em>of the disk will not need to match its</em>&nbsp;logical size&nbsp;<em>- meaning you can create a very large logical disk that will increase in physical size only as space is used.</em></p>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>TIP: To&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.conversion-metric.org/filesize/gigabytes-to-megabytes\">convert a Gigabyte value into Megabytes</a>&nbsp;use an online calculator.</em></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out the name of the Storage Controller to attach the newly resized disk to.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage showvminfo mybox_default_1382400620 | grep &quot;Storage&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Attach the newly resized disk to the Storage Controller of the Virtual Machine. In our case we&#39;re going to use the same name for the Storage Controller,&nbsp;<code>IDE Controller</code>, as revealed in the step above.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage storageattach mybox_default_1382400620 --storagectl &quot;IDE Controller&quot; --port 0 --device 0 --type hdd --medium clone-disk1.vdi\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Reboot the Virtual Machine using Vagrant.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd provisioning/boxes/mybox\r\n# vagrant up\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Open a command-line shell as root on the Virtual Machine via ssh.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vagrant ssh\r\n# sudo bash\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find the name of the logical volume mapping the file-system is on (ie.&nbsp;<code>/dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># df \r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find the name of the physical volume (or device) that all the partitions are created on (ie.&nbsp;<code>/dev/sda</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># fdisk -l\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new primary partition for use as a Linux LVM</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># fdisk /dev/sda\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>p</code>&nbsp;to print the partition table to identify the number of partitions. By default there are two -&nbsp;<code>sda1</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>sda2</code>.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>n</code>&nbsp;to create a new primary partition.&nbsp;</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>p</code>&nbsp;for primary.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>3</code>&nbsp;for the partition number, depending the output of the partition table print.</li>\r\n		<li>Press Enter two times to accept the default First and Last cylinder.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>t</code>&nbsp;to change the system&#39;s partition ID</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>3</code>&nbsp;to select the newly creation partition</li>\r\n		<li>Type&nbsp;<code>8e</code>&nbsp;to change the Hex Code of the partition for&nbsp;<code>Linux LVM</code></li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>w</code>&nbsp;to write the changes to the partition table.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Reboot the machine, then ssh back in when it is up again and switch to the root user once more.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># reboot\r\n# vagrant ssh\r\n# sudo su -\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new physical volume using the new primary partition just created.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># pvcreate /dev/sda3\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out the name of the Volume Group that the Logical Volume mapping belongs to (ie.&nbsp;<code>VolGroupOS</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vgdisplay\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Extend the Volume Group to use the newly created physical volume.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vgextend VolGroupOS /dev/sda3\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Extend the logical volume to use more of the Volume Group size now available to it. You can either tell it to add a set amount of space in Megabytes, Gigabytes or Terabytes, and control the growth of the Disk:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># lvextend -L+20G /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p>Or if you want to use all the free space now available to the Volume Group:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Resize the file-system to use up the space made available in the Logical Volume&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># resize2fs /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Verfiy that there is now more space available</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># df -h \r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>A restart of the VM using vagrant may be a good idea here, to ensure that all services are running correctly now that there is more space available. Exit the root user, exit the vagrant user and ssh session, then tell vagrant to restart the machine.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># exit\r\n# exit\r\n# vagrant reload</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Guide based very heavily on Christopher Hoppers guide found here:&nbsp;https://gist.github.com/christopher-hopper/9755310</p>\r\n',NULL,19,'2016-08-24 11:53:45','2016-08-24 11:56:45'),(55,0,'Prism Database Tables','Describes tables used by Prism in iaptus and Postroom','<table border=\"1\" bordercolor=\"#ccc\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:1000px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Table Name</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Codebase</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_clinical_contact</td>\r\n			<td>Postroom</td>\r\n			<td>Contains clinical contact data returned from online provider.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_episode</td>\r\n			<td>Postroom</td>\r\n			<td>Maps episode IDs to external patient UUIDs, episode UUIDs and therapist UUIDs.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_clinical_contact_link</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Links a clinical contact ID with an atlas clinical contact ID from postroom (atlas_clinical_contact).</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field_config</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Field configurations for data to send to online providers (providers have different requirements).</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field_history</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>History of changes made to Prism field confi</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_sent_referrals</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Details about episodes that have been sent off to third party online provider.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_service</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Links an online provider to an iaptus service. &nbsp;Interface for this is in left hand superuser menu in iaptus, under &quot;Online Providers&quot; menu option.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',NULL,34,'2016-09-13 12:55:07','2016-09-13 14:14:40'),(63,29,'Setting Care Pathway Diagram Locally','','<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>In local iaptus database truncate nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Copy row from nh_diagram table from iaptus_demo database that has a diagram that you want to set up locally.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Insert this row into nh_diagram table into your local iaptus database. Remember to change ser_id value to 101.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Go to “New Care Pathway Tool” in local Iaptus front-end.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Open the diagram you have just inserted into the database.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Click “Export To Demo Site”. This will populate rows in nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables and you will be able to see this care pathway in “Care Pathway (Mayden Only)” tool.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',NULL,35,'2016-09-20 15:50:56','2016-09-20 15:50:56'),(64,29,'Setting Care Pathway Diagram Locally','to be updated','<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>In local iaptus database truncate nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Copy row from nh_diagram table from iaptus_demo database that has a diagram that you want to set up locally.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Insert this row into nh_diagram table into your local iaptus database. Remember to change ser_id value to 101.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Go to “New Care Pathway Tool” in local Iaptus front-end.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Open the diagram you have just inserted into the database.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Click “Export To Demo Site”. This will populate rows in nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables and you will be able to see this care pathway in “Care Pathway (Mayden Only)” tool.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',NULL,35,'2016-09-20 15:51:25','2016-09-20 15:51:25'),(65,29,'Understanding XML Care Pathway Diagram','to be updated','<p><strong>Diagram lives in nh_diagram table in demo database in xml column. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The diagram starts with &nbsp;a &lt;carepathway&gt; tag and it is divided into 4 parts:<br />\r\n1. All stages (excluding discharge stages)<br />\r\n2. All links.<br />\r\n3. All discharge stages (from nh_stage table where discharge_group_id = 1 or 2 and type = process, or type = end)<br />\r\n4. All groups where discharge_group_id is non-zero.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&lt;carepathway services=”100,101,102,103,115”&gt;<br />\r\nServices are numbers that correspond to service_pathway_id in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global database. In example: 100 corresponds to IAPT0 and 115 to Employment.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>All stages (excluding discharge stages) are contained in &lt;node&gt; tags right after &lt;carepathway&gt; tag.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;node id=\"2\"&gt; // found in id column in nh_stage table (prefixed with service number if on demo database)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagecode&gt;REF&lt;/stagecode&gt; // found in code column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagename&gt;Referral Received&lt;/stagename&gt; // found in title column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagelevel&gt;0&lt;/stagelevel&gt; // found in stage_intensity column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;servicecode&gt;IAPT0&lt;/servicecode&gt; // found in code column in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;service&gt;100&lt;/service&gt; // found in service_pathway_id column in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagetype&gt;Treatment&lt;/stagetype&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;redvalue&gt;2&lt;/redvalue&gt; // found in second_waring column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;yellowvalue&gt;1&lt;/yellowvalue&gt; &nbsp;// found in first_warning column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;hidden&gt;0&lt;/hidden&gt; // depends on live column in nh_stage table (when live=1 is 0, when live=0 is 1)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;xcord&gt;947.3&lt;/xcord&gt; // x coordinates on diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ycord&gt;89.35&lt;/ycord&gt; // x coordinates on diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;width&gt;160&lt;/width&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;height&gt;100&lt;/height&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;strokeWidth&gt;2&lt;/strokeWidth&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;strokeColor&gt;#000000&lt;/strokeColor&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stageColor&gt;#FFFFFF&lt;/stageColor&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/node&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. All links - found in nh_stage_process, contained in &lt;links&gt; tag.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:<br />\r\n&lt;links&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;link id=\"3\" name=\"line3\" direction=\"down\" source=\"rectangle2\" target=\"rectangle4\" xCoords=\"1027.3,1027.4\" yCoords=\"131.35,254\" hidden=\"0\" archived=\"0\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/links&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Id number corresponds to id column in nh_stage_process (prefixed with service number if on demo database).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Source is a value in stage_from column and target is value in stage_to column, hence example link come from stage with id value of 2 to stage with id value of 4. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>x- and yCoords are values of start and end point on the diagram.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" - &nbsp;means is visible in the diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>archived=\"0\" - means value in live column in nh_stage_process is 1</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" archived=\"0\" - setup for live link between non-discharge stages ( where value in type column is ‘bak’, ‘fwd’ or ‘def’ but never when is ‘end’)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"1\" archived=\"0\" - for any discharge stages or any stage to/from discharge planning or refer on ( when value in type column is ‘end’ or ‘def’); it also can be a links from a stage that has been archived</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"1\" archived=\"1\" - for all archived links</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" archived=\"1\" - this set up is incorrect and should never appear in the diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. All discharge stages for each care pathway service are contained in &lt;discharge&gt; tag</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;discharge&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;node id=\"162\" hidden=\"0\" imported=\"1\" group_id=\"1\" link_id=\"\" disp=\"yes\"&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagecode&gt;DISP&lt;/stagecode&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagename&gt;Discharge &nbsp;Planning / Referrals&lt;/stagename&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;mds&gt;Not Known &nbsp;- 215&lt;/mds&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;level&gt;0&lt;/level&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;serviceid&gt;100&lt;/serviceid&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;servicecode&gt;IAPT0&lt;/servicecode&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/node&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/discharge&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Similar to non-discharge stages, id can be found in id column in nh_stage table (prefixed with service number if on demo database). </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=”0” - means is live (ticked in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool”)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=”1” - means is archived (unticked in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool”)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Group_id - corresponds to &nbsp;discharge_group_id column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Link_id - link id (value in id column in nh_stage_process table) that corresponds to link going into stage with id in that node (i.e. where target=”rectangle162” in xml or where stage_to column value is 162).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>disp: &nbsp;“yes” - means it is a “Discharge Planning Stage, “ref” - means it is “Refer On” stage, “no” - means it is standard discharge stage.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stagecode, stagename, level, serviceid, servicecode can be found the same as for non-discharge stages in point 1.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. &nbsp;Discharge Groups are contained in &lt;discharge&gt; tag after discharge nodes</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;group id=\"9\" groupcode=\"NSS\" groupname=\"Not Suitable for Service\" mds=\"Not suitable for service - 214\" xcord=\"41\" ycord=\"270\" hidden=\"0\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;group id=\"28\" groupcode=\"ATCC\" groupname=\"(Old) Assessment and Treatment Care Complete\" mds=\"Completed treatment - 210\" xcord=\"41\" ycord=\"840\" hidden=\"1\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>id - corresponds to &nbsp;id column in nh_stage_group and to group_id in discharge node in xml</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>groupname - corresponds to &nbsp;group_name column in nh_stage_group</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>mds - corresponds to &lt;mds&gt; in discharge node in xml</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden - when the value is 0, group is live; when the value is 1, group has been archived, ‘(Old)’ is added to from of the group’s name, it appears grayed out in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool” and all discharge nodes in xml that belong to this group have the hidden value set to 1.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Information which stages belong to which group can be found in link table nh_stage_togroup.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: in nh_diagram when value in autosave column is 1 it means it has NOT been autosaved.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: When archiving a stage, in diagram, set all links going into that stage to hidden=\"1\" archived=\"1\" (to disallow to move any patient into that stage) and change value in live column to 0 in nh_stage_process, and all links going out of that stage to hidden=\"1\" archived=\"0\" (to allow any patient that is currently in that stage to be move out from it). In nh_stage do NOT set value in live column to 0, unless you are 100% sure that you will not strand any patient in that stage).</strong></p>\r\n',NULL,35,'2016-09-20 15:56:21','2016-09-20 15:56:21'),(66,29,'Understanding XML Care Pathway Diagram','to be updated','<p><strong>Diagram lives in nh_diagram table in demo database in xml column. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The diagram starts with &nbsp;a &lt;carepathway&gt; tag and it is divided into 4 parts:<br />\r\n1. All stages (excluding discharge stages)<br />\r\n2. All links.<br />\r\n3. All discharge stages (from nh_stage table where discharge_group_id = 1 or 2 and type = process, or type = end)<br />\r\n4. All groups where discharge_group_id is non-zero.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&lt;carepathway services=”100,101,102,103,115”&gt;<br />\r\nServices are numbers that correspond to service_pathway_id in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global database. In example: 100 corresponds to IAPT0 and 115 to Employment.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>All stages (excluding discharge stages) are contained in &lt;node&gt; tags right after &lt;carepathway&gt; tag.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;node id=\"2\"&gt; // found in id column in nh_stage table (prefixed with service number if on demo database)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagecode&gt;REF&lt;/stagecode&gt; // found in code column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagename&gt;Referral Received&lt;/stagename&gt; // found in title column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagelevel&gt;0&lt;/stagelevel&gt; // found in stage_intensity column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;servicecode&gt;IAPT0&lt;/servicecode&gt; // found in code column in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;service&gt;100&lt;/service&gt; // found in service_pathway_id column in nh_pathway_service in Iaptus_global</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagetype&gt;Treatment&lt;/stagetype&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;redvalue&gt;2&lt;/redvalue&gt; // found in second_waring column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;yellowvalue&gt;1&lt;/yellowvalue&gt; &nbsp;// found in first_warning column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;hidden&gt;0&lt;/hidden&gt; // depends on live column in nh_stage table (when live=1 is 0, when live=0 is 1)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;xcord&gt;947.3&lt;/xcord&gt; // x coordinates on diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ycord&gt;89.35&lt;/ycord&gt; // x coordinates on diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;width&gt;160&lt;/width&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;height&gt;100&lt;/height&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;strokeWidth&gt;2&lt;/strokeWidth&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;strokeColor&gt;#000000&lt;/strokeColor&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stageColor&gt;#FFFFFF&lt;/stageColor&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/node&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. All links - found in nh_stage_process, contained in &lt;links&gt; tag.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:<br />\r\n&lt;links&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;link id=\"3\" name=\"line3\" direction=\"down\" source=\"rectangle2\" target=\"rectangle4\" xCoords=\"1027.3,1027.4\" yCoords=\"131.35,254\" hidden=\"0\" archived=\"0\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/links&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Id number corresponds to id column in nh_stage_process (prefixed with service number if on demo database).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Source is a value in stage_from column and target is value in stage_to column, hence example link come from stage with id value of 2 to stage with id value of 4. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>x- and yCoords are values of start and end point on the diagram.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" - &nbsp;means is visible in the diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>archived=\"0\" - means value in live column in nh_stage_process is 1</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" archived=\"0\" - setup for live link between non-discharge stages ( where value in type column is ‘bak’, ‘fwd’ or ‘def’ but never when is ‘end’)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"1\" archived=\"0\" - for any discharge stages or any stage to/from discharge planning or refer on ( when value in type column is ‘end’ or ‘def’); it also can be a links from a stage that has been archived</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"1\" archived=\"1\" - for all archived links</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=\"0\" archived=\"1\" - this set up is incorrect and should never appear in the diagram</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. All discharge stages for each care pathway service are contained in &lt;discharge&gt; tag</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;discharge&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;node id=\"162\" hidden=\"0\" imported=\"1\" group_id=\"1\" link_id=\"\" disp=\"yes\"&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagecode&gt;DISP&lt;/stagecode&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;stagename&gt;Discharge &nbsp;Planning / Referrals&lt;/stagename&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;mds&gt;Not Known &nbsp;- 215&lt;/mds&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;level&gt;0&lt;/level&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;serviceid&gt;100&lt;/serviceid&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;servicecode&gt;IAPT0&lt;/servicecode&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/node&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;/discharge&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Similar to non-discharge stages, id can be found in id column in nh_stage table (prefixed with service number if on demo database). </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=”0” - means is live (ticked in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool”)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden=”1” - means is archived (unticked in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool”)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Group_id - corresponds to &nbsp;discharge_group_id column in nh_stage table</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Link_id - link id (value in id column in nh_stage_process table) that corresponds to link going into stage with id in that node (i.e. where target=”rectangle162” in xml or where stage_to column value is 162).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>disp: &nbsp;“yes” - means it is a “Discharge Planning Stage, “ref” - means it is “Refer On” stage, “no” - means it is standard discharge stage.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stagecode, stagename, level, serviceid, servicecode can be found the same as for non-discharge stages in point 1.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. &nbsp;Discharge Groups are contained in &lt;discharge&gt; tag after discharge nodes</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;group id=\"9\" groupcode=\"NSS\" groupname=\"Not Suitable for Service\" mds=\"Not suitable for service - 214\" xcord=\"41\" ycord=\"270\" hidden=\"0\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lt;group id=\"28\" groupcode=\"ATCC\" groupname=\"(Old) Assessment and Treatment Care Complete\" mds=\"Completed treatment - 210\" xcord=\"41\" ycord=\"840\" hidden=\"1\"/&gt;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>id - corresponds to &nbsp;id column in nh_stage_group and to group_id in discharge node in xml</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>groupname - corresponds to &nbsp;group_name column in nh_stage_group</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>mds - corresponds to &lt;mds&gt; in discharge node in xml</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>hidden - when the value is 0, group is live; when the value is 1, group has been archived, ‘(Old)’ is added to from of the group’s name, it appears grayed out in “Discharge Stages” in “New Care Pathway Tool” and all discharge nodes in xml that belong to this group have the hidden value set to 1.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Information which stages belong to which group can be found in link table nh_stage_togroup.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: in nh_diagram when value in autosave column is 1 it means it has NOT been autosaved.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: When archiving a stage, in diagram, set all links going into that stage to hidden=\"1\" archived=\"1\" (to disallow to move any patient into that stage) and change value in live column to 0 in nh_stage_process, and all links going out of that stage to hidden=\"1\" archived=\"0\" (to allow any patient that is currently in that stage to be move out from it). In nh_stage do NOT set value in live column to 0, unless you are 100% sure that you will not strand any patient in that stage).</strong></p>\r\n',NULL,35,'2016-09-20 15:57:31','2016-09-20 15:57:31');
