g it to yourself .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>VPN into the appropriate data-center and&nbsp;SSH to the appropriate server:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><code>iaptusvnode26</code> for &#39;a&#39; testing sites</li>\r\n	<li><code>iaptusvnode7</code> for &#39;b&#39; testing sites</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Change directories to the live build script in the source code folder:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-a4/build/live</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Switch branches to the branch you need to check out:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing switch-testing</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Insert GitHub read-only password twice found in Mayden KeePass.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run the command which deploys the branch you just checked out:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing deploy-local</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter the database username/password of the data set that is currently on the test site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to your testing site and ensure everything is up and running.</p>\r\n','test-sites-deploying',5,1,1,'2016-08-08 16:10:16','2016-08-11 15:06:16',NULL),(25,1,'Test Sites: Copying Databases (Same Datacenter)','Instructions for how to copy a live database to a test site','<ol>\r\n	<li>Find which data center the service is located on by looking at the <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">&#39;Services&#39;</a> page.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you allocate the testing site you are using to yourself in the &#39;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1HO9zfbEycSBxlsYeKikhzh3N8jBJrkwTljcG4kxx3FA/edit#gid=9\">Developer Portal&#39;</a></li>\r\n	<li>VPN into the relevant&nbsp;datacenter and&nbsp;SSH into the relevant&nbsp;server.</li>\r\n	<li>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL and double check with&nbsp;devOps that it is an appropriate size/time to copy it accross.</li>\r\n	<li>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the command which will copy the database you need to the test server:&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Follow the prompts from the script to complete the process:</li>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n	<li>Check test site you selected&nbsp;is up and running by logging in&nbsp;with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','test-sites-copying-databases-same-datacenter',6,1,1,'2016-08-08 16:15:40','2016-08-19 10:40:36',NULL),(26,4,'How To Sensu','An overview of how to create sensors and run them with Sensu.','<h3>First Things First</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Read the wikis for <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/sensor-manager/wiki\">sensor-manager</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/sensor-services/wiki\">sensor-services</a>. &nbsp;The sensor-manager allows you to run a sensor from the command line while the sensor-services repo contains interfaces and classes that must be implemented by your sensors. Also look at the sensu <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1O7G4-pjmZ2bSiuj1CJV_4O-wOtt80D5MMIW36-DONp8/\">document</a> for conventions relating to checks and metrics.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>How To Make A Sensor</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Go to the sensor repo of the product that you&rsquo;re writing a sensor for e.g <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/postroom-sensors\">postroom-sensors</a>. &nbsp;The <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/master/README.md\">readme</a> should give you instructions on how to create a sensor.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Here is an example of a <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/master/src/Sms/Metrics/SmsCount.php\">sensor</a> in iaptus-sensors.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You can write helpers to handle common functionality sensors might need like connecting to all <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/master/src/Databases/PdoConnectionIterator.php\">databases</a>.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Postroom &amp; iaptus Sensors</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new Metric or Check file for your sensor.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Take a look at existing sensors to see how they are written.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a query for your sensor using the $sensorQuery property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a .json config file in the same directory as your sensor (take a look at other .json config files for reference)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to give your sensor a name using the $sensorName property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Add your sensor to config/di-config.php file</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>How To Test</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Use TDD! Write tests as you go to make sure your sensor is behaving as you would expect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can also copy changes into the sensor-manager version of your sensor repo in the vendor directory and run the sensor from your console.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Running Sensu</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code>php SensorManager.php run Iaptus Users\\\\Metrics\\\\UniqueUserLoginsPerService</code></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Running Tests</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Run &lsquo;<code>composer test</code>&rsquo; from either the iaptus-sensors or postroom-sensors repo.</p>\r\n','how-to-sensu',2,1,1,'2016-08-09 09:35:47','2016-08-11 15:04:05',NULL),(27,21,'Basement CUPS LaserJet','Adding this networked printer to your personal printer configs','<h1>HP LaserJet 1 @ raspberry-cups-1</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>This printer is available on the Mayden Network, but not the guest network.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>If you have an Apple OS</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open <strong>System Preferences</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Click <strong>Printers and Scanners </strong></li>\r\n	<li>Click the <strong>&quot;+&quot;</strong> symbol at the bottom left of the left navigation pane</li>\r\n	<li>Select <strong>&quot;HP LaserJet 1 @ raspberry-cups-1 | Bonjour Shared&quot;</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Name the printer as you wish - the &quot;Location&quot; should say &quot;BASEMENT&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>Click <strong>&quot;Add&quot;</strong> on the bottom right on the pane</li>\r\n	<li>????</li>\r\n	<li>Profit</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>If you have a Windows OS</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Printers and devices\r\n<li>Add printer\r\n<li>Add network or bluetooth printer\r\n<li>pi@raspberry-cups-1 <strong>\"OR\"</strong> 10.10.2.201\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>If you have a *nix OS</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong> Follow printer installation instructions for your distribution</strong>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','basement-cups-laserjet',1,1,16,'2016-08-10 10:27:11','2016-08-10 13:21:44',NULL),(28,22,'How To: Signing CAE Certificates','Processes for signing CAE Certificates, adapted from the library article.','<h1><strong>The Process:</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>1. Process For Signing Certificates:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Normal Process:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n# Upload the CR to /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/client.csr\r\ncd /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/\r\n\r\n# Read &amp; review the certificate request (see misc information below). If any of the criteria are not met,\r\n# the certificate cannot be signed and the issue should be referred back to the support team to contact the client.\r\nopenssl req -noout -text -in request.csr\r\n\r\n# Generate a certificate\r\nopenssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in client.csr -out client.crt\r\n\r\n# Check the Certificate has worked\r\nopenssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt\r\n\r\n# Download the client.crt file to send to client\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Windows 2003 Server Process:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n#On ivnode14\r\ncd /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/\r\n# Make a PK\r\n# Choose a passphrase first, you will need to provide this to the client later - over the phone\r\nopenssl genrsa -des3 -out client.key 2048\r\n\r\n# Make a Certificate Request from the Key\r\n# Use the clients org name as the Common Name (CN) in the request\r\n# THIS MUST BE UNIQUE - if you use an existing CN the other certificate user will not longer be able to use their certificate.  It&#39;s also impossible to tell \r\n# if the CN is in use by another certificate...\r\nopenssl req -new -config ../../openssl.cnf -key client.key -out client.csr \r\n\r\n# Generate a Certificate from the Request\r\nopenssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in client.csr -out client.crt\r\n\r\n# Generate a combined Certificate and Private Key file - use the same passphrase as before\r\nopenssl pkcs12 -export -clcerts -in client.crt -inkey client.key -out client.p12\r\n\r\n# Check the combined file\r\nopenssl pkcs12 -info -in client.p12\r\n\r\n# Download the client.p12 file to send to client - do not send the passphrase electronically, provide it over the phone instead\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>If you see the error:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nSign the certificate? [y/n]:y\r\nfailed to update database\r\nTXT_DB error number 2&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Then there has been a collision in the CA index file. Find the X509 path in /var/www/ca/index.txt, and match using the &#39;Subject&#39; line (you will need to modify it) from the certificate request (the part sent in the Orbit ticket). It&#39;ll look like this:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nC=GB, ST=Wiltshire, O=Mayden, CN=MyClientSite/emailAddress=rob.andrews@mayden.co.uk&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>You&#39;ll need to reformat it to look like this:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n/C=GB/ST=Wiltshire/O=Mayden/CN=BSMHFT/emailAddress=Ananda.Situnayake@bsmhft.nhs.uk</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Find it in /var/www/ca/index.txt and remove the line. Once you have saved the file, re-run the &#39;openssl ca -cert...&#39; command and it should work happily.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>2. Sending The Client Files:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The client requires a number of files for their import process.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Certificate *.crt or Certificate + Key *.p12 file (dependent on which method above was used)</li>\r\n	<li>Our CA Certificate which they must trust as a Root CA</li>\r\n	<li>Windows Powershell script to automate download of the xml files to their local machine</li>\r\n	<li>MSSQL script to import content from XML files into MSSQL</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>These files are all put into a pre-defined ZIP file for the client to use.&nbsp; *.nhs.uk mail strips zip files so we upload them to https://welcome.iaptus.nhs.uk/CLIENT_NAME/mayden.zip&nbsp; We also remove the file once the client has completed the setup process.&nbsp; The path to this location is /var/www/html/iaptus-welcome/CLIENT_NAME/&nbsp;<strong>on iaptusvnode14</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A sample ZIP file has been attached to this page. &nbsp;We now keep the current export files in the iaptus codebase. They can be found in iaptus under docs/exports/ with each version having it&#39;s own folder. To create a new zip you need to zip everything inside the relevant version folder. However a number of key changes are required before sending to client.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The export.ps1 file needs the correct URL for the client adding into the $source variable at the top of the file</li>\r\n	<li>The client.crt or client.p12 file needs adding alongside the ca.crt file in the certs folder (often sent by support)</li>\r\n	<li>Version 4 on-wards - Update and remove any service specific exports (and associated comments) files from the bottom of &quot;export.ps1&quot; file</li>\r\n	<li>Version 4 on-wards -&nbsp;Update and remove any service specific&nbsp;exports (and associated comments)&nbsp;from the &quot;scripts/all.sql&quot; file</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>If the content of the exports changes, then the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts will all need regenerating to reflect the changes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>3. Updating The Clients Database:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>You also need to update the database with the common name from the certificate.&nbsp;Go to the live database and find nh_export_users.&nbsp; Add an entry with the service_id and certificate common name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The common name can be found by typing: cat client.crt&nbsp;&nbsp; from the command prompt when in the client&#39;s certificate folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><strong>Misc Information:</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Certificate Authority File:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Certificate Authority file can&nbsp;accessed via the cmd line on iaptusvnode14 in /var/www/ca</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Reviewing Certificate Request Files:</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>When reading and reviewing the certificate request file from the client, check the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>C=GB</li>\r\n	<li>L=Bath</li>\r\n	<li>S=Wiltshire</li>\r\n	<li>O=Mayden</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Common Names:</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>For a common name (CN) field to be considered suitable, it must contain the organisation name or some means of identifying&nbsp;the requesting client.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For a common name to be &quot;valid&quot;, it must be&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>unique</strong></span>. That is, it must <strong>not be used by any other signed certificate</strong>&nbsp;on our servers. There are a couple of ways of checking if common names are unique:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>In each services database, there is a table called nh_export_users, the third column in this table has the common names for all&nbsp;certificates associated with that service.</li>\r\n	<li>On ivnode14, go to /var/www/ca. There is a file called index.txt in this location that contains all of the certificates we currently have signed.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n','how-to-signing-cae-certificates',1,1,24,'2016-08-10 13:51:28','2016-08-10 13:54:40','2016-08-10 13:54:40'),(29,19,'Deploy To iaptusvnode7','At the moment we have to manually rsync files across from iaptusvndoe7 to node 32 and 33.','<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">\r\n<pre>\r\n<code>$ cd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/build/live\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl  --exclude &#39;backup/&#39; --exclude &#39;/build/&#39; --exclude &#39;.svn/&#39; --exclude &#39;.git/&#39; --exclude &#39;test/&#39; --exclude &#39;*.log&#39; --exclude &#39;logs/*&#39;  --verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ /var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl  --exclude &#39;backup/&#39; --exclude &#39;/build/&#39; --exclude &#39;.svn/&#39; --exclude &#39;.git/&#39; --exclude &#39;test/&#39; --exclude &#39;*.log&#39; --exclude &#39;logs/*&#39;  --verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ 192.168.63.32:/var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl  --exclude &#39;backup/&#39; --exclude &#39;/build/&#39; --exclude &#39;.svn/&#39; --exclude &#39;.git/&#39; --exclude &#39;test/&#39; --exclude &#39;*.log&#39; --exclude &#39;logs/*&#39;  --verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ 192.168.63.33:/var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ curl 127.0.0.1/clear-cache.php</code></pre>\r\n</div>\r\n','deploy-to-iaptusvnode7',4,1,6,'2016-08-11 11:25:22','2016-08-11 14:50:28','2016-08-11 14:50:28'),(30,1,'Test Sites: Copying Data (Bmth to Brck)','Instructions for how to copy a live database from Bournemouth to a test site on Bracknell','<h3 style=\"color:#aaa; font-style:italic\">Please make sure you read and understand all these commands before executing them. This is the safest way of getting a bournmoth site to bracknell. This can be done at any time of the day as providing you do everything right there is very minimal risk.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please replace the in the below commands with the details below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>SERVICE_DB_NAME</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Name of the DB you need to copy</li>\r\n    <li>e.g. IAPTus_IOW</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>DB_USER_NAME</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Your master DB user name</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>PORT</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>3306 for Set 4</li>\r\n    <li>3312 for Set 5</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<pre>\r\n$ ssh iaptusvnode26&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ cd ~/&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ mysqldump -u -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P --add-drop-table --skip-lock-tables --skip-add-locks --compress --skip-triggers --ignore-table=.nh_stats_history --ignore-table=.nh_stats --ignore-table=.nh_user_activity_view --ignore-table=.nh_user_activity_edit &gt; .sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ mysqldump -u -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &nbsp;--add-drop-table --compress --no-data nh_stats --no-data nh_stats_history --no-data nh_user_activity_view --no-data nh_user_activity_edit &gt;&gt; .sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ mysqldump IAPTus_Global -u -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &nbsp;--add-drop-table --skip-lock-tables --skip-add-locks --compress --skip-triggers --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_gp_bak --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_gp_import --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_practice_bak --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_practice_import &gt; IAPTus_Global.sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ mysql -u -p -h 10.0.2.54 -P 3306 &lt; .sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ mysql -u -p -h 10.0.2.54 -P 3306 &lt; IAPTus_Global.sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ rm .sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n\r\n$ rm IAPTus_Global.sql&lt;br /&gt;\r\n</pre>','test-sites-copying-data-bmth-to-brck',7,1,6,'2016-08-11 14:42:12','2016-09-13 15:43:51',NULL),(31,19,'Deploying To Bournemouth','Commands for manually deploying to the iaptus bournemouth cluster','<h2>Release Managers Only</h2>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p>When deploying to bournemouth there is currently an issue with re-syncing the code accross the cluster. This means that the deploy process actualy fails.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Untill the systems team fix the issue, the below commands will do what the automated script used to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n$ cd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/build/live\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl &nbsp;--exclude \'backup/\' --exclude \'/build/\' --exclude \'.svn/\' --exclude \'.git/\' --exclude \'test/\' --exclude \'*.log\' --exclude \'logs/*\' &nbsp;--verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ /var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl &nbsp;--exclude \'backup/\' --exclude \'/build/\' --exclude \'.svn/\' --exclude \'.git/\' --exclude \'test/\' --exclude \'*.log\' --exclude \'logs/*\' &nbsp;--verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ 192.168.63.32:/var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ rsync -rpKl &nbsp;--exclude \'backup/\' --exclude \'/build/\' --exclude \'.svn/\' --exclude \'.git/\' --exclude \'test/\' --exclude \'*.log\' --exclude \'logs/*\' &nbsp;--verbose --checksum --delete-after --ignore-errors --force --itemize-changes ../../ 192.168.63.33:/var/www/html/iaptus\r\n\r\n$ curl 127.0.0.1/clear-cache.php</pre>\r\n\r\n','deploying-to-bournemouth',4,1,6,'2016-08-11 15:24:39','2016-09-13 16:14:02',NULL),(32,23,'New Developer Setup','A few things to cover when getting a new starter set up in an iaptus team.','<h3>Get Set Up With the Core Mayden Tools:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/set-up-1password\">Set up 1Password</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-github\">Set up a GitHub account and SSH keys</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Set up your local Vagrant environment</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Set Up the Main Mayden Projects Locally:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/projects/iaptus\">iaptus</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Get Familiar With Jira and Bamboo</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Ask Jira admin to create Jira account</li>\r\n	<li>Explain the dashboard</li>\r\n	<li>Go to an issue (preferrably a well documented one!)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the different types of issues</li>\r\n		<li>Explain which issues branch off where</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the workflow diagram</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the different fields</li>\r\n		<li>Definition of Done</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Bamboo admin to create Bamboo account\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the difference between the different plans</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','new-developer-setup',2,1,24,'2016-08-18 10:57:22','2016-08-25 14:55:19',NULL),(33,25,'Test!','TestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTest','<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;Create new Service on Demo with Webtools&lt;/h2&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at &lt;a href=&quot;http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools&lt;/a&gt;. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &amp;#39;Create New Service&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;When the &amp;#39;Create New Service&amp;#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;The script requires you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;Code and script&lt;/h2&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by &lt;strong&gt;copying the settings of an existing &amp;#39;generic&amp;#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &amp;nbsp;(service name &amp;quot;generic&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;on the demo site).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Setupservice class&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). &lt;strong&gt;Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;Instructions for Running Locally&lt;/h2&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Configure the setup &amp;amp; database&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;There is a setup.php file at &lt;code&gt;tools/webtools/inc/setup.php&lt;/code&gt; that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at &lt;code&gt;/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Change permissions on the backups folder&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Go to &lt;code&gt;iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript&lt;/code&gt; and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;chmod 777 backups&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Change the &amp;#39;generic&amp;#39; service to copy from&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;$copy_ser_id = 101;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &amp;quot;&amp;quot;;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n','test',1,0,1,'2016-08-18 15:33:46','2016-08-18 15:38:17','2016-08-18 15:38:17'),(34,23,'Test!','test testtest testtest testtest testtest testtest testtest testtest testtest testtest test','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create new Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new 