is file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','test',3,0,1,'2016-08-18 15:36:45','2016-08-23 13:19:57','2016-08-23 13:19:57'),(35,18,'Test2','se. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of ','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create new Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at <a href=\"http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools</a>. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &#39;Create New Service&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the &#39;Create New Service&#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script requires you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Code and script</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by <strong>copying the settings of an existing &#39;generic&#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &nbsp;(service name &quot;generic&quot;&nbsp;on the demo site).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setupservice class</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). <strong>Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&nbsp;</strong>to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Instructions for Running Locally</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Configure the setup &amp; database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a setup.php file at <code>tools/webtools/inc/setup.php</code> that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','test2',3,0,1,'2016-08-18 15:38:53','2016-09-13 16:12:27','2016-09-13 16:12:27'),(36,6,'Adding a New Service to Demo','Information about the script on demo that creates a new service on the demo database given some basic details such as name of the new service. ','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create New Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at <a href=\"http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools</a>. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &#39;Create New Service&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the &#39;Create New Service&#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script allows you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Code and script</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by <strong>copying the settings of an existing &#39;generic&#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &nbsp;(service name &quot;generic&quot;&nbsp;on the demo site).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setupservice class</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). <strong>Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&nbsp;</strong>to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Instructions for Running Locally</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>Configure the setup &amp; database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a setup.php file at <code>tools/webtools/inc/setup.php</code> that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','adding-a-new-service-to-demo',2,1,30,'2016-08-18 15:42:44','2016-08-18 16:17:20',NULL),(37,19,'e connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now spli','e connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now spli','<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;Create new Service on Demo with Webtools&lt;/h2&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at &lt;a href=&quot;http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools&lt;/a&gt;. Once log