pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# create user</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnet-snmp-config --create-snmpv3-user -A SHA -a \'PASSWORD\' -x AES -X \'PASSWORD\' -ro maydensnmp</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Autostart SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nchkconfig snmpd on\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>#or centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl enable snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Backup snmpd.conf first</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncp /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf.ori</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# then append the config</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf</pre>\r\n\r\n\r\n<pre>rocommunity public5T88kl prtg.may:161\r\nrocommunity public5T88kl 127.0.0.1:161\r\nincludeAllDisks 10%\r\ndisk&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5%\r\nsyslocation Bat. C2\r\nsyscontact system@mayden.co.uk\r\nrouser maydensnmp priv</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Start SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nservice snmpd start\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p># centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl start snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Verify it works on localhost</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsnmpwalk -v 3 -l authPriv -a sha -A \'PASSWORD\' -x AES -X \'PASSWORD\' -u maydensnmp localhost | less</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# SNMP iptables rules (if required)</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\niptables -A INPUT -p udp -m udp -s 0/0 --dport 161:162 -j ACCEPT</pre>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Add device and sensors to PRTG</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>\'Add device\' at bottom of device view > select a group</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add name & DNS name (keep them the same if possible)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set sensor management to: Automatic device id (standard) > Continue</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leave it 5 minutes to scan the device, it will add a load of sensors, everything it can find, then trim them back to what you need.</p>\r\n','ups-monitoring',4,1,20,'2016-08-23 09:52:57','2016-09-13 16:13:16',NULL),(41,24,'Setting Up Vagrant','Instructions for how to set up vagrant on your local machine','<p>Vagrant is a software which facilitates the provisioning of virtual machines (VMs). Whilst the virtual machine itself runs on VirtualBox, the set up and configuration is overseen by Vagrant, which creates an environment for your code based off a configuration file named &#39;Vagrantfile&#39;. You can think of a virtual machine as an isolated&nbsp;computer and operating system&nbsp;running on your own laptop, but separate from your own operating system&#39;s setup and configuration. At Mayden we use our company vagrant boxes to run projects like iaptus locally, and they are supposed to mirror the set up on the actual Mayden servers as closely as possible (ahem). Most company vagrant boxes run on CentOS (Linux), as do the live servers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow these steps to get your Vagrant local environment set up:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Install VirtualBox</li>\r\n	<li>Install Vagrant</li>\r\n	<li>Download and Set Up the Mayden Vagrant Boxes</li>\r\n	<li>Start the Vagrant Box</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>1. Installing VirtualBox</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Download the latest version of VirtualBox from <a href=\"https://www.virtualbox.org/\">here</a> and install it. Phew that was super hard. Next step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Installing Vagrant</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Download the latest version of Vagrant <a href=\"https://www.vagrantup.com/downloads.html\">here</a> and install it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Downloading and Setting Up the Mayden Virtual Boxes</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Clone the <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/vagrant-vms\">vagrant-vms</a> repository from the Mayden GitHub account.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy the <code>vagrant-vms/iaptus/php56</code>&nbsp;folder into the location of your laptop drive where you want your GitHub repositories to be stored. When you come to clone the iaptus repository, it should be cloned inside this folder.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following this, run these commands to install the necessary dependencies:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant plugin install vagrant-vbguest</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code><tt>vagrant plugin install vagrant-hosts</tt></code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>4. Starting the Vagrant Box</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>To start your new vagrant box, navigate to it and run the up command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /directory/where/you/stored/the/box</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant up</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As this is the first time your box has been run, it will also provision it (run its&nbsp;setup and config scripts). This will not happen on subsequent &#39;up&#39; commands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have any issues getting the box up and running, please ask someone and document your solutions in the &#39;Troubleshooting&#39; section below if it seems like an issue more people may run into.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>5. SSH&#39;ing into the Vagrant Box</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>To SSH into your box and access it as a server, navigate to its directory and run the ssh&nbsp;command:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have any issues getting the box up and running, please ask someone and document your solutions in the &#39;Troubleshooting&#39; section below if it seems like an issue more people may run into.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>6. Extra Vagrant Commands</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant halt</code> - stops the vagrant box running</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant provision</code> - resets and reconfigures the box&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant reload&nbsp;</code>- halts and restarts the box</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant destroy</code> - halts and destroys the box so you will not be able to use it any more</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Never interrupt your vagrant box after you run the <code>vagrant&nbsp;up</code> command. This can cause Irritating and Unspecified Problems which will usually result in you having to destroy your vagrant box and set it up all over again. If &#39;destroying&#39; sounds dramatic to you, it is nothing compared to doing this whole process all over.&nbsp;Just don&#39;t do it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Troubleshooting:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Starting the box fails with &#39;<code>/sbin/mount.vboxsf: mounting failed with error: No such device</code>&#39;:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may need to update your box&#39;s package manager and then reload the vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>sudo yum update</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>exit</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant reload</code></p>\r\n','setting-up-vagrant',1,1,1,'2016-08-23 14:04:12','2016-08-24 13:10:33',NULL),(42,19,'Building Mayden PHP MySQL RPM','How tobuild the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus:','<p>This is how we build the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus, it uses a git repo from Rob Andrews.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><code>git clone https://github.com/borb/c6buildenv</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir -p ~/rpmbuild/{BUILD,RPMS,SOURCES,SPECS,SRPMS}</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum install -y https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-6.noarch.rpm http://rpms.remirepo.net/enterprise/remi-release-6.rpm<br />http://repo.mysql.com/yum/mysql-community/el/6/x86_64/mysql-community-release-el6-5.noarch.rpm</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum install -y figlet rpm-build redhat-rpm-config</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SPECS/php56.spec&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SOURCES/*&nbsp;&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SOURCES</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum-builddep&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS/php56.spec</code></p>\r\n','building-mayden-php-mysql-rpm',5,1,20,'2016-08-23 14:05:39','2016-08-23 14:08:13',NULL),(43,24,'Setting Up GitHub','How to get set up with GitHub so you can access the Mayden Repositories','<p>GitHub is service which Mayden uses to store and keep track of work done to the various projects (repositories) we work on, which uses Git version control. You can read more about Git version control and GitHub <a href=\"https://jahya.net/blog/git-vs-github/\">here</a>. To get set up with the system for work at Mayden, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create an Account on GitHub</li>\r\n	<li>Configure Your SSH Keys</li>\r\n	<li>Get&nbsp;Familiar with the Git Commands</li>\r\n	<li>Creating New Branches</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>1. Creating an Account on GitHub</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If you already have a GitHub&nbsp;account and you would also like to use this for work, you can do so. If not, create a personal account on GitHub <a href=\"https://github.com/join?source=header-home\">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have a username and are all signed up, ask a GitHub admin to add you to the Mayden developers group on the company GitHub.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Configuring Your SSH Keys</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to create a set of SSH keys for your laptop and add them to your GitHub account in order to be able to interact with the Mayden repositories. If you&#39;re not sure how, there are some really great instructions here:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-mac\">Mac</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/\">Windows</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-linux\">Linux</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Getting Familiar with the Git Commands</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Git has a number of terminal commands to help you read and write from a repository. You may wish to do some further reading on these, but <a href=\"https://www.git-tower.com/blog/git-cheat-sheet/\">here is a cheatsheet</a> of most of the commands. In particular, make sure you are familiar with:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>git clone</li>\r\n	<li>git add</li>\r\n	<li>git commit</li>\r\n	<li>git push</li>\r\n	<li>git pull</li>\r\n	<li>git fetch</li>\r\n	<li>git checkout</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>4. Creating New Branches</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All work should be done on a new git branch. This branch should be named according to this convention:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>[issue-type]/[jira-task-id]/[short-summary]</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>feature/jira-111/care-pathway-go-live-for-sunderland</code></p>\r\n','setting-up-github',2,1,1,'2016-08-23 14:24:49','2016-08-24 14:13:01',NULL),(44,24,'Setting Up 1Password','Instructions for how to set up 1Password ','<p>At Mayden we use 1Password to store both personal and company authentication details in a secure and easily accessible way. 1Password will give you access to both a personal vault and also&nbsp;a Mayden team vault, which will enable you access to login details for things like the Demo iaptus site, databases and company ecommerce accounts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow these steps to get set up:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Request a Mayden Team Vault Invite and Register</li>\r\n	<li>Download and Set Up 1Password Desktop App</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>1. Request a Mayden Team Vault Invite and Register</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Ask a member of the SysOps team to send you an email invite to the Mayden Vault. The current designated 1Password Guru is Matt E.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow the instructions in the email invite and follow the dialogs. This should guide you through registering with your name and generating a secret key and password. You do not need to store your secret key for the Mayden account&nbsp;as it can be reset by an administrator.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Downloading and Setting Up 1Password Desktop App</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Download and install the software for your operating system <a href=\"https://agilebits.com/downloads\">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the program and log in using the details you got from step 1, using &#39;mayden.1password.com&#39;&nbsp;as the sign-in address</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Maintain a distinction between your personal vaults and the Mayden vault or you&#39;ll end up sharing your private details with the whole company!</li>\r\n	<li>You may also want to download the <a href=\"https://agilebits.com/onepassword/extensions\">1Password browser plugin</a>, which can autofill website forms for you.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>If you want to import your Keepass store to 1Password, there are instructions for this <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/software-tools/1password-importing-keepass-vault\">here</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n','setting-up-1password',3,1,1,'2016-08-23 14:52:32','2016-08-25 14:47:21',NULL),(45,28,'Resize a Hard Disk for a Virtual Machine','Increasing disk space on a VirtualBox .vmdk','<p>Our Virtual Machines are provisioned using Vagrant from a Linux base box to run using VirutalBox. If the Hard Disk space runs out and you cannot remove files to free-up space, you can resize the Hard Disk using some VirtualBox and Linux commands.</p>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Some assumptions</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The following steps assume you&#39;ve got a set-up where:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>you use a Linux command-line terminal on your host machine</li>\r\n	<li>the vagrant boxes live at the path&nbsp;<code>provisioning/boxes/mybox</code></li>\r\n	<li>VirtualBox creates new Virtual Machines in the default location&nbsp;<code>~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>Steps to resize the hard disk</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Stop the virtual machine using Vagrant.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd provisioning/boxes/mybox\r\n# vagrant halt\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Locate the VirtuaBox VM and the HDD attached to its IDE Controller. In this instance we&#39;re assuming the VM is located in the default location and is named&nbsp;<code>mybox_default_1382400620</code>.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd ~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/mybox_default_1382400620\r\n# VBoxManage showvminfo mybox_default_1382400620 | grep &quot;.vmdk&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p>The&nbsp;<code>showvminfo</code>&nbsp;command should show you the location on the file-system of the HDD of type VMDK along with the name of the Controller it is attached to - it will look something like this:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code>IDE Controller (0, 0): \\VirtualBox VMs\\mybox_default_1382400620\\box-disk1.vmdk (UUID: 2f79610e-6c06-46d5-becb-448386ea40ec)\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>clone the VMDK type disk to a VDI type disk so it can be resized.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd ~/VirtualBox\\ VMs/mybox_default_1382400620\r\n# VBoxManage clonehd &quot;box-disk1.vmdk&quot; &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot; --format vdi\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>NOTE: We do this because VMDK type disks cannot be resized by VirtualBox. It has the added benefit of allowing us to keep our original disk backed-up during the resize operation.</em></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out how big the disk is currently, to determine how large to make it when resized. The information will show the current size and the Format variant. If Dynamic Allocation was used to create the disk, the Format variant will be &quot;dynamic default&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage showhdinfo &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Resize the cloned disk to give it more space. The size argument below is given in Megabytes (1024 Bytes = 1 Megabyte). Because this disk was created using&nbsp;<em>dynamic allocation</em>&nbsp;I&#39;m going to resize it to 100 Gigabytes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage modifyhd &quot;clone-disk1.vdi&quot; --resize 102400\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>NOTE: If the disk was created using</em>&nbsp;dynamic allocation&nbsp;<em>(see previous step) then the</em>&nbsp;physical size&nbsp;<em>of the disk will not need to match its</em>&nbsp;logical size&nbsp;<em>- meaning you can create a very large logical disk that will increase in physical size only as space is used.</em></p>\r\n\r\n	<p><em>TIP: To&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.conversion-metric.org/filesize/gigabytes-to-megabytes\">convert a Gigabyte value into Megabytes</a>&nbsp;use an online calculator.</em></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out the name of the Storage Controller to attach the newly resized disk to.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage showvminfo mybox_default_1382400620 | grep &quot;Storage&quot;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Attach the newly resized disk to the Storage Controller of the Virtual Machine. In our case we&#39;re going to use the same name for the Storage Controller,&nbsp;<code>IDE Controller</code>, as revealed in the step above.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># VBoxManage storageattach mybox_default_1382400620 --storagectl &quot;IDE Controller&quot; --port 0 --device 0 --type hdd --medium clone-disk1.vdi\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Reboot the Virtual Machine using Vagrant.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># cd provisioning/boxes/mybox\r\n# vagrant up\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Open a command-line shell as root on the Virtual Machine via ssh.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vagrant ssh\r\n# sudo bash\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find the name of the logical volume mapping the file-system is on (ie.&nbsp;<code>/dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># df \r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find the name of the physical volume (or device) that all the partitions are created on (ie.&nbsp;<code>/dev/sda</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># fdisk -l\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new primary partition for use as a Linux LVM</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># fdisk /dev/sda\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>p</code>&nbsp;to print the partition table to identify the number of partitions. By default there are two -&nbsp;<code>sda1</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>sda2</code>.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>n</code>&nbsp;to create a new primary partition.&nbsp;</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>p</code>&nbsp;for primary.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>3</code>&nbsp;for the partition number, depending the output of the partition table print.</li>\r\n		<li>Press Enter two times to accept the default First and Last cylinder.</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>t</code>&nbsp;to change the system&#39;s partition ID</li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>3</code>&nbsp;to select the newly creation partition</li>\r\n		<li>Type&nbsp;<code>8e</code>&nbsp;to change the Hex Code of the partition for&nbsp;<code>Linux LVM</code></li>\r\n		<li>Press&nbsp;<code>w</code>&nbsp;to write the changes to the partition table.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Reboot the machine, then ssh back in when it is up again and switch to the root user once more.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># reboot\r\n# vagrant ssh\r\n# sudo su -\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new physical volume using the new primary partition just created.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># pvcreate /dev/sda3\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Find out the name of the Volume Group that the Logical Volume mapping belongs to (ie.&nbsp;<code>VolGroupOS</code>).</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vgdisplay\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Extend the Volume Group to use the newly created physical volume.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># vgextend VolGroupOS /dev/sda3\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Extend the logical volume to use more of the Volume Group size now available to it. You can either tell it to add a set amount of space in Megabytes, Gigabytes or Terabytes, and control the growth of the Disk:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># lvextend -L+20G /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n	<p>Or if you want to use all the free space now available to the Volume Group:</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Resize the file-system to use up the space made available in the Logical Volume&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># resize2fs /dev/mapper/VolGroupOS-lv_root\r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Verfiy that there is now more space available</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># df -h \r\n</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>A restart of the VM using vagrant may be a good idea here, to ensure that all services are running correctly now that there is more space available. Exit the root user, exit the vagrant user and ssh session, then tell vagrant to restart the machine.</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n<code># exit\r\n# exit\r\n# vagrant reload</code></pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>* Whole guide taken from Christopher Hoppers guide found here:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://gist.github.com/christopher-hopper/9755310\">https://gist.github.com/christopher-hopper/9755310</a>&nbsp;*</p>\r\n','resize-a-hard-disk-for-a-virtual-machine',1,1,19,'2016-08-24 11:58:02','2016-08-24 12:10:27',NULL),(46,16,'Testing New Self Referral Forms','The process for testing a Self Referral Form prior to go-live that is completely new.','<h1>You Need:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>An internet connection.</li>\r\n	<li>The specification documents (Design Elements and Form Fields) from Fi</li>\r\n	<li>Live Access for the steps in <strong>bold</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Some way of noting down issues&nbsp;that should be relayed back to Fi<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Steps:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Go to the form URL.\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If this has not been provided on the task, the URL is&nbsp;https://test-gateway.mayden.co.uk/referral-v2/{UUID} where UUID can be found in the form_configs table of the test Paywall database for each form</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check the following against the specification document:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>That the fields appear in the correct order</li>\r\n		<li>That&nbsp;the field types for each field are correct (e.g. radio, select, text box)</li>\r\n		<li>That the Notes / Informational Texts on the form match</li>\r\n		<li>That&nbsp;the visuals are correct - e.g. look for dodgy CSS / misplaced or badly sized logos, etc</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Check form element list IDs&nbsp;against database list IDs for this service</strong>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><strong>​</strong>For a lot of the fields that are selects, radios or checkboxes, the values may link directly to the list IDs used in the services iaptus</li>\r\n		<li>For these elements, check that each front-end option (where the list ID is a list ID)&nbsp;relates to a realistic list ID in iaptus</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check that the right fields are &quot;required&quot;:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If a field is required, it shouldn&#39;t allow you to submit the form without it</li>\r\n		<li>If it&#39;s not required, then it should be ignored if empty</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is &quot;conditionally required&quot; (see below), then it should not be required by default</li>\r\n		<li>When you hit &quot;submit&quot;, if a required field isn&#39;t filled in, the form should flag it up in a pop up. To test requiredness of all fields, you can fill in one field at a time, hitting submit after each to check that the next required field that is empty gets flagged up.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check front end validation\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><span class=\"marker\"><em>Every</em></span> field should have &quot;SafeCharacters&quot; validation at minimum, that is, it should reject the following characters\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>#</li>\r\n			<li>-- (double hyphen)</li>\r\n			<li>&lt;</li>\r\n			<li>&gt;</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is a date field, it should only accept a date in the format&nbsp;dd/mm/yyyy</li>\r\n		<li>Conditional requirement, in the spec there will be a number of fields that are &quot;required if field X is filled in&quot;, &quot;either X or Y must be filled in&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;required if field X = Yes&quot;. Check that these fields are required&nbsp;<em>only&nbsp;</em>when the conditions are met.</li>\r\n		<li>Phone numbers should only be accepted if they contain 11 digits and if a mobile, must start with &quot;07&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Other special validation requirements will be on the specification.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>End To End Test</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Set up an iaptus test site and postroom, as detailed <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/iaptus/self-referrals/configuring-test-sites-for-self-referral-testing\">here</a></li>\r\n		<li>Fill in the form on the<strong>&nbsp;<em>test paywall site</em></strong>&nbsp;and submit it (<strong>TAKE A SCREENSHOT OF WHAT YOU SUBMIT BEFORE YOU PUSH THE BUTTON)</strong></li>\r\n		<li>Log into the test iaptus and accept the new referral by creating a patient from it</li>\r\n		<li>Go to the Referral Data page and check that all the details showing match the data you submitted (and hopefully screenshotted)</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Cheer/have a drink</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','testing-new-self-referral-forms',2,1,24,'2016-08-24 13:07:03','2016-08-24 15:23:28',NULL),(47,16,'Testing Changes to Self Referral Forms','A slightly shorter test plan for use only when testing updates to an existing form.','<p><var><span class=\"marker\">NOTE: This test plan may *ONLY* be used when testing updates to an existing form that has been approved as a suitable base with which to compare changes. Speak to FD if you&#39;re not sure whether its use is appropriate.&nbsp;</span></var></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>You Will Need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to bpvnode13 (Paywall/Bacpac&nbsp;Testing) and bpvnode14 (Paywall Live)</li>\r\n	<li>Access to the databases on the aforementioned servers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;base&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table (`spec` column)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>This will, in most cases, be from the&nbsp;<strong>LIVE</strong>&nbsp;Paywall Database.</li>\r\n		<li>However, if you&#39;re updating a form that has not yet gone live, then someone should have taken a backup copy as a base from the testing database&nbsp;before updates were made&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;updated&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table of the Paywall Test database</li>\r\n	<li>Run both JSONs through the&nbsp;<strong>same&nbsp;</strong>JSON prettyfier, so that you get two lots of data that have the same formatting</li>\r\n	<li>Perform a file diff between the two files, to see what changes have been made\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If there&#39;s a lot of fields changed that you weren&#39;t expecting or can&#39;t sufficently explain,&nbsp;refer this back to FD and discuss whether a full test may be more appropriate</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>For each element changed, check that the element still works as you would expect it to against the spec by using the updated version of the form:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Check that the right fields are &quot;required&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Check element ordering on the form</li>\r\n		<li>Check the fields labels and types:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In the case of select/radio, check the option values&nbsp;and their order (including the back-end &quot;submitted&quot; value) are the same as the old version</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check validation:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>No field on the form should accept -- (double hyphen), #, &lt; or &gt; due to SQL injection concerns.</li>\r\n			<li>If the specification mentions special validation rules, check those too</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check dependencies\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In a case where the field can be required as a result of another field being filled in, or having a certain value, make sure this link still works</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Perform an End to End test as described <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/iaptus/self-referrals/testing-new-self-referral-forms\">here</a></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Notes:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Especially on the older forms, it is likely that &quot;priority&quot; of fields may change, this is&nbsp;<strong>fine</strong>, provided the rule below still holds.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements on the form may have the same priority, if this has happened, there&#39;s a bug with the form builder and this needs to be raised ASAP.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements may have the same &quot;name&quot;, otherwise data in the second element will overwrite that in the first.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','testing-changes-to-self-referral-forms',3,1,24,'2016-08-24 14:33:58','2016-08-24 15:28:39',NULL),(48,29,'Manually Removing Care Pathway Links','How to remove a link from a care pathway so it no longer appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually remove links from care pathways. This must be done on the Demo site and the link itself must <strong>not&nbsp;</strong>be deleted - only archived/\'olded\'.&nbsp;To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs deleting. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be removed, making note of the ID for the \'from\' stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the \'to\' stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, use these IDs to find the link in the nh_stage_process table and change the live column from <code>1</code> to <code>0</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>UPDATE nh_stage_process SET live=0 WHERE stage_from=STAGE_FROM_ID AND stage_to=STAGE_TO_ID;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to set the link in the XML to archived too. You can find the XML in the&nbsp;nh_diagram table. Open the XML in a text editor and locate&nbsp;the link which needs archiving. You will be able to find it by removing the service id and \'00\' from the beginning of the STAGE_FROM&nbsp;ID and&nbsp;STAGE_TO_ID and looking for the link with a source and target with this number in it. For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>SERVICE_ID = 160</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>STAGE_FROM_ID = 1600022</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>STAGE_TO_ID = 1600044</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To archive the link, simply replace the <code>hidden=&quot;0&quot; archived=&quot;0&quot;</code> part with&nbsp;<code>hidden=&quot;1&quot; archived=&quot;1&quot;:</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to check that it is no longer possible travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus. When you have a patient in the \'stage from\' stage, it should not be possible to process the patient onto the \'to stage\' as you removed the link.</p>\r\n','manually-removing-care-pathway-links',4,1,1,'2016-08-24 14:36:33','2016-09-21 13:28:48',NULL),(49,29,'Manually Adding Care Pathway Links','How to add a link from a care pathway so it appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually add links to care pathways. This must be done on the Demo. To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs adding. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be added, making note of the ID for the \'from\' stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the \'to\' stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also need to find your next LINK_ID -&nbsp;this should be the next autoincrement value in the nh_stage_process table, e.g. if the highest existing id is 2000, your link ID will be 2001&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, you need to write the XML for your new link:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&amp;lt;link id=&amp;quot;LINK_ID&amp;quot; name=&amp;quot;lineLINK_ID&amp;quot; direction=&amp;quot;down&amp;quot; source=&amp;quot;rectangleSTAGE_FROM_ID&amp;quot; target=&amp;quot;rectangleSTAGE_TO_ID&amp;quot; xCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; yCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; hidden=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; archived=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot;/&amp;gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&amp;lt;link id=&amp;quot;200&amp;quot; name=&amp;quot;line200&amp;quot; direction=&amp;quot;down&amp;quot; source=&amp;quot;rectangle22&amp;quot; target=&amp;quot;rectangle44&amp;quot; xCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; yCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; hidden=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; archived=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot;/&amp;gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These links then need to be added to the XML file for this service in the latest non-auto-saved nh_diagram row. It should be appended to the section with the other links in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This adds the links to the care pathway diagram tool. To carry these changes over to the iaptus care pathway section, you should&nbsp;export the SQL from the Mayden Care Pathway Tool (as you would when putting a care pathway live) and run the resulting SQL on demo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to check that it is now possible to travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus using your link. When you have a patient in the \'stage from\' stage, it should now&nbsp;be possible to process the patient onto the \'to stage\' as you removed the link.</p>\r\n','manually-adding-care-pathway-links',5,1,1,'2016-08-24 15:08:20','2016-09-14 09:41:42',NULL),(50,26,'iaptus','How to get a local version of iaptus running and work with it','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What is iaptus?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus is the core product here at Mayden and assumes the majority of all development time. It is a patient management system for mental health services and, among other things, allows services to track and report on&nbsp;patient care, accept referrals from patients and refer them on to othert mental health care providers, and communicate with patients via letters and SMSs. If you&#39;re new to iaptus, you will probably have some dedicated iaptus training which will inform you more fully on the capabilities of the iaptus system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;For the First Time</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>These instructions assume that you have a working vagrant VM in which to run iaptus. If you do not, follow the instructions layed out in the <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Setting Up Vagrant</a> article before continuing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step to setting iaptus up locally is cloning the iaptus repository inside an <code>html</code>&nbsp;directory inside&nbsp;your PHP 5.6 vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /path/to/your/php56/vagrant/box</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir html</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>git clone&nbsp;git@github.com:may-den/iaptus.git</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the dependencies have finished installing, you need to SSH into your vagrant box and run the iaptus&nbsp;build scripts:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to select a &#39;build and create&#39; type, select whichever option you prefer. &#39;1&#39; will suffix database names with whichever git branch you are on, &#39;2&#39; won&#39;t&nbsp;so each time iaptus is built, your local databases will be dropped and rebuilt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to continue connecting with the given RSA fingerprint, enter &#39;yes&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also be asked for a GitHub Token. You will find this in the Mayden 1Password vault and it should be pasted into the terminal now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the build script finishes, you should be able to go to&nbsp;<code><a href=\"http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php\">http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php</a></code> in your browser and access the aptus login page. You can use the username &#39;superuser&#39; and password &#39;biddestone4211&#39; to log in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;After Checking Out&nbsp;a New Branch</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each time you checkout a different branch of the iaptus repository, iaptus will need to be rebuilt:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessing Your Local Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to download a database tool such as SequelPro, Heidi or MySQL Workbench. On a PHP 5.6 box, you should be able to access your database using the following credentials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Host:&nbsp;192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Username: root</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What To Do Next</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol><br />\r\n	<li>Explore the codebase and ask someone to explain the key parts of the iaptus repository to you</li>\r\n	<li>Log into your local database and ask someone to explain the key tables to you</li>\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;\r\n</ol>\r\n','iaptus',1,1,1,'2016-08-24 15:50:09','2016-08-24 15:52:40',NULL),(51,30,'1Password: Importing Keepass Vault','How to import the credentials in your Keepass into a 1Password vault','<p>If you have credentials stored in your Keepass software, this can be exported and then imported into 1Password. You will need access to your Keepass vault, the&nbsp;1Password software and a personal 1Password Vault. If you need help setting up the 1Password software you can reference <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-1password\">this page</a>. To import your Keepass credentials, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export your Keepass vault as XML</li>\r\n	<li>Convert your Keepass XML file to a 1Password compatible file&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Import your 1Password compatible file to 1Password</li>\r\n	<li>Super destroy your Keepass XML and 1Password compatible files</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>1. Exporting Your Keepass Vault as XML</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Open Keepass and begin the export process by clicking on File &gt; Export. Then click the &#39;Keepass XML (2.x)&#39; option, select an &#39;Export to&#39; directory and click &#39;Ok&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Converting Your Keepass XML File to a 1Password Compatible File</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You can use Mayden&#39;s handy Keepass conversion tool to convert your Keepass XML file. To do this, go to <a href=\"http://cloud4.may:8011/\">the conversion tool</a> and use it to upload the XML file you exported from Keepass. On hitting the &#39;Upload XML File&#39; button, a download should begin. This is your 1Password compatible file.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Importing Your 1Password Compatible File into 1Password</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Mac:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Open the 1Password software</li>\r\n		<li>Click File &gt; Import...</li>\r\n		<li>Make sure &#39;Other&#39; is select under &#39;Where is your data coming from&#39;, and click &#39;Import a 1PIF file&#39;</li>\r\n		<li>Select your destination vault (that you want to import your credentials into) and select the file you want to import</li>\r\n		<li>Follow the dialog to finish the import process</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Windows:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Open the 1Password software</li>\r\n		<li>Click the gear icon in the top left of the 1Password window</li>\r\n		<li>Click &#39;Import&#39;</li>\r\n		<li>Select your destination vault (that you want to import your credentials into) and select the file you want to import</li>\r\n		<li>Follow the dialog to finish the import process</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>​</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Linux:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Puzzle through it on your own and document it here</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>4.&nbsp;Super Destroy Your Keepass XML and 1Password Compatible Files</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have ascertained that your passwords have been imported successfully, obliterate your Keepass XML file and 1Password compatible file&nbsp;as they contain super secret things and leaving them lying around completely defeats the point of having a password manager. The end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','1password-importing-keepass-vault',5,1,1,'2016-08-25 13:20:39','2016-08-25 14:17:25',NULL),(52,31,'Set up Local Development Environment','how to get a local copy of the bacpac application with a virtual machine and get everything working','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Access to the Mayden Github bacpac repository and appropriate SSH keys installed</li>\r\n    <li>Vagrant software installed on your laptop</li>\r\n    <li>Copy of the Mayden <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/vagrant-vms\" target=\"_blank\">vagrant-vms</a> repository from GitHub</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Create a folder in an appropriate place on your computer called \'bacpac\' and move into that directory</li>\r\n    <li>Create a folder within the bacpac folder called html and move into that directory</li>\r\n    <li>Do <code>git clone&nbsp;ssh://sls@slsapp.com:1234/mayden/bacpac.git</code> in the html directory </li>\r\n    <li>Go to up to date copy of the Mayden vagrant-vms repository and get a copy of the Vagrantfile from the bacpac directory in that repository. Copy the vagrantfile into the bacpac directory created at step 1. above.</li>\r\n    <li>Edit the Vagrantfile from step 3. as follows: <code>config.vm.network &quot;private_network&quot;, ip: &quot;192.168.20.31&quot;</code></li>\r\n    <li>Use the <code>vagrant up</code> command to start the vagrant box from inside the top level bacpac directory created at step 1.</li>\r\n    <li>When the machine is up and ready (you will need to enter your password to permit the file syncing with the Vagrant box) go to the bacpac code folder (<em>still in your host machine</em>) and do composer install<br />\r\n    <code>cd html/bacpac;</code><br />\r\n    <code>chmod +x composer.phar;&nbsp;./composer.phar install;</code><br />\r\n    <code>cd -</code></li></code><br />\r\n    <li>Use the <code>vagrant ssh</code> command to start a shell session to the vagrant box</li>\r\n    <li>From within the vagrant box go to /var/www/html/bacpac/build directory and create a new file <code>build.properties</code> at the same level as the build.properties.example file. Copy the contents from the section below (build.properties) into the new build.properties file. </li>\r\n    <li>From within the build folder in the vagrant box run <code>ant rebuild</code></li>\r\n    <li>Still in the vagrant box go to /etc/httpd/conf.d and edit the bacpac.conf file so that the DocumentRoot is <code>/var/www/html/bacpac/public</code> and change the Directory path two lines below to match</li>\r\n    <li>Restart the apache server for the changes in step 11 to take effect.</li>\r\n    <li>Update /etc/hosts file on your local machine - add following: \r\n    <ul><li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>\r\n192.168.20.31 bacpac.dev\r\n192.168.20.31 bacpac.test\r\n192.168.20.31 paywall.dev\r\n192.168.20.31 paywall.test</pre></li></ul>\r\n    You should now be able to go to  the URL bacpac.dev in a browser on your host machine and see the bacpac login page.</li>\r\n    <li>Login details:<br />\r\n    email: chris.eldridge@mayden.co.uk,<br />\r\n    password: well known password</li>\r\n    <li>To connect to the bacpac databases running in the vagrant box (for example with Sequel Pro) on your host machine use host: 127.0.0.1  <strong>port: 4040</strong>  username: root  password: vagrant</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>build.properties</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><pre>db.username=root&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.ip=127.0.0.1&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.host=localhost&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.password=vagrant&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.database=bacp_trunk&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.test_database=bacp_trunk_test&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.app.username=root&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndb.app.password=vagrant&lt;br /&gt;\r\nowner=rick&lt;br /&gt;\r\ngroup=wheel&lt;br /&gt;\r\nbuild.dir=.&lt;br /&gt;\r\nroot.dir=/var/www/html/bacpac&lt;br /&gt;\r\nbase.url=&lt;br /&gt;\r\nemail.bacp.support.username=noreply.bacpac@mayden.co.uk&lt;br /&gt;\r\nemail.bacp.support.password=MyP2NdzzGRsZe7tHPedR&lt;br /&gt;\r\nfunctionaltest_url=http://bacpac.test&lt;br /&gt;\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://jenkins.may:4444/wd/hub&lt;br /&gt;\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://10.1.16.28:4444/wd/hub&lt;br /&gt;\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://192.168.20.1:4444/wd/hub&lt;br /&gt;\r\nfunctionaltest_hub_url=http://10.0.2.2:4444/wd/hub&lt;br /&gt;\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://rick.hewes@dWxKNVWWd6F1GShQXbKm@hub.browserstack.com/wd/hub&lt;br /&gt;\r\nselenium.host=bacpac.test&lt;br /&gt;\r\nenvironment=development&lt;br /&gt;\r\nradius.ip=10.1.16.208&lt;br /&gt;\r\nradius.api_key=sdfdfgRJnKyd6abQsdfsdfsdfsdfZf4BhF3Dqu06hhAZxJsdf&lt;br /&gt;\r\nbacp.api_username = MaydenBacPac&lt;br /&gt;\r\nbacp.api_password = ja9REbRu&lt;br /&gt;\r\nrecurly.url=https://mayden-test.recurly.com&lt;br /&gt;\r\nrecurly.api_key=4c969b92f7604533989f79a6dfa4bb3b&lt;br /&gt;\r\nmonitor.url=http://external.may/bacpac_mon/portal.php&lt;br /&gt;\r\nadmin.delete_key=rick&lt;br /&gt;\r\n#gpdata.url=http://localhost/Pathways/paywall/public/gpdata&lt;br /&gt;\r\ngpdata.url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk/gpdata&lt;br /&gt;\r\ngpdata.api_key=tyuibghjkbyt7uy7804688nkhu579y78y7606708y7ubyhuyu2&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndoctrine.generate.proxies=Doctrine\\\\Common\\\\Proxy\\\\AbstractProxyFactory::AUTOGENERATE_ALWAYS&lt;br /&gt;\r\npaywall.url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk&lt;br /&gt;\r\nmayselfreferral.paywall_self_referral_api_key=a439bb7e-d4dc-47d3-8ff4-208a8c275a2f&lt;br /&gt;\r\nmayselfreferral.paywall_self_referral_url=localhost/Pathways/paywall/referral-api&lt;br /&gt;\r\nmayselfreferral.referral_form_base_url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk/referral/</pre></p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n','set-up-local-development-environment',1,1,30,'2016-08-25 15:11:14','2016-09-13 16:20:44',NULL),(53,17,'Core Iaptus Databases','Information on the core databases for the iaptus application ','<h3>Core iaptus databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The iaptus application uses 3 core databases:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><code>iaptus</code> database&nbsp;-&nbsp;for which there is normally one database per iaptus service containing data for that service</li>\r\n	<li><code>global</code>&nbsp;database&nbsp;-&nbsp;where there is one per live server/server&nbsp;cluster&nbsp;which contains data that is common for all iaptus clients (e.g. definitions of reports or tags used in iaptus). All global databases need to be kept in sync.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><code>shared</code> database -<strong>&nbsp;</strong>a single database instance containing common data that could potentially&nbsp;be used by other mayden applications&nbsp;(e.g. national gp practice data, national healthcare provider data). The shared database for live sites is located in the Bracknell datacentre.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>* See multi-service databases below however</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Multi-Service Databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There are however some cases where you find multiple services sharing a single iaptus database:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Demo - all iaptus services start off with a demo site so the<strong> demo iaptus database contains all the iaptus services</strong> <strong>ever created,</strong> and is also the source of the iaptus service id numbers&nbsp;(auto-increment on nh_service demo database table). &nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Local Development - on our local development environment the database contains several services so we can easily test code in a multi-service scenario and also log-in as different services with different sets of test data.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Live Sites - there are a few instances where two or even three related clients have been set up on a single live site database. This is not being done going forward and some have since been separated out, but at the time of writing there is at least one live site iaptus database that contains three separate services.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Demo Database Missing Global Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A further anomaly worth noting is that for historical reasons the iaptus demo site has no separate global database - instead the tables from the iaptus database and the iaptus global database are mixed together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','core-iaptus-databases',1,1,30,'2016-08-25 15:19:18','2016-08-25 15:32:17',NULL),(54,17,'Putting a New Demo Service Live','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Run&nbsp;the Copy&nbsp;Demo to Live Script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server&nbsp;as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.&nbsp;However export nh_stats, nh_stats_history, nh_stats_speed, nh_diagram, nh_stage_xml,&nbsp;nh_user_activity_edit and&nbsp;nh_user_activity_view as empty tables, otherwise you will be copying alot of data.</li>\r\n	<li>Rename local copy demo database to \"<code>iaptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new empty local database called&nbsp; \"<code>iaptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database&nbsp;details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;file at&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code>&nbsp;by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n	<li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n	<li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or&nbsp;CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Adding a Documents Folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>FTP into the relevant&nbsp;server and navigate to the <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/documents </code>directory</li>\r\n	<li>Create a new directory called \'documentService\' followed by the service id, eg. documentService200</li>\r\n	<li>Create two directories inside this new directory named <code>letters </code>and <code>exports</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Add Service to Config File</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the server and navigate to <code>/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/html/inc/config</code>&nbsp;for Bournemouth, or&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/html/inc/config</code> for Bracknell</li>\r\n	<li>Edit serviceconfig.php and add a new array with the new service details in it, where the key is the name of the service\'s includes folder</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Run the Global Patches</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the server and navigate to <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the <code>\'php patches.php\'</code> command and when prompted, choose the global database to run patches for</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Deploy the Code</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the server and navigate to the <code>/var/www/iaptus/build/live</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the \'phing deploy-local\' command</li>\r\n	<li>Run the \'phing deploy-cluster\' command</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Clear The Server Cache</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Run the <code>curl 127.0.0.1/clear-cache.php</code> command</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Copy Any Letters from Their Demo Documents</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the demo server and navigate to <code>/var/www/html/iaptus_live/documents/documentServiceSERVICE_ID_HERE</code></li>\r\n	<li>Copy all of the JPEGS from this directory and upload them to the service\'s documents/letters&nbsp;directory</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Transfer Over the Service\'s Demo User Accounts</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the server and navigate to <code>/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the <code>php passtool.php</code> command</li>\r\n	<li>When prompted, enter \'C\' for the action and follow the prompts\r\n	<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Delete Dummy Account Users</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remove dummy/testing users from the service\'s nh_user table</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc\');\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc\');\r\ndefine(\'SCORING_CLASS_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/\');\r\ndefine(\'MYSQL_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/\');\r\ndefine(\'IAPTUS_PATH\', \'/iaptus/trunk/html\');\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;amp;$DBObject)\r\n{\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;if (PEAR::isError($DBObject)) {\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;$trace=debug_backtrace();\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;$report=str_replace(\'/var/www/html/\', \'\', $trace[0][\'file\']).\' Line: \'.$trace[0][\'line\'].\' Msg: \'.$DBObject---&amp;gt;getDebugInfo();\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;error_log(\'MySQL Error: \'.$report);\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;die(\'An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files\');\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;}\r\n}</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>db_data.inc:</h3>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n$hostname &amp;nbsp;= &quot;192.168.20.56&quot;;\r\n$username &amp;nbsp;= &quot;root&quot;;\r\n$password &amp;nbsp;= &quot;&quot;;\r\n$database &amp;nbsp; = &quot;iaptus_demo_bak&quot;;\r\n\r\n$dbDemoBak = DB::connect(&quot;mysql://$username:$password@$hostname/$database&quot;);\r\nif(DB::isError($dbDemoBak))\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; die($dbDemoBak-&amp;gt;getMessage());\r\n$dbDemoBak-&amp;gt;setFetchMode (DB_FETCHMODE_ASSOC);\r\n\r\n$hostname &amp;nbsp;= &quot;192.168.20.56&quot;;\r\n$username &amp;nbsp;= &quot;root&quot;;\r\n$password &amp;nbsp;= &quot;&quot;;\r\n$database &amp;nbsp; = &quot;iaptus_new_client&amp;quot;;\r\n\r\n$dbNewClient = DB::connect(&quot;mysql://$username:$password@$hostname/$database&quot;);\r\nif(DB::isError($dbNewClient))\r\ndie($dbNewClient-&amp;gt;getMessage());\r\n$dbNewClient-&amp;gt;setFetchMode (DB_FETCHMODE_ASSOC);\r\n</pre>\r\n','putting-a-new-demo-service-live',2,1,30,'2016-08-25 16:41:03','2016-09-21 15:25:12',NULL),(55,29,'Adding a Step to a Care Pathway','How to add a step to a care pathway','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Access to demo</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To add a step which exists on demo to a service\'s care pathway, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Locate the step you want to add for a service in the IAPTus_Demo.nh_pathway_service table. You will need to copy this row and insert it into the nh_pathway_service table in the service\'s database:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>INSERT INTO `nh_pathway_service` (`pathway_service_id`, `code`, `title`, `step`, `prefix`)&nbsp;VALUES&nbsp;(data, from, the , demo, database);</pre></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Find the latest non-auto-saved care pathway in IAPTus_Demo.nh_diagram and grab the XML from it.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the id of step from <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>to the list of comma separated values in the \'carepathway service\' tag</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the all of the XML blocks for the last step in the care pathway (e.g. all nodes for IAPT4) and paste them in below. You will need to update each node of these copied blocks according to the following:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>node_id: this needs to be updated with an incrementing number</li>\r\n		<li>level: this needs to be updated with the value of the \'step\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>serviceid: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'pathway_service_id\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>servicecode: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'code\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>other: any references to the original stage you copied in your pasted nodes need to be updated to the new stage, e.g. \'IAPT4 Refer On\' should become \'NEW_STAGE_CODE Refer On\' (where NEW_STAGE_CODE is the code of the new stage you are adding)</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Next, you need to add links from this new step onwards. Each link that the step you <em>copied </em>has, your new stage needs to have also. You should be able find the links for the copied step by doing a find on the node id. You may see multiple \'link\' tags containing \'source=\"rectangleNODE_ID\"\' or target=\"rectangleNODE_ID\" (where NODE_ID is the value in the \'id\' property of the node). Each of these needs copying and the NODE_ID replacing to reflect the new node ids. You need to paste the new links into the XML below the existing links.</li>\r\n	<li>Once the new XML is in place, you should update the row in the nh_diagram table with it and try to load it into the care pathway tool.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n','adding-a-step-to-a-care-pathway',6,1,1,'2016-08-26 10:24:50','2016-09-13 16:08:42',NULL),(56,7,'Adding/Changing Patient Tab Navigation','How to add or change the patient tabs','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Adding a New Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Adding a new tab usually involves writing a patch to update some data in a service\'s database, since there are a finite number of tabs and \'adding\' a new one usually actually involves editing an existing one. Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table, and will have a <code>per_tabName</code> column which tells you what type of tab you\'re looking at. The tab you\'ll find yourself changing the most often will be the Assessment tabs for example, whose type is \'assessment\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Editing an Existing Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table. You should locate the one you want to change and use its ID to make a patch which updates this row. From this table, you can change the tab\'s name and display order. The following is an example of a patch which changes the order. TYhese kinds of patches should be stored in the <code>mysql/service_patches</code> directory and include the audit log query that inserts a row into <code>db_patches</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (\'20160830-NAME_OF_THE_PATCH.sql\', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), \'YOUR_MYSQL_USERNAME\', \'\');\r\n\r\nUPDATE `nh_userPermission` SET `per_order`=NEW_ORDER&nbsp;where `per_id`=PERMISSION_ID;</pre>\r\n </p>\r\n','addingchanging-patient-tab-navigation',6,1,1,'2016-08-30 10:18:14','2016-09-13 15:58:26',NULL),(57,7,'Adding Globals','How to add globals to iaptus','<h3>Add the Global with a Default Setting </h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Write a patch which inserts the new global into the <code>nh_global</code> table, setting a default value. You could use the following query, replacing \'<code>NEW_GLOBAL_NAME\' with the name of your new global:</code>\r\n\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>INSERT INTO nh_global (var_name, var_value, var_type, ser_id, live)&lt;br /&gt;\r\nSELECT \'NEW_GLOBAL_NAME\', 1, \'copyName\', ser_id, 1 FROM nh_service;</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>If you have any services you need to change the default value for, you should also update these in the same patch. You could use the following query, replacing \'<code>NEW_GLOBAL_NAME\' with the name of your new global:</code>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>​​UPDATE nh_global SET var_value = 0 WHERE ser_id IN (8, 38) and var_name = \'  NEW_GLOBAL_NAME\';</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>​Save this new patch to <code>mysql/patches.</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Add a Switch for the Global in the Control Panel</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Open html/inc/class/GlobalsEditorConfig.php</li>\r\n    <li>Locate the $groupsArray for the area you need to add the gloabl to. This will be <strong>after</strong> line 953, and will look something like this:\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>$groupsArray[\'Assessment\'] = array(\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'assessmentRiskDetails\'\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;\'hideAssSummary\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'dontShowRiskNotAssessedLabel\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'showTreatGoalInAssessmentTab\'\r\n);</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>​Add the new global name into this array:\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>$groupsArray[\'Assessment\'] = array(\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'assessmentRiskDetails\'\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;\'hideAssSummary\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'dontShowRiskNotAssessedLabel\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'showTreatGoalInAssessmentTab\'\r\n    \'myNewAwesomeGlobalName\'\r\n);</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>​Next you need to add the global switch config to the $globalsConfig array. Add this in before line 953 along with the other $globalsConfigs. You can use an existing $globalsConfig declaration as a template for your new one, but it may look something like this:\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>$globalsConfig[\'myNewAwesomeGlobalName\'] = array(\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'description\' =&gt; \'Enable the new awesome global\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'formFieldType\' =&gt; \'radio\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'varValues\' =&gt; array(\'enabled\' =&gt; \'1\', \'disabled\' =&gt; \'0\')\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'var_type\' =&gt; \'copyName\'\r\n);</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','adding-globals',7,1,1,'2016-08-31 08:59:44','2016-09-13 15:57:28',NULL),(58,7,'National GP Practices and GPs','Information about the national GP practices and GP and practice information in the system','<p>Iaptus handles both GP practice and individual GP data. <strong>GP practice&nbsp;data is used in national reporting and the codes and information is from the national data published by the HSCIC.&nbsp;Individual GP data and GP&nbsp;codes however are not necessarily unique and the gp_code entries cannot be relied upon</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Database Storage</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Shared Database&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The shared database contains the&nbsp;<strong>nh_national_practice</strong> and <strong>nh_national_gp&nbsp;</strong>tables.&nbsp;These tables contain national GP practice and national general practitioner data derived from national data released&nbsp;by the HSCIC and updated at quarterly intervals. <em>Previously these tables were located on the iaptus Global databases and at the time of writing, there are still copies there - these are not being updated and will be removed in the future when we are certain everything in iaptus is using the Shared Database source without any issues.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Iaptus Databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_gp_serPractice</strong> : this table contains the gp practices that are turned on for a particular service. It has a local_pr_id autoincrement column which provides the local_pr_id values that are used everywhere else in the database to identify practices. The pr_id column relates to different things depending on the local_entry column value:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width:800px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>local_entry value</td>\r\n			<td>pr_id value</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>pr_id is the foreign key from pr_id column in nh_gp_local_practice (see below)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>0</td>\r\n			<td>pr_id is the foreign key&nbsp;from pr_id column in nh_national_practice table in Shared database (see above)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If local_entry is 0 (ie. relates to practice from nh_national_practice table on Shared database) then the data should match national data in the shared database and the superuser tools will only allow national practices to be added or deleted - not amended (except for &quot;nicknames&quot;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_gp_local_practice</strong>: this table contains data for &quot;practices&quot;&nbsp;that are not in the national GP&nbsp;data that comes from the HSCIC. Iaptus services can create their own&nbsp;entries in here using&nbsp;the &#39;Local Sources&#39; section of the GP Practice Manager Tool. The two instances where you usually have local sources are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>GP referrals from institutions that are not a normal GP practice on the national register (e.g. army base referral)</li>\r\n	<li>Old entries that could not be successfully matched against a national practice when iaptus moved to using the official national GP Practice&nbsp;data a few years back and all practices already present in the iaptus databases&nbsp;were mapped across to the correct national practice. Practice codes in this table are optional and may not be accurate even when present.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_gp</strong> : this table contains individual GP&nbsp;data and each GP row is linked to a single gp practice. The auto-increment gp_id column from this table is used everywhere else in the database to identify individual gps.&nbsp;When a national gp practice is added to an iaptus service initially a list of gps with gp_codes for that practice are imported at the same time. Thereafter this data can be freely updated however via front end tools (see GP Practice Manager) and gp codes and data cannot be relied upon as matching national data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_gp_group</strong>: defines groups of gp practices which can be created by iaptus services using front end superuser tools (see GP Practice Manager)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_gp_groupPractice</strong>: link table which links local_pr_ids to gp groups (see nh_gp_group above)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>GP Practice Manager</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The superuser GP Practice Manager tool allows clients to:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Add and remove national GP Practices to their local iaptus instance from the national GP Practice&nbsp;data (see Shared database above)</li>\r\n	<li>Create Local Sources for &quot;practices&quot; unavailable in the national data</li>\r\n	<li>Create and remove GP Practice Groups and assign and remove practices / local sources to the groups</li>\r\n	<li>Amend individual GP details attached to any practices or local sources</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Client Requests to Amend or Add Practices&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In the past we used to amend practice data that was wrong in the HSCIC updates and add new practices in advance of them being included in the next quarterly HSCIC update. <strong>We no longer do this - clients should contact the HSCIC directly for corrections to existing entries or wait for the next quarterly update to be released if a new practice is missing.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The national practice lists are currently updated by the Data Services team - queries about when the next update is due and if a specific practice or correction appears in it may be referred to that team. The update download and processing script is currently run manually, but may be turned into a fully automated process on the server in the near future.</p>\r\n','national-gp-practices-and-gps',8,1,30,'2016-09-07 16:23:03','2016-09-08 09:00:28',NULL),(59,31,'Tests','TestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTestTest','<p></p>\r\n','tests',2,1,1,'2016-09-12 11:13:38','2016-09-12 11:13:49','2016-09-12 11:13:49'),(60,31,'Tests','xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;','<p>xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;xfcgvhbjkl;vghbjnkl;</p>\r\n','tests',2,NULL,1,'2016-09-12 14:19:49','2016-09-12 14:19:52','2016-09-12 14:19:52'),(61,8,'Prism Database Tables','Describes tables used by Prism in iaptus and Postroom','<p>A description of the tables used by Prism in iaptus and the Postroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<table border=\"1\" bordercolor=\"#ccc\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:1000px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><strong>Table Name</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Codebase</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Database</strong></td>\r\n			<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_clinical_contact</td>\r\n			<td>Postroom</td>\r\n			<td>apiv2</td>\r\n			<td>Contains clinical contact data returned from online provider.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_episode</td>\r\n			<td>Postroom</td>\r\n			<td>apiv2</td>\r\n			<td>Maps episode IDs to external patient UUIDs, episode UUIDs and therapist UUIDs.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>atlas_clinical_contact_link</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Links a clinical contact ID with an atlas clinical contact ID from postroom (atlas_clinical_contact).</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field_config</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Field configurations for data to send to online providers (providers have different requirements).</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field_history</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>History of changes made to Prism field configurations, and who made the change.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_sent_referrals</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Details about episodes that have been sent off to third party online provider.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_service</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>Links an online provider to an iaptus service. &nbsp;Interface for this is in left hand superuser menu in iaptus, under \"Online Providers\" menu option.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus_shared</td>\r\n			<td>Master list of all online providers and the flag to indicate whether a provider supports courses</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_courses</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus_shared</td>\r\n			<td>List of courses for each online provider - this is just a name and course_id which we send to the online provider to indicate which course the patient is being referred to</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus_shared</td>\r\n			<td>Master list of all fields used for&nbsp;Prism referrals - essentially just a mapping between the name in the JSON data and a display name for the front end</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>online_providers_field_required</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus</td>\r\n			<td>iaptus_shared</td>\r\n			<td>List of fields that each provider&nbsp;<strong>requires</strong> is sent to them in a referral</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','prism-database-tables',3,1,34,'2016-09-13 14:15:18','2016-09-21 13:27:55',NULL),(62,18,'Tidy Mqueue On Maydenmtanode16','This is how you can tidy up the mqueue, as it will have a lot of email that has not been sent. The main issue is email destined for maydenasvnode1/2/3/5 or similar, this does need addressing.','<p>Follow the following steps to remove any unsent emails on asvnodes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>login to maydenmtanode16</li>\r\n	<li><code>cd /var/spool/mqueue</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>sudo sh /root/del_mail</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>sudo sh /root/tmp</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','tidy-mqueue-on-maydenmtanode16',5,1,20,'2016-09-19 08:44:04','2016-09-21 13:34:58',NULL),(63,32,'Setting Webforms up Locally & Testing','Created\r\n10 months ago by Andy Elsbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n10 months ago by Andy Elsbury','<h2>Setting Webforms up Locally &amp; Testing</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>**This is based on testing on the same vagrant machine, you can use this as a template to set up webforms on a separate Vagrant machine, just by changing the paths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Initial Action</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Obtain both the api private_key.pem &amp; webforms www.myprogress.info.crt files. (These can be obtain by asking someone who has access to these files).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In iaptus Code</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Modify api_config.ini to change the location paths for various files and urls</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ssl_cert_file = \"/var/www/html/iaptus/api/config/www.myprogress.info.crt\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>webservice_url = \"http://192.168.20.56/webforms/html/public/api.php?....”</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ansible Box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ssl_cert_file = \"/vagrant/applications/iaptus/api/config/www.myprogress.info.crt\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>webservice_url = \"http://192.168.20.99/api.php?....”</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In iaptus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create [patient appointment with] a webform [the patient will need an email address]</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Back up httpd.conf file</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo cp /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.bk</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open httpd.conf file</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo nano /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf (or any other type of text editor to modify conf)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Modify httpd.conf file</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Change DocumentRoot Path</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DocumentRoot \"/var/www/html/webforms/html/public/\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Ansible Box: DocumentRoot \"/vagrant/applications/webforms/html/public/\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set AllowOverride (line 304)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowOverride All</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Change Directory Path</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;Directory \"/var/www/html/webforms/html/public/\"&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Ansible Box: &lt;Directory \"/vagrant/applications/webforms/html/public/\"&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set AllowOverride (line 338)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowOverride All</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add this to the bottom</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ServerName 192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ServerAlias 192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DocumentRoot /var/www/html/webforms/html/public/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowEncodedSlashes On</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;Directory \"/var/www/html/webforms/html/public/\"&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Options Indexes MultiViews FollowSymLinks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowOverride All</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Order allow,deny</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Allow from all</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;/Directory&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ErrorLog logs/webforms-error_log</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CustomLog logs/webforms-access_log common</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;/Virtualhost&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*** Change ServerName and ServerAlias to match vagrant IP Address</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ansible Box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ServerName 192.168.20.99</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ServerAlias 192.168.20.99</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DocumentRoot /var/www/html/webforms/html/public/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowEncodedSlashes On</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;Directory \"/vagrant/applications/webforms/html/public/\"&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Options Indexes MultiViews FollowSymLinks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AllowOverride All</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Order allow,deny</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Allow from all</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;/Directory&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ErrorLog logs/webforms-error_log</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CustomLog logs/webforms-access_log common</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;/Virtualhost&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Restart Httpd</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo service httpd restart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run the API Cron (To send webform)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[You may have to create api_cron_config.php and comment out the non-Webform tasks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php /var/www/html/iaptus/api/cron/cron.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ansible Box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php /vagrant/applications/iaptus/api/cron/cron.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Browser</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fill in the webform (have to change https to http)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Modify httpd file</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo mv /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.webforms</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo mv /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.bk /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo service httpd restart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo rm /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.webforms</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run API Cron</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run API Cron (Update API DB from webforms)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php /var/www/html/iaptus/api/cron/cron/php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run Cron</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run Cron (Update iaptus DB)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php /var/www/html/iaptus/cron/cron/php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In iaptus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check webform has come back in</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Relax!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','setting-webforms-up-locally-testing',1,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 14:44:32','2016-09-20 14:44:32',NULL),(64,7,'Adding Columns to Find Patients','How to add columns to the \'Find Patients\' data table','<p>To add columns to the \'Find Patients\' table, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Open the nh_searchFields table in the selected global database and find the jsonName of the field you wish to turn on</li>\r\n	<li>Write a global&nbsp;patch which inserts this field into the nh_serSearchFields for the service who needs this field:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nINSERT INTO nh_serSearchFields (`fieldId`, `ser_id`, `order`) VALUES (\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;(SELECT fieldId FROM nh_searchFields WHERE jsonName=\'JSON_NAME_HERE\' LIMIT 1),&amp;nbsp;\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; SERVICE_ID_HERE,\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 100\r\n);</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','adding-columns-to-find-patients',2,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:46:12','2016-09-22 12:20:13',NULL),(65,33,'Getting PAF Log Data','How to get a count of postcodes looked up by services from the Postcode Address Finder log','<p>To extract a&nbsp;count of postcodes looked up by services using the PAF, run the following query on both the Demo paf_log database and the live paf_log database:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nSELECT&amp;nbsp;\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; paf_log.serviceId,\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; services.serviceName,\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; substring(UPPER(paf_log.postcode), 1, 2) as pcArea,\r\n&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; count(*)&amp;nbsp;\r\nFROM paf_log&amp;nbsp;\r\nLEFT JOIN services ON services.serviceId = paf_log.serviceId&amp;nbsp;\r\nWHERE paf_log.date &amp;gt; \'FROM_DATE_HERE\'&amp;nbsp;\r\nAND paf_log.date &amp;lt; \'TO_DATE_HERE\'\r\nGROUP BY paf_log.serviceId, substring(paf_log.postcode,1,2)\r\nORDER BY services.serviceName, pcArea</pre>\r\n','getting-paf-log-data',3,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:47:43','2016-09-22 12:26:27',NULL),(66,7,'Add Field to Group Sessions','How to add a field to group sessions for a service','<p>To start with, you need to know whether the field you need to add to group session exists in the nh_fields table.&nbsp;If the field&nbsp;<strong>does not</strong>&nbsp;exist, you need to write a patch which adds it to the nh_fields table and arrange for it to be deployed. You cannot add it to group sessions until this has been done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To add an&nbsp;<strong>existing</strong>&nbsp;field to group sessions, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Write a patch which adds the field to the nh_fieldsSer table. Check the notes for help replacing the placeholders in this query:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nINSERT INTO nh_fieldsSer table (fieldId, priority, type, course_order, ser_id, live) VALUES (FIELD_ID_HERE, PRIORITY_HERE, TYPE_HERE, COURSE_ORDER_HERE, SERVICE_ID_HERE, 1);</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Add the fieldId into nh_fieldsSer table, set priority, course_order = \'position in which the field appears on the front end\'.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the field to the groups template.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Replace the following placeholders in the query above with:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>FIELD_ID_HERE: id of the field you want to add to group sessions</li>\r\n	<li>PRIORITY_HERE:&nbsp;<strong>1</strong> if always&nbsp;mandatory, <strong>2</strong> if manadtory unless \'allow less than minimum dataset\' is ticked, <strong>3</strong> if always optional or <strong>4</strong> if always mandatory for MDS</li>\r\n	<li>TYPE_HERE:&nbsp;<strong>0</strong>&nbsp;for not dataset specific,&nbsp;<strong>1</strong>&nbsp;for IAPT dataset,&nbsp;<strong>2</strong>&nbsp;for Employment&nbsp;dataset, <strong>4</strong>&nbsp;for CYP dataset</li>\r\n	<li>COURSE_ORDER_HERE:&nbsp;the number of the position that the field appears on the iaptus front end</li>\r\n	<li>SERVICE_ID_HERE: id of the service you want to add the field for</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','add-field-to-group-sessions',4,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:48:33','2016-09-22 13:46:16',NULL),(67,32,'IAPTus Penetration Map','Created\r\n57 months ago by Chris Eldridge\r\nLast Updated\r\n19 months ago by Chris Eldridge','<p>https://fusiontables.googleusercontent.com/embedviz?q=select+col0%3E%3E1+from+1kwvDJU_jEzkrwpMevA1ELIaKcoKUbXnjCrsgSzc&amp;viz=MAP&amp;h=false&amp;lat=53.12401764289639&amp;lng=-1.26460302734381&amp;t=1&amp;z=7&amp;l=col0%3E%3E1&amp;y=3&amp;tmplt=4&amp;hml=GEOCODABLE</p>\r\n','iaptus-penetration-map',5,0,15,'2016-09-20 14:51:06','2016-09-22 12:40:08',NULL),(68,17,'Core iaptus Tables','A summary of tables in iaptus and key notes associated with them','<h3>nh_session:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Clinical contacts are stored in the nh_session table. Clinical contacts can be saved as \'incomplete contacts\', which allows a therapist to come back and complete them at a later date. They&nbsp;can also be marked as deleted which prevents them from&nbsp;appearing on the front end of iaptus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are 2 columns relevant to incomplete and deleted contacts: the \'live\' column and the \'temp\' column for which the entries don\'t work exactly as you might expect - see the table below.</p>\r\n\r\n<table class=\"table\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Description</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Live column value</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Temp column value</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Live completed clinical contact</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;1</td>\r\n			<td>0&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Deleted completed clinical contact</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;0</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;0</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Live incomplete clinical contact</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;0</td>\r\n			<td>1&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;Deleted incomplete clinical contact</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;0</td>\r\n			<td>0&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','core-iaptus-tables',6,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:52:31','2016-09-22 12:55:28',NULL),(69,13,'About Webforms Data','A list of useful information about Webforms and how the data is stored.','<p><strong>Security</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no patient identifiable information stored outside IAPTus, even when the patient has filled in the webform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We store only an id number for the patient with the webform and the questionnaire results are in a format that is meaningless unless you have access to the questionnaire within IAPTus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite having no patient identifiable information we also encrypt the results while outside IAPTus using AES public/private key pairs which means they can not be decrypted without the private key which is only stored on the IAPTus server.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Statuses</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we send a webform we can see if we have sent the email but can\'t know if the patient received it successfully unless they access the questionnaire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We log if they access the questionnaire, log if they attempt to fill it in (but don\'t fill in everything required), and we log and store the encrypted results if they fill it in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any status updates and results are routinely collected from the Webforms server by the Postroom (part of IAPTus that deals with data going in and out of IAPTus) and then from there they are moved into IAPTus itself, the results being decrypted and checked at that point.</p>\r\n','about-webforms-data',7,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:53:54','2016-09-22 12:57:27',NULL),(70,32,'Webforms isn\'t working, error \"Unable to find status code for id_public\"','Created\r\n35 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n35 months ago by Matt Ellis','<p>If the webforms_io table is filling up with entries that have a status_text like:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unable to find status code for id_public: 10044</p>\r\n\r\n<p>it means that something has gone wrong somewhere (usually a cron not setup right) and it\'s left the webforms database all messed up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check that crons are running (/var/www/includes/cron/scripts/log/cron.log) and they are not reporting errors</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To see what webforms are causing the issue run this sql on the webform database:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&amp;nbsp;SELECT wf.id_public, al.* FROM webform_session as wf LEFT JOIN api_log as al ON wf.id_public = al.id_public_session WHERE wf.updated = 1\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Any with a null value from the api_log table are outstanding webforms that the webforms system thinks are complete. To correct the issue you need to copy the last row in api_log_archived for those entries into the api_log table. Let cron run, check it worked, let it work through any backlog.</p>\r\n','webforms-isnt-working-error-unable-to-find-status-code-for-id-public',8,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 14:55:06','2016-09-22 12:57:44','2016-09-22 12:57:44'),(71,32,'Letter Tags','Created\r\n20 months ago by Nina Barlow\r\nLast Updated\r\n19 months ago by Nina Barlow','<p><strong>New Letter Tags</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check that data for new tags exist in DB and if so what table(s) - in task 33238 data available in nh_assessment_summary_results</li>\r\n	<li>Make a new branch (see Branch Tool section of&nbsp;https://crm.mayden.co.uk/library/3472/ )</li>\r\n	<li>Go to letters.class.php within&nbsp;..htmlincclass &nbsp;and find relevant function (if it exists) for that group of data (e.g. getAssessmentDetails)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to applicable class to update the function above (in this instance, getAssessmentDetails is within patient.class.php)</li>\r\n	<li>Update SQL statement in function to include required DB field(s) for new $tags</li>\r\n	<li>Update letters.class.php to refer to new tags returned by function</li>\r\n	<li>New tag(s) need to be added to nh_letter_tags. &nbsp;Since new rows required are related to a code change, the DB changes need to be added to a \"patch\":<br />\r\n	...branchmysqlpatches</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','letter-tags',9,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 14:56:00','2016-09-20 14:56:00',NULL),(72,32,'Add Custom Assessment Tab','Created\r\n21 months ago by Nina Barlow\r\nLast Updated\r\n14 months ago by Nina Barlow','<div style=\"margin-left:auto;\">\r\n<div style=\"margin-left:-9px;\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p><strong>Adding Custom Assessment</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>e.g. Task 48629</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Requirement</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bath (BANES) currently have a version within their Assessment Tab. They have provided a completely different assessment form. Therefore, create version 2 in the database (it can’t be created from the front-end), which will auto create a v2 tab within the assessment tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Sample Form:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"CA1\" src=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/CA1.png\" style=\"height:auto; margin-bottom:20px; width:966px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Need to add to the following db tables:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nh_assessment</strong><br />\r\nAdd each line (whether it’s a title or a question – include html to format as required) as a separate row.<img alt=\"CA2\" src=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/CA2.png\" style=\"height:auto; margin-bottom:20px; width:1153px\" />For each answer that is not a text box, need to generate row(s) within the list table to provide a listid (of parent) to refer to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>nh_list</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"CA3\" src=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/CA3.png\" style=\"height:auto; margin-bottom:20px; width:1142px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nh_assess_results</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Generate new column for additional answers to be collected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>e.g</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"CA4\" src=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/CA4.png\" style=\"height:auto; margin-bottom:20px; width:828px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nh_assess_results_old</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Replicate the new columns as above.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note \"feature\" of the scorable field on nh_assessment</strong><br />\r\nThere must&nbsp;<strong><em>not&nbsp;</em></strong>be any scorable fields set in previous versions of the assessment if the new version requires scorable fields.<br />\r\nIf there are, then an error equivalent to the following will appear:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;[2015-01-16 16:30:08] iaptus.ERROR: 32950950-699B-C080-8E3B-903C1136D828: Uncaught Exception: \'DB Error: syntax error\' iaptus/iaptus-demo/html_live/patients.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Line: 2101&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Msg: SELECT ,sefton_v2_1,sefton_v2_2,sefton_v2_3 FROM nh_assess_results WHERE pat_id = 11506 AND epis_id = 11746</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[nativecode=1064 ** You have an error in your SQL syntax; check the manual that corresponds to your MySQL server version for the right syntax to use</p>\r\n\r\n<p>near \'sefton_v2_1,sefton_v2_2,sefton_v2_3 FROM nh_assess_results WHERE pat_id = 11506 \' at line 1] []</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{\"fileName\":\"/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus-demo/html_live/inc/exceptionHandler.php\",\"line\":23,\"serviceId\":32,\"userId\":\"1540\"}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Generate SQL Statement</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the client has checked within the demo site that the Assessment Tab is OK, an SQL Statement needs to be generate from the demo site that can be run directly against the live database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Firstly, statements to add all new columns to nh_assess_results_old &amp;&nbsp;nh_assess_results:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ALTER TABLE `nh_assess_results_old`<br />\r\nADD COLUMN `croy_v2_1` TEXT,<br />\r\nADD COLUMN `croy_v2_2` TEXT;</p>\r\nALTER TABLE `nh_assess_results`<br />\r\nADD COLUMN `croy_v2_1` TEXT,\r\n<p>ADD COLUMN `croy_v2_2` TEXT;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, for any new list answer items, insert the parent item and save the ID as a variable (@varName) to use in later statements:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `nh_list` (`listName`, `listDescription`, `score`, `listGroup`, `listOrder`, `listMDSReference`, `listParent`, `updatedTime`, `team_id`, `updatedBy`, `listArchived`)&nbsp;<br />\r\nVALUES (\'croy_v2_done_notdone\', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, \'0000-00-00 00:00:00\', 137, NULL, 0);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SET @croy_v2_done_notdone= last_insert_id(); #@croy_v2_done_notdone</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, insert the list items, using the @varName as the listParent:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `nh_list` (`listName`, `listDescription`, `score`, `listGroup`, `listOrder`, `listMDSReference`, `listParent`, `updatedTime`, `team_id`, `updatedBy`, `listArchived`) VALUES (\'Done\', \'\', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, @croy_v2_done_notdone, \'0000-00-00 00:00:00\', 137, NULL, 0);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `nh_list` (`listName`, `listDescription`, `score`, `listGroup`, `listOrder`, `listMDSReference`, `listParent`, `updatedTime`, `team_id`, `updatedBy`, `listArchived`) VALUES (\'Not Done\', \'\', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, @croy_v2_done_notdone, \'0000-00-00 00:00:00\', 137, NULL, 0);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then add insert each row in nh_assessment, referring to any new list items using the @varName:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `nh_assessment` (`ass_name`, `ass_type`, `ass_fieldName`, `ass_description`, `ass_order`, `questionnaire_id`, `scorable`, `risk_scorable`, `listId`, `version`, `ser_id`, `live`) VALUES (\'&lt;br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CRISIS PLAN SUMMARY: Once you have asked these questions, read them back to the client by way of a plan of what to do in a crisis.&lt;/strong&gt;\', \'radio\', \'croy_v2_9\', NULL, 72, NULL, 0, 0, @croy_v2_yes_no, 2, 136, 1);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `nh_assessment` (`ass_name`, `ass_type`, `ass_fieldName`, `ass_description`, `ass_order`, `questionnaire_id`, `scorable`, `risk_scorable`, `listId`, `version`, `ser_id`, `live`) VALUES (\'32. How likely are you to follow this plan?\', NULL, \'\', NULL, 73, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 2, 136, 1);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Test SQL Statement</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the statement has been generated, delete all changes (columns, table rows in both assess and list) in the Demo environment and run the full statement. &nbsp;Check via the front end that the assessment is OK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n','add-custom-assessment-tab',10,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 14:56:50','2016-09-20 14:56:50',NULL),(73,32,'Client Advanced Exports','Created\r\n20 months ago by Nina Barlow\r\nLast Updated\r\n20 months ago by Nina Barlow','<p>If there\'s an issue with Client Advanced Exports (e.g. Task 51579 where dates are returning lo-date rather than null in csv file):</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Open Vagrant &amp; vagrant ssh</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Switch on exports by creating a copy of ...croncron-config-example.php (named cron_config.php) and uncomment the following code:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>// &nbsp; &nbsp;\'exports\'=&gt;array(</p>\r\n\r\n<p>// &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\'hours\'=&gt;\'0\',</p>\r\n\r\n<p>// &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\'minutes\'=&gt;\'15\',</p>\r\n\r\n<p>// &nbsp; &nbsp;),</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Create version of&nbsp;cron_setup_example.php (named&nbsp;cron_setup.php)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- &nbsp;Create new folder(s) in branch ...htmldocumentsdocumentService101exports&nbsp;and change permissions within ConEmu command shell</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cd html/document</p>\r\n\r\n<p>chmod 777 documentService101</p>\r\n\r\n<p>chmod 777 documentService/exports</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;- Run export&nbsp;(n.b. &nbsp;this currently doesn\'t work - need further assistance to get this up and running)&nbsp;to create csv files</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cd cron</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php exports.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- &nbsp;If changes required, update ExportConfig_6.class.php SQL script in ..htmlincclassexport</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>e.g. for the date issue within 51579, need to ensure all date fields are returned with the following IF statement:<br />\r\nDATE(IF(`pat_dob`&gt;\'1900-01-01\',`pat_dob`,NULL)) AS `dob`, -- date of birth<br />\r\nrather than:<br />\r\n&nbsp;DATE(nh_actions.date) AS move_date,</p>\r\n','client-advanced-exports',11,0,15,'2016-09-20 14:57:56','2016-09-22 13:15:30',NULL),(74,32,'Add new Diagnosis codes','Created\r\n46 months ago by Joe Haines\r\nLast Updated\r\n2 weeks ago by Joe Haines','<p>Currently we don\'t have all Diagnosis codes within iaptus and whenever a client requests to add one, &nbsp;the following process needs to be followed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Check the nh_mdsReference table to see if we already have them within the nh_mdsReference table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. If we already have those codes within the nh_mdsReference table, create a patch to add these new diagnosis codes into the nh_list table for the service who requested it. Make sure the \'listMDSReference\' column is mapped to the correct id and update the \'listOrder\' column to make the list sort alphabetically.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. If we don\'t already have those codes within the nh_mdsReference table, create a patch to add those codes to nh_mdsReference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: For insert queries, include the&nbsp;<strong>Id</strong>&nbsp;of the new row. Thus allowing all the&nbsp;nh_mdsReference&nbsp;tables to be in sync with each other</p>\r\n','add-new-diagnosis-codes',12,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 14:58:36','2016-09-20 14:58:36',NULL),(75,34,'IAPTus Deploy Setup','How to correctly configure your environment on iaptusvnode14 for deployment','<p>In order to use the automated deploy tools effectively, you must first correctly configure your environment on iaptusvnode14 (10.0.2.42):</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into iaptusvnode14 and create your own custom build properties file in<strong>&nbsp;</strong><code>~/iaptus.properties</code>.&nbsp; This file is read by the build script and can add your own login names to the database.&nbsp;Do not add your passwords&nbsp;- storing user passwords on live servers is a security risk. Example iaptus.properties file:\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nsvn_user=YOUR_NAME@mayden.co.uk\r\ndb.admin.username=mayhealthv_YOUR_INITIALS</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Adding these entries to your local build file will pre-populate the build script login questions and save you having to type them it.</li>\r\n	<li>Add your private key for iaptusivnode15 to your identity, this is needed for deploying code to other hosts in the cluster.&nbsp; Use a tool like PuttyGen to export the key in&nbsp; OpenSSH format.&nbsp; Make sure it has a strong password and uploaded it to maydenvnode14 (10.0.2.42) to:<strong>&nbsp;</strong><code>~/.ssh/identity</code>&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Run the following command to set the correct permissions on the file\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nchmod a-rwx,u+r ~/.ssh/identity</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>A correct OpenSSH key file looks like this:</p>\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\n-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\r\nProc-Type: 4,ENCRYPTED\r\nDEK-Info: DES-EDE3-CBC,8345D2A7FD1E32F5\r\nLBz6pUUP/a3rvbvS80sXy6H5Kdnf/DUt00n8wVJL0o9wjnNnJ8BywnPCW/gqetM7\r\n...... etc </pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Test your private key works by typing <code>ssh-add</code>.&nbsp; This will look for your identity file and prompt for the keyfile password.&nbsp; If this does not work, then you will not be able to deploy to other hosts in the cluster.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Run the&nbsp;<code>ssh 10.0.2.43</code>&nbsp;command - this will confirm whether you can connect or not</li>\r\n	<li>For convenience,&nbsp;set your database and ssh key passwords to auto type just the password by default.&nbsp; This will enable you to use your password during deploys quickly via hotkeys</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','iaptus-deploy-setup',13,1,15,'2016-09-20 14:59:32','2016-09-22 13:47:48',NULL),(76,32,'Dev Team - moving care pathway changes to live','Created\r\n73 months ago by Dave Bould\r\nLast Updated\r\n2 months ago by Dave Bould','<p>Care pathway changes are made by the Admin team on the demo site and agreed with the client. Once agreed the Admin team will ask the Development team to move the changes from the demo site to the live site.The developer who moves the care pathway should normally make a written note on the care pathway folder to say the date and time they moved the pathway, in addition to completing the CRM task for the move. If as a developer you have not been given a CRM task ID and/or care pathway diagram to make a note on, ask Claire for them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Moving updated Care Pathway from Demo Site to Live Site</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;<strong>Super user -&gt;</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Care Pathway (mayden only)</strong>&nbsp;on the demo site. Near the bottom, you should be able to see a section called&nbsp;<strong>Care Pathway Sync Tool.</strong>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Click on the&nbsp;<strong>Check Care Pathway</strong>&nbsp;button on the very bottom of the page just to make sure the care pathway has no errors. If there are any errors, please let Claire know before continuing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Click the&nbsp;<strong>Export&nbsp;</strong>button (it should say Export SQL to Update&nbsp;<strong>Live&nbsp;</strong>Care Pathway. If it says Export to Update&nbsp;<strong>Demo&nbsp;</strong>Care Pathway on the<strong>Demo&nbsp;</strong>site, please refer to Richard He). A download dialog will pop up with a .SQL patch file ready to download. If you are using IE, please always use the Save button (it won\'t work otherwise).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to the database you are about to update using a SQL client.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check the patch file and make sure the value of&nbsp;<strong>id&nbsp;</strong>column in&nbsp;<strong>nh_stage</strong>&nbsp;table and<strong>&nbsp;id, stage_from</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>stage_to</strong>&nbsp;columns in<strong>nh_stage_process</strong>&nbsp;table are always less than&nbsp;<strong>100,000</strong>. Double check that the ser_id values in the patch match the ser_id in the nh_service table of the live database to confirm you have picked up the right care pathway from demo.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Download the nh_stage_process and nh_stage table from the live customer\'s database. &nbsp;Import them into a local database.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the Care Pathway patch (leaving out the last four queries where tables get dropped and renamed) on your local database server, in the same database as the customer\'s imported tables.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the following query on your local database:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n\r\n&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nSELECT * </pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nFROM nh_stage_process</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nLEFT JOIN nh_stage_process_tempVersion ON nh_stage_process.`id` = nh_stage_process_tempVersion.`id`</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nWHERE nh_stage_process.stage_from != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_from</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nOR nh_stage_process.stage_to != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_to</pre>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If any results are returned, new process IDs that link stage_from and stage_to together no longer hold the same stages as they did on the live site. &nbsp;This will lead to data corruption. &nbsp;If rows are returned DO NOT DEPLOY THE CARE PATHWAY. &nbsp;Instead revert the broken Care Pathway on the demo site to a previously stable version.</li>\r\n	<li>If the patch is safe, continue moving it through the Jira workflow to get it ready for deploy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check the existing care pathway history for at least 3 patients just to make sure there aren\'t any unexpected errors in our patch file.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to the care pathway tool on live site and update their diagram which can be downloaded from their demo site.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Synchronizing the Demo care pathway from Live</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is only necessary where the demo care pathway has got into a mess and you want to put the demo care pathway back to match live ie. the last approved / agreed version.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;<strong>Care Pathway (mayden only)</strong>&nbsp;under Super user menu on the live site. Near the bottom, you should be able to see a section called<strong>Care Pathway Sync Tool.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Click the&nbsp;<strong>Export&nbsp;</strong>button (it should say Export SQL to Update&nbsp;<strong>Demo&nbsp;</strong>Care Pathway. If it says Export to Update Live Care Pathway on the&nbsp;<strong>Live</strong>site, please refer to Richard He), and a download dialog will pop up with a .SQL patch file ready to download. If you are using IE, please always use the Save button (it won\'t work otherwise).&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the .SQL patch file on&nbsp;<strong>Demo&nbsp;</strong>site and the&nbsp;<strong>Demo&nbsp;</strong>care pathway will be synchronized with Live automatically.&nbsp;<strong>IMPORTANT: NEVER RUN THIS PATCH FILE ON THE LIVE SITE AS IT WILL BREAK THE ENTIRE CARE PATHWAY!</strong></p>\r\n','dev-team-moving-care-pathway-changes-to-live',14,0,15,'2016-09-20 15:39:28','2016-09-22 13:07:13',NULL),(77,29,'Importing a Care Pathway Diagram Locally','How to import a care pathway from demo into your local version of iaptus.','<p>To&nbsp;import a care pathway from demo into your local version of iaptus, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>In your local iaptus database truncate the nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Copy the row for the diagram you need&nbsp;in Demo\'s&nbsp;nh_diagram table</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Insert this row into nh_diagram table into your local iaptus database, remembering to change the ser_id column value to 101</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Click the “New Care Pathway Tool” superuser link in your local version of iaptus</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Select&nbsp;the diagram you have just inserted into the database</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Click “Export To Demo Site”. This will populate rows in nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables and you will be able to see this care pathway in “Care Pathway (Mayden Only)” tool</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','importing-a-care-pathway-diagram-locally',7,1,35,'2016-09-20 15:51:36','2016-09-21 13:41:06',NULL),(78,29,'Download Care Pathway PDF','How to download a copy of a care pathway diagram PDF','<p>To download a copy of a care pathway diagram PDF, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Go to “New Care Pathway Tool” in <strong>iaptus</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Open the&nbsp;last&nbsp;non-autosaved&nbsp;diagram.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Wait for it to load (it might take some time)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Click “Create PDF” - this should trigger download.If it does&nbsp;not, check your pop-up settings.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Attach the&nbsp;downloaded PDF to the relevant orbit task, if necessary</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','download-care-pathway-pdf',8,1,35,'2016-09-20 15:52:13','2016-09-21 13:53:42',NULL),(79,29,'Changing a Care Pathway On Demo','How to get manual changes to a care pathway put onto demo','<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Make the necessary changes in the care pathway xml</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Write a patch with the following queries:</p>\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nDELETE FROM nh_stage WHERE ser_id=SER_ID_HERE\r\nDELETE FROM nh_stage_process WHERE pathway_id=SER_ID_HERE</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Write a patch which inserts a row into the nh_diagram table in the demo database with corrected diagram xml, for example:</p>\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_diagram` (\r\n    `ser_id`,\r\n    `title`,\r\n    `author`,\r\n    `date`,\r\n    `xml`,\r\n    `notes`,\r\n    `autosave`,\r\n    `imported`,\r\n    `live`,\r\n    `removed`\r\n) VALUES (\r\n    SERVICE_ID_HERE,\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;SERVICE_NAME_HERE,\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;YOUR_INITIALS_HERE,\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,\r\n    XML_HERE,\r\n    NOTES_HERE\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;\'1\',\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;\'0\',\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;\'0\',\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;\'0\'\r\n);</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>In the notes please include what has changed / what has been fixed and add the note that it has been exported to demo.</li>\r\n	<li>These queries will have to be run manually on demo database. Please ask someone from release team to code review it before you run it. Update the “Special Notes for Release Team” section in JIRA with \"Please do not run on live, patch already has been run manually on demo database.”. After the queries have been run, please make sure that you complete the JIRA workflow and get this issue into release branch and to “deployed” stage.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to “New Care Pathway Tool” in demo site for this service, open your diagram and click “Export To Demo Site”. This will populate rows in nh_stage and nh_stage_process tables and you will be able to see this care pathway in “Care Pathway (Mayden Only)” tool.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','changing-a-care-pathway-on-demo',9,1,35,'2016-09-20 15:52:58','2016-09-22 13:07:27',NULL),(80,11,'Accessing SMS XML Log','How to access SMS information using the iaptus SMS log feed','<p>As all IAPTUs SMS messages have their statuses routed through the iaptus.co.uk server. We can use this to get a cross service count of messages and filter by service and/or date. This information is available through a web api at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/library/1769/%20http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/xmlfeed.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/xmlfeed.php</a>&nbsp;which requires various parameters passed in. You can see the available options and test it using &nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/test.php?secretknock=mayden\">http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/test.php?secretknock=mayden</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Current options include filtering by service and date and how the information should be grouped and&nbsp;displayed. The following are examples of this&nbsp;(copied from &nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/test.php?secretknock=mayden\">http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/test.php?secretknock=mayden</a>):</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/pub