a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/xmlfeed.php?type=sms&amp;service=26&amp;dateFrom=2011-01-01&amp;dateTo=2012-01-01&amp;byDay=1&amp;idinloop=1&amp;IQLU6C0U4QCHLZEEC56XGKMEQ6OOXWFO1N4N9P872TRH1GB2X590EHX698RP=LAJG72RA2CA51HQIZRI0MN4YE5ZNPSYBXSE0IBLGIEW31HW8VT2B96L1DTHK\" target=\"_blank\">service-dateFrom-dateTo-byDay-idInLoop-</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/xmlfeed.php?type=sms&amp;service=26&amp;dateFrom=2011-01-01&amp;dateTo=2012-01-01&amp;byDay=1&amp;byMonth=1&amp;IQLU6C0U4QCHLZEEC56XGKMEQ6OOXWFO1N4N9P872TRH1GB2X590EHX698RP=LAJG72RA2CA51HQIZRI0MN4YE5ZNPSYBXSE0IBLGIEW31HW8VT2B96L1DTHK\" target=\"_blank\">service-dateFrom-dateTo-byDay-byMonth-</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.iaptus.co.uk/public/xmlfeed.php?type=sms&amp;service=26&amp;dateFrom=2011-01-01&amp;dateTo=2012-01-01&amp;byDay=1&amp;byMonth=1&amp;idinloop=1&amp;IQLU6C0U4QCHLZEEC56XGKMEQ6OOXWFO1N4N9P872TRH1GB2X590EHX698RP=LAJG72RA2CA51HQIZRI0MN4YE5ZNPSYBXSE0IBLGIEW31HW8VT2B96L1DTHK\" target=\"_blank\">service-dateFrom-dateTo-byDay-byMonth-idInLoop-</a></p>\r\n','accessing-sms-xml-log',15,1,15,'2016-09-20 15:53:38','2016-09-22 13:23:16',NULL),(81,29,'Adding Stages to \'Find Patients From\'','How to add a care pathway stage to the \'Find Patients From\' sidebar area','<p>To make a care pathway stage appear&nbsp;in&nbsp;the \'Find Patients From\' sidebar&nbsp;area you need to write a patch which sets the value of the <code>stage_shotcut</code> column to “yes” in the nh_stage table for that stage. To remove a care pathway stage from&nbsp;the \'Find Patients From\' sidebar&nbsp;area, set the column value to \"no\"&nbsp;instead.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Example patch text:</h3>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nUPDATE nh_stage\r\nSET stage_shotcut = \'yes\'\r\nWHERE ser_id = 101\r\nAND `id`=STAGE_ID_HERE);</pre>\r\n','adding-stages-to-find-patients-from',10,1,35,'2016-09-20 15:54:57','2016-09-22 13:21:47',NULL),(82,11,'SMS Statuses','An explanation of what statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from AQL','<p>This is taken directly from AQL\'s site and explains what each of the statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMS delivery reports are acknowledgements from the handsets that the message has been received by the phone. This is not the same as being *READ* by the recipient and&nbsp;though some phones may receive the message, they may choose not to display it depending on the settings on the phone.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Statuses</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Sending</strong>: the message has been sent to the mobile networks - ie. it has left the AQL&nbsp;platform and is now in the hands of the mobile network</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Buffered</strong>: the&nbsp;message is on the network and awaiting delivery to the handset. Buffered will usually appear when there is either network or handset congestion - for example:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>the network provider is busy</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for delivery report from the handset</li>\r\n		<li>the handset\'s memory is full</li>\r\n		<li>the handset is switched off</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for the handset to accept the message.</li>\r\n		<li>bad reception or network coverage</li>\r\n		<li>out of service area</li>\r\n		<li>handset is not registered properly to a mast</li>\r\n		<li>The buffer memory (temporary holding memory) of the handset is corrupted</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Delivered&nbsp;</strong>to handset: handset has acknowledged the message. Note - the time of the delivery report = time for the message to be sent, PLUS the time for the delivery report to get back to AQL. This means that a delivery report taking 10 seconds means the message was probably delivered in about 5 seconds.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Rejected</strong>:&nbsp;message not delivered. This status could be caused by bad reception or out of service area. A few phone networks do reject sms if the phone is unreachable without further attempts. If you are using non-privileged route such as standard or economy route, \"Failed\" status will be returned if the mobile network is too busy processing data via privileged route. We would strongly suggest customer to route via our premium uk or global route because more often than not unprivileged-route ended up as failed.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Binary data not shown</strong>:&nbsp;the message is not text message. It could be a wap-push message, mms message, ringtones, images, vcard, the message being&nbsp;split up into different packets etc</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Invalid Number</strong>:&nbsp;means that the destination number is not a valid number.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','sms-statuses',16,1,15,'2016-09-20 16:27:42','2016-09-22 13:29:35',NULL),(83,32,'Blacklisting Patients','Created\r\n73 months ago\r\nLast Updated\r\n72 months ago by Tomas Cerney\r\nShould be in SMS section','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The SMS class has a system to blacklist a patient if their mobile number does not appear valid, or if a response comes back after sending a text with an Invalid number status. No messages will be sent to a blacklisted patient, and once blacklisted a patient remains blacklisted until their mobile number is changed.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Creating / Editing Patient Registration</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>When a patient is created or edited, the SMS class processes the patients mobile number and decides if the patient should be blacklisted or not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"create_edit_blacklist\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/sms/create_edit_blacklist.png\" style=\"height:453px; width:773px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Sending SMS</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Before sending an SMS, the SMS class processes the patients mobile number and decides if it should be blacklisted or not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"send_sms_blacklist\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/sms/send_sms_blacklist.png\" style=\"height:303px; width:773px\" /></p>\r\n','blacklisting-patients',17,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 16:29:40','2016-09-22 13:28:36','2016-09-22 13:28:36'),(84,32,'Updating Risk Assessment','Created\r\n70 months ago by Andy Elsbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n47 months ago by Andy Elsbury\r\nLook for newer article on CRM first, then delete','<ol>\r\n	<li>Open HeidiSQL -&gt; load database</li>\r\n	<li>Go to the&nbsp;<strong>nh_assessment table</strong>&nbsp;from the list of tables</li>\r\n	<li>Enter an&nbsp;<strong>ass_name</strong>&nbsp;(used to display the text for the field names on the html assessment page)</li>\r\n	<li>Choose the&nbsp;<strong>ass_typ</strong>e (text, select, radio, textarea, textareasmall, textareamedium) This will be used on the HTML page.</li>\r\n	<li>Give the Record an&nbsp;<strong>ass_fieldName</strong>. This will be used in the<strong>&nbsp;nh_assess_results</strong>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<strong>nh_assess_results_old tables.</strong></li>\r\n	<li>(OPTIONAL)&nbsp;You&nbsp;can provide a field with a tooltip.&nbsp;<strong>ass_description</strong>&nbsp;needs to be filled in, in order to do this.</li>\r\n	<li>Choose an&nbsp;<strong>ass_order</strong>. This is the order that you wish the risk assessment form to be in, which field comes first etc.</li>\r\n	<li>(OPTIONAL)&nbsp;If you wish to add a questionnaire to any field, you will need to enter the questionnaire id number into the&nbsp;<strong>questionnaire_id</strong>field.</li>\r\n	<li>You must then decide whether the field is scorable or not scorable. If the&nbsp;<strong>ass_type</strong>&nbsp;is ‘select’, then the field should be scorable. The field needs to be either 1 for scorable or 0 for not scorable.</li>\r\n	<li>Leave&nbsp;<strong>risk_scorable</strong>&nbsp;as 0.</li>\r\n	<li>If the field uses ‘Select’ as its&nbsp;<strong>ass_type</strong>&nbsp;then it will have an listId. The listId relates to various drop down boxes for that field. It also links to the<strong>nh_list</strong>&nbsp;table.</li>\r\n	<li>Enter the service ID you are working on into the&nbsp;<strong>ser_id</strong>&nbsp;field. You can find a list of services form the&nbsp;<strong>nh_service table</strong>. E.g. enter 110 into<strong>ser_id</strong>&nbsp;for Rushmoor.</li>\r\n	<li>Select all the new records that you created in the table and copy the&nbsp;<strong>ass_fieldName</strong>&nbsp;of each.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the&nbsp;<strong>nh_assess_results table</strong>&nbsp;and Select Object Browser</li>\r\n	<li>Click on \'Add a field\'.&nbsp;Paste the name of the&nbsp;<strong>ass_fieldName</strong>&nbsp;that you just copied into the Name text box. Select a type e.g. text / varChar etc. select the desired Length and click OK.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat this process for all records created in&nbsp;<strong>nh_assessment table.</strong>&nbsp;E.g. copy each&nbsp;<strong>ass_filedName</strong>&nbsp;and add it to the&nbsp;<strong>nh_assess_results table.</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Copy all records that you just added in the&nbsp;<strong>nh_assess_results table</strong>&nbsp;into the<strong>&nbsp;nh_assess_results_old table</strong>&nbsp;(this is the backup table).</li>\r\n	<li>To make the assessment tab&nbsp;<strong>work fully</strong>&nbsp;at least one filed has to be&nbsp;<strong>scorable</strong>, (even if the field is blank and does not appear on the assessment tab)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3><strong>If you have used a \'Select\' as an ass_type&nbsp;</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If you have used ‘Select’ for the&nbsp;<strong>ass_type</strong>&nbsp;field in the&nbsp;<strong>nh_assessment table</strong>&nbsp;you will need to create the various drop down options that are needed. These options can be created in the<strong>&nbsp;nh_list table</strong>.</li>\r\n	<li>Enter a name into the&nbsp;<strong>listName</strong>&nbsp;field. The first thing that you need to do is create a parent field which all the other options are linked to. E.g. Outcome Depression).</li>\r\n	<li>Create a new record (for the drop down options) and give it a&nbsp;<strong>listName</strong>.&nbsp;Decide on the order that you wish the drop downs to be viewed in. This can be done by giving the record a&nbsp;<strong>listOrder</strong>&nbsp;.</li>\r\n	<li>You must the link that record to the parent record by entering the parent’s&nbsp;<strong>listId</strong>&nbsp;number into the&nbsp;<strong>listParent&nbsp;</strong>field.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Download the attached word document for all the steps and screen shots relating to each step.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Contents of the Document:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open MySQL Front -&gt; load database</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the nh_assessment table from the list of tables</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter an ass_name (used to display the text for the field names on the html assessment page)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choose Details or Summary drop down from ass_used_for field, depending on where you want to create the assessment (either under details or summary tab)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 5</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choose the ass_type (text, select, radio, textarea, textareasmall, textareamedium) This will be used on the HTML page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 6</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Give the Record an ass_fieldName. This will be used in the nh_assess_results &amp; nh_assess_results_old tables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 7 (Optional)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ass_description is used to provide a tooltip</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 8</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choose an ass_order. This is the order that you wish the risk assessment form to be in, which field comes first etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 9&nbsp; (optional)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you wish to add a questionnaire to any field, you will need to enter the questionnaire id number into the questionnaire_id field.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You must then decide whether the field is scorable or not scorable. If the ass_type is ‘select’, then the field should be scorable. The field needs to be either 1 for scorable or 0 for not scorable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 11</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leave risk_scorable as 0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 12</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the field uses ‘Select’ as its ass_type then it will have an listId. The listId relates to various drop down boxes for that field. It also links to the nh_list table.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 13</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter the service ID you are working on into the ser_id field. You can find a list of services form the nh_service table. E.g. enter 110 into ser_id for Rushmoor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 14</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Select all the new records that you created in the table and copy the ass_fieldName of each.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 15</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Select the nh_assess_results table and Select Object Browser</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 16</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Click on Add a field .&nbsp; Paste the name of the ass_fieldName that you just copied into the Name text box. Select a type e.g. text / varChar etc. select the desired Length and click OK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 17</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Repeat this process for all records created in nh_assessment. E.g. copy each ass_filedName and add it to the nh_assess_results table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 18</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy all records that you just added in the nh_assess_results table into the nh_assess_results_old table (this is the backup table).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>If you have used a \'Select\' as an ass_type&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have used ‘Select’ for the ass_type field in the nh_assessment table you will need to create the various drop down options that are needed. These options can be created in the nh_list table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter a name into the listName field. The first thing that you need to do is create a parent field which all the other options are linked to. E.g. Outcome Depression.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a new record (for the drop down options) and give it a listName.&nbsp; Decide on the order that you wish the drop downs to be viewed in. This can be done by giving the record a listOrder .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You must the link that record to the parent record by entering the parent’s listId number into the listParent field.</p>\r\n','updating-risk-assessment',18,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:47:51','2016-09-20 18:47:51',NULL),(85,32,'Get Active / Registered Users','Created\r\n40 months ago by Andy Elsbury\r\nUPDATE','<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Change the dateLastLogin in the WHERE clause to correct date</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>#Number of active (logged in in last 90 days) and not deleted users</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SELECT COUNT(*), nh_team.team_name FROM nh_user&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LEFT JOIN nh_team ON nh_user.team_id = nh_team.team_id</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WHERE dateLastLogin &gt;= \'2012-12-12 00:00:00\' AND live = 1 AND grp_id != 4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GROUP BY nh_team.team_name;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>#Number of registered (and not deleted) users</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SELECT COUNT(*), nh_team.team_name FROM nh_user&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LEFT JOIN nh_team ON nh_user.team_id = nh_team.team_id</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WHERE live = 1 AND grp_id != 4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GROUP BY nh_team.team_name;</p>\r\n','get-active-registered-users',19,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:49:44','2016-09-20 18:49:44',NULL),(86,32,'DataTransfer - SWLSTG','Created\r\n42 months ago by Andy Elsbury\r\nUPDATE','<h2>Data Transfer Script&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>There are Two files to be copied to SWLSTG WAMP server,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>curlScript.php</li>\r\n	<li>db.php</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two files that need to be on our end,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>document_save.php</li>\r\n	<li>setup.php</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The patch file needs to be run on their database to create the database to check if files have been transferred.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;transfer-docs-database-creation.sql</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>curlScript.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Contains the curl information to post over to document save on our side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The folder address that it is currently pointing to needs to change to correct SWLSTG folder, so that it can loop through the correct folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &nbsp;destination folder needs to change to our server and folders were we wish to transfer the information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>db.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Contains the connection to the database, this needs to be change so that it connects with the clients WAMP database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>document_save.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Receives the post data from the curl script on our end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Needs to be saved in the same location to where the transferred files are going to be placed on our end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Creates the correct folder structure to receive the files.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Needs to be saved in the same location to where the transferred files are going to be placed, so they end up in the right directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>transfer-docs-database-creation.sql&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>creates the database structure, needs to be run on clients WAMP server&nbsp;</p>\r\n','datatransfer-swlstg',20,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:51:02','2016-09-20 18:51:02',NULL),(87,32,'Patient Locking FAQ','Created\r\n59 months ago by Dave Bould','<p><strong>How do you turn on patient locking for a service?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Patient locking has to be turned on by a&nbsp;<strong>MAYDEN</strong>&nbsp;superuser. &nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Access the \"Tags Manager (Mayden Only)\" option in the \"Super Users\" panel.</li>\r\n	<li>Tick the \"Can set patient lock tags\" checkbox.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;You then need to assign locking permissions to one of the service\'s Superusers:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Find the service Superuser\'s &nbsp;username in the \"Users\" section of the \"Super Users\" panel</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the \"Keys / Permissions\" tab.</li>\r\n	<li>Create a new group for patient locking.</li>\r\n	<li>Tick the \"Can set patient lock tags\" permission.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the service Superuser to this group.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;This user will be the person responsible for locking and unlocking patients, so it\'s usually the service\'s lead.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How do you lock a patient?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Find the patient you wish to lock.</li>\r\n	<li>Navigate to the \"Patient Registration\" page.</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the \"Patient Details\".</li>\r\n	<li>Near the bottom of the patient details form, there is now a heading called \"Locking\".</li>\r\n	<li>Set the radio button to \"Locked\" and save the patient details.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Who can see a locked patient?&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When a patient is locked, only people with locking permissions, or that patient\'s currently allocated therapist can access the patient. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This includes being able to find the patient in the patient search and accessing the actual record itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Locked patients in reports</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Giving permission for the service Superuser to assign locking permissions</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>?&nbsp;</p>\r\n','patient-locking-faq',21,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:52:28','2016-09-20 18:52:28',NULL),(88,32,'Client Access & Authentication','Created\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury','<h3>Access &amp; Authentication</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The data export system to download the latest export dump is accessed via&nbsp;<strong>https://*.iaptus.nhs.uk/export&nbsp;</strong>(where * is the iaptus service name).&nbsp; The&nbsp;<strong>system can only be accessed via N3</strong>&nbsp;since the Internet proxy interferes with the security steps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two way SSL certification is used to authenticate exports.&nbsp; IAPTus already has Server-&gt;Client authentication via the https certificate issued by Thawte to IAPTus - this is the same technology used by on-link banking and e-commerce etc to authenticate servers.&nbsp; Client-&gt;Server authentication is much less common and although all the tools are available in Windows, they are much less common.&nbsp; To make SSL certificates work, a number of components are required.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A Certificate Authority (CA) - this is a trusted body used to create SSL certificates.&nbsp; Mayden is its own CA on behalf of our clients.&nbsp; We issue them certificates and they must trust our CA in order to use them,</li>\r\n	<li>A Private Key (PK) - this is held only by the client and is like a password for the certificate.&nbsp; They send a Certificate Request to us based on this PK.&nbsp; In Windows, this PK is normally dealt with via the OS so the user is not directly aware of it, however a Certificate from our CA will only work on the machine used to generate the Certificate Request because the PK also needs to be present.</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate Request (CR) - this is the file generated by the client to our CA specifying the Certificate they want.&nbsp; Mayden reviews these before issuing the Certificate</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate - this is the file sent automatically by the client with each request to our server.&nbsp; It will only work if the PK is also present on the client machine and if it has been issued by our CA.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Critically, the export process will only work if all the above has been correctly setup.&nbsp; The initial stage of authentication where the incoming Certificate is validated against our CA is done by Apache, if this authentication fails then the user will get an error in their browser related to SSL failure and the request will fail at that point.&nbsp; If Apache validates the certificate then it will reach the PHP code and a further double check is done by ExportAuth.class.php.&nbsp; This class also validates the Common Name (CN) of the certificate against the specific database &amp; service they want to download from.&nbsp; This prevents a client from one service using their valid certificate to download data from another.&nbsp; The presence of these checks also makes development more of a challenge as there is no backdoor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TODO - we need to set up a CA on the demo site or internally for development purposes.</p>\r\n','client-access-authentication',22,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:54:55','2016-09-20 18:54:55',NULL),(89,32,'Code, files and database tables','Created\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury','<h3>Iaptus code files</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The data dump export files (.zip) are produced overnight by means of a cron job on the live servers.&nbsp; Cron jobs are configured in cron/cron-config.php (array key \'CronExports\'). The cron/cron.php script calls cron/class/CronExports.class.php which loops round the database connections and calls the actual exports code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The actual code for the exports is in html/inc/class/export.&nbsp; There are three files required to generate exports. (TODO - this has changed a bit. Need to amend this....).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Export.class.php&nbsp; This is the main export code and handles retrieval of data from the db and conversion into the requested download format, it also generates the download scripts for the client</li>\r\n	<li>ExportAuth.class.php&nbsp; This class handles the connection authentication process</li>\r\n	<li>ExportConfig_*.class.php&nbsp; These files contain different versions of the export data, configuration is very simple in the form of select queries that generate the required data for download</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The export data is made available to download in the requested format (xml, csv, nsv[null-separated value using nulls instead of comma]).&nbsp; All the configuration comes from the ExportConfig class.&nbsp; This is interrogated by the Export class to provide the requested download.&nbsp; As well as downloading data, the export system call also generates the sample code required by the client to automate the process.&nbsp; This code includes lists of tables and database schemas and so will change for each version of the ExportConfig file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Iaptus database tables</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The iaptus database includes two tables related to client advanced exports,&nbsp;<strong>nh_export_users</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>nh_export_log</strong>. The first table nh_export_users contains export user authentication details that tie in with the client-&gt;server certificate common name. See Access &amp; Authentication and New client setup sections for further details. The second table records client access to the exports data downloads (request parameters, export user id, date and time of request etc).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Location of exports .zip files</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The data dump zip files produced by the exports are stored in the relevant document folder for the service on the live server e.g.&nbsp;<strong>/var/www/html/iaptus/documents/documentService101/exports&nbsp;</strong>where \"101\" is the service_id of the relevant iaptus service. We keep the three most recent exports files for each service on the live servers.</p>\r\n','code-files-and-database-tables',23,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:56:34','2016-09-20 18:56:34',NULL),(90,32,'Care Pathway DB Structure Explained','Created\r\n73 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n72 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nUPDATE','<h3>Relevant tables</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>nh_actions - The table stores all care pathway movements history</li>\r\n	<li>nh_stage_process - All possible movements are stored in this table.</li>\r\n	<li>nh_stage - Details of all care pathway stages</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>How these tables work together</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"file:///C:/DOCUME~1/Richard/LOCALS~1/Temp/moz-screenshot-1.png\" /><img alt=\"carePathwayDB\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/care_pathway/carePathwayDB.JPG\" style=\"height:427px; width:492px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Important table columns explained</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;nh_stage_process</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>id - the process id</li>\r\n	<li>pathway_id - the service id (or ser_id)</li>\r\n	<li>stage_from - stage move from</li>\r\n	<li>stage_to - stage move to</li>\r\n	<li>type - type of movement. Acceptable values are\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\'end\' - use this if discharge the referral</li>\r\n		<li>\'fwd\' - use this if move into a waiting stage</li>\r\n		<li>\'bak\' - use this if move backwards to early steps of the care pathway</li>\r\n		<li>\'def\' - use this for anything else.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>live - active (=1) or not active (=0)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>nh_actions</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>id - the move action id. Each time a patient is moved in the care pathway, this id is increased by 1.</li>\r\n	<li>date - the actual date/time the patient has been moved.</li>\r\n	<li>entry_date - the system date/time the user has performed this action.</li>\r\n	<li>pat_id - the patient id</li>\r\n	<li>epis_id - the referral / treatment episode id</li>\r\n	<li>pathway_id - service id ( or ser_id)</li>\r\n	<li>action_order - the care pathway actions are sorted by this column starts from 0.</li>\r\n	<li>notes - any notes attached to this action</li>\r\n	<li>user_id - the user who performed this action.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>th_id - the therapist id that the user is working on behalf of when moving the patient.</li>\r\n	<li>assigned_th - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>type - note used</li>\r\n	<li>live - indicates whether the action is active (=1) or not (=0)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>nh_stage</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>id - the stage id</li>\r\n	<li>ser_id - the service id</li>\r\n	<li>code - the abbreviation name of the stage.</li>\r\n	<li>stage_from_note - used when two stages have the same name. This note will be added in front of the stage name. Please note, it\'s better to never give two stages the same name if possible.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>stage_shotcut - if needs to appear (=yes) under the \"Find Patients from\" section on the left navigation bar. (Note spelling error in column, shotcut not shortcut)</li>\r\n	<li>stage_order - the column used for sorting.</li>\r\n	<li>stage_intensity - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>stage_type - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>stage_group - always use the keyword \'CARE\'</li>\r\n	<li>short_name - used in the care pathway tool but don\'t think it\'s referenced anywhere in the system.</li>\r\n	<li>title - the stage name</li>\r\n	<li>description - the stage name can have html elements in. e.g. if the stage name is too long, you can add a&nbsp;<br />\r\n	tag to make it appear in two lines. This may have to be changed in the reskin.</li>\r\n	<li>step - the step number. e.g. Not specified = 0, Low intensity = 2, High Intensity = 3.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>type - the type of the stage, acceptable values are\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\'end\' - this is a discharge stage</li>\r\n		<li>\'wait\' - this is a waiting stage</li>\r\n		<li>\'process\' - this is a normal processing stage</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>mdsReference - link to the nh_mdsReference table for a valid Minimum Dataset entry. Please note, this is only applicable for discharge stages.</li>\r\n	<li>max_stay - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>first_warning - No. of days till the stage will be flagged up in yellow color.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>second_warning - No. of days till the stage will be flagged up in red color.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>therapist_allocation_required - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>first_stage - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>final_stage - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>main_form_id - only used by Newham. Indicates the main questionnaire needs to be completed at this stage.</li>\r\n	<li>view_form_id - not sure</li>\r\n	<li>view_form2_id - not sure</li>\r\n	<li>diagnosis - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>help_notes - not used.</li>\r\n	<li>org_id - the original origramy id generated by the drawing.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>live - active (=1) or not (=0)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','care-pathway-db-structure-explained',24,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:58:14','2016-09-20 18:58:14',NULL),(91,32,'Global settings','Created\r\n72 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n71 months ago by Tomas Cerney\r\nUPDATE','<p>There are settings in the nh_global table which are specific to a service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some of these are configuration settings such as the ids for the nh_list items for the service and the ids for the start of the care pathway. Others are settings to turn various optional features on or off for a service such as SMS messages or automatic postcode lookup.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;For an explanation of the various globals (many of which are no longer used in the code but which may still be present in the databases) see the<strong>spreadsheet on Google docs named \'IAPTus Globals</strong>\'. This is shared to the Mayden group so if you can\'t see it you need to check you are properly included in the Mayden group.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Database structure</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;Id</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;var_name</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;var_value</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;var_type</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;ser_id</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;live</th>\r\n			<th>&nbsp;notes</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;auto-incrementing id field</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;the name of the global. When IAPTus runs on every page load code is included which turns var_name and var_value into php globals. For example if var_name is \'refProcessId\' there will be a $refProcessId available for use in IAPTus code with the assigned value from var_value</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;the variable value. It is a varchar field. See the Google docs spreadsheet for more information.</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>&nbsp;the type of variable. At time of writing there are 4 valid types which tell the set-up script what to do when setting values for a new service being created.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>listParentId - global identifies a list from the nh_list table (listId number). Set up script will complete it automatically for new service when nh_list items created.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;listId - global identifies a list item from the nh_list table (listId number). Set up script will complete it for new service automatically when nh_list items created.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>copyValue - this global will be created for a new service and will have the same var_value as the generic service (ser_id 6).</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>copyName - this global will be created for the new service when the setupscript runs but the var_value will not be copied so will need to be set manually.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;the service id taken from nh_service column.</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;flag for archiving a global (ie. turning it off). 1=live, 0=archived</td>\r\n			<td>&nbsp;[not used - was intended to act as a comments field in the demo db originally]</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','global-settings',25,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 18:59:23','2016-09-20 18:59:23',NULL),(92,32,'Creating new globals checklist','Created\r\n73 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n72 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nUPDATE','<p>If you create a new global - or amend a global - there are a number of steps to be taken to make sure the global is documented and included correctly for all new services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note - speak to Steve / other developers before creating new globals. We are trying to reduce the number of nh_global settings required by the code and in many cases there is an alternative solution.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Add details about the new global into the&nbsp;<strong>IAPTUS globals spreadsheet</strong>&nbsp;in the Mayden Health Google Docs.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the global is&nbsp;<strong>added to nh_global on demo for the \"Generic\" service</strong>&nbsp;which is&nbsp;<strong>ser_id 6</strong>.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Choose the correct var_type value for the new global to tell the setup script what it should do with it when creating a new service.<strong>T</strong>he four types are&nbsp;<strong>copyValue, copyName, listParentId and listId.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>listParentId -&nbsp;</strong>global identifies a list from the nh_list table (listId number). Set up script will complete it automatically for new service when nh_list items created.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>listId -&nbsp;</strong>global identifies a list item from the nh_list table (listId number). Set up script will complete it for new service automatically when nh_list items created.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>copyValue</strong>&nbsp;- this global will be created for a new service and will have the same var_value as the generic service (ser_id 6)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>copyName</strong>&nbsp;- this global will be created for the new service when the setupscript runs but the var_value will not be copied so will need to be set manually for the new service appropriately</p>\r\n','creating-new-globals-checklist',26,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:00:40','2016-09-20 19:00:40',NULL),(93,32,'Investigating Exports Problems','Created\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nLast Updated\r\n9 months ago by Oliver Musgrove-Wethey','<p>Exports problems divide into two basic types. Problems with the production of the .zip files for download and problems with the client trying to access the .zip files for download.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Error Logging</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>When errors occur during the cron process to produce the export data .zip files messages appear in the relevant server cron logs for the service. (There are also basic log messages generated on each successful run of the cron - see CronExports.class.php for details).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When errors occur when trying to access and download the zip files you can get errors in different types of logs.Where there is an initial error when the Apache server tries to validate the certificate against our CA errors can be found in the ssl access logs for the relevant iaptus service. Where the error occurs in the second layer of authentication within the php code (see ExportAuth.class.php), for example because the common name doesn\'t match an export user entry within the nh_export_user table, then errors can be found in the php-fpm logs for the relevant service on the live servers (or the configured apache error logs locally).</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;Bournemouth 301 Redirect Issues</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;In Bournemouth if you go to *.iaptus.nhs.uk/export it will redirect you to *.iaptus.nhs.uk/export<strong>/</strong>&nbsp;however the IP in the background will be different. If you access /export/ with a trailing slash it will send you to 192.168.63.7 however if the 301 redirect occurs it will take you to 192.168.63.4.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Limitations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The current export system assumes the client is only downloading data for one service, this is because the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts overwrite any pre-existing data with new as part of the process.&nbsp; The current workaround is to manually create the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts to avoid overwriting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The export process does require Apache config changes to handle the incoming certificate process.&nbsp; All sites on ivnode1 have been created with this in place.&nbsp; Older sites on node1 may not have this in place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The system only works when the connection to the server is direct.&nbsp; The RSA/Blackshield gateway break this, less obvious is that many of the migrated IAPTus sites are actually being proxied from node1 to ivnode1 as this avoids DNS hassle when moving sites around, this proxy also breaks the authentication and will need migrating properly before exports will work.&nbsp; Typing \'host CLIENT.iaptus.nhs.uk\' on the node1 command line will tell you where the DNS currently points and then you need to see if this is different to where the actual code is for that site.&nbsp; node1 is 10.191.213.132, ivnode1 is 10.191.213.140.</p>\r\n','investigating-exports-problems',27,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:01:54','2016-09-20 19:01:54',NULL),(94,32,'Detecting Issues With Invalid Characters in XML files','Created\r\n12 months ago by Oliver Musgrove-Wethey\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Dave Bould','<p>Note: These are Linux commands. If you are running from Windows or Mac you may need to adjust accordingly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create your own PKCS12 certificate - follow this guide\r\n	<pre>\r\n&lt;a href=&quot;https://crm.mayden.co.uk/library/4197/&quot; target=&quot;&quot;&gt;https://crm.mayden.co.uk/library/4197/&lt;/a&gt;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Convert this to a PEM file\r\n	<pre>\r\n$ openssl pkcs12 -export -in &quot;path.p12&quot; -out &quot;newfile.pem&quot;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Get a copy of the PEM version of the mayden CA file (attached)</li>\r\n	<li>Add your common name to the nh_export_users table and check you can access the\r\n	<pre>\r\nhttps://[SERVICE].iaptus.nhs.uk/export/</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Download the XML file locally. (either run this out of hours or off a test site)\r\n	<pre>\r\n$ wget --certificate=[PERSONAL_CERT.pem] --ca-certificate=[server.pem] -O ~/Downloads/autodownloads/sessions_`date +&quot;%Y%m%d-%H%M%S&quot;`.xml &quot;https://[SERVICE].iaptus.nhs.uk/export/index.php?export=[TABLE]&amp;amp;version=5&amp;amp;type=mssxml&quot;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>install&nbsp;xmlstarlet\r\n	<pre>\r\n$ apt-get install&amp;nbsp;xmlstarlet</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>run\r\n	<pre>\r\n$ xmlstarlet validate --err [XML_FILE_PATH]</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>This should give you a human readable reason why the XML file is valid or not.</p>\r\n','detecting-issues-with-invalid-characters-in-xml-files',28,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:02:26','2016-09-20 19:02:26',NULL),(95,32,'Key Generator (NHS Number Lookup)','Created\r\n44 months ago by Louis Rickman\r\nLast Updated\r\n19 months ago by Louis Rickman\r\nUPDATE','<p>This is the instruction to generate keys requested by each IAPTus service for the ITK NHS Patient Lookup service to work. &nbsp;<br />\r\nThis should only be done after 4 pm during the day.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Key Files on live servers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ivnode14</strong>&nbsp;- /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/itk_smsp/Keys.class.config.php<br />\r\n<strong>ivnode7</strong>&nbsp;-&nbsp;/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/itk_smsp/Keys.class.config.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Key Generator</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>URL -&nbsp;http://www.iaptus.co.uk/itk_key_gen/index.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Login Credentials</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>username: mayden</li>\r\n	<li>password: you can guess</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Steps to follow</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1) Open Penguinet and connect to node1.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2) Type in</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n(For Bracknell)\r\ncd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/itk_smsp\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>rm Keys.class.config.bak.php cp -p Keys.class.config.php Keys.class.config.new.php cat Keys.class.config.new.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(For Bournemouth) cd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/itk_smsp rm Keys.class.config.bak.php&nbsp; cp -p Keys.class.config.php Keys.class.config.new.php cat Keys.class.config.new.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This should remove the backup and make a copy of the Key file. It should display the content of the Key file and you should take a note of the constant that has been defined with the highest service ID number</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3) Run the Key Generator and you should have some new constants defined at the bottom of the&nbsp;<strong>Constants to be added under all other defined constants</strong>&nbsp;section as well as some new references added at the bottom of the&nbsp;<strong>References &amp; Keys to be added within get() under all other references</strong>&nbsp;section.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4) Go back to command line and type in the following command to open the Key file.&nbsp;<strong>Please note that it is very important you DO NOT change any existing contents in the Key file or existing services may no long be able to access the ITK service.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnano Keys.class.config.new.php</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy and paste all newly defined constants under all other constants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy and paste all newly added references under all other references within the get() method. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Save changes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5) Type in the following command to make sure there is no parse error.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n\r\n&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>php Keys.class.config.new.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6) Type in the following commands to finish the change</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n\r\n&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>mv Keys.class.config.php Keys.class.config.bak.php mv Keys.class.config.new.php Keys.class.config.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7) Run deploy-cluster in both Bournemouth and Bracknell from build script to ensure changes are copied to all nodes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8) Open a live site has ITK Patient Lookup service turned on and make sure it still works (you will get \"There was an issue processing your request, please try again or contact customer support\" if there is an issue with the change when using the lookup service)</p>\r\n','key-generator-nhs-number-lookup',29,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:04:02','2016-09-20 19:04:02',NULL),(96,32,'Bulk Addition of GP Practices','Created\r\n40 months ago by Louis Rickman\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Nina Barlow\r\nEDIT','<p>This guide will allow you to add a load of GP practices to a demo or live site within 30 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Go to the&nbsp;<strong>nh_national_practice&nbsp;</strong>table on the Global database and search based on the search criteria given to you. Usually this will be an area code but could be something like all the organisation codes starting with \'H81\'. If its the area code then you will need to filter by the ro_code or ha_code.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Filter and see how many results you get back</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>&nbsp;Run the query below and replace where appropriate</p>\r\n\r\n	<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;SELECT pr_id, [you_ser_id] as ser_id, organisation_code as pr_code, NULL as nickname, 0 as updated, now() as updated_by, 0 as local_entry, 1 as live\r\nFROM nh_national_practice WHERE organisation_code like [your query string]&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>This will give you the results in the format that you need to add them to the&nbsp;<strong>nh_gp_serPractice&nbsp;</strong>table which is in the local database. Copy the rows as SQL and put them in to the query editor</li>\r\n	<li>Do a find and replace, replacing&nbsp;<strong>nh_national_practice&nbsp;</strong>with&nbsp;<strong>nh_gp_serPractice</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you have the local database selected and run the query. Check the front end to see if the practices have been added.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that above does not consider closed practices or add associated GPs to nh_gp table, however it has been left for reference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The nh_national_practice and nh_national_gp tables should have been updated recently, if not then the data will not be up to date.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create a list of insert statements for nh_gp_serPractice using the following query, replacing the service id and parent_organisation_code.\r\n	<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;SELECT concat(&amp;quot;INSERT INTO `nh_gp_serPractice` (`pr_id`, `ser_id`, `pr_code`, `nickname`, `updated_by`, `updated`, `letter_send_mode`, `local_entry`, `live`) VALUES (&amp;quot;,\r\npr_id,&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;,184,&amp;quot;,\'&amp;quot;,organisation_code,&amp;quot;\',NULL, 0,\'&amp;quot;, now(),&amp;quot;\', 1,0,1);&amp;quot;)\r\nFROM nh_national_practice WHERE parent_organisation_code = \'11H\'\r\nAND (close_date = \'0000-00-00\'\r\n    OR close_date &amp;amp;gt;&amp;amp;nbsp;&lt;/code&gt;now());</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the resulting rows to query editor and run. &nbsp;This will add the practices to nh_gp_serPractice.</li>\r\n	<li>The GP process which follows strips out any apostrophes from organisation_name to enable easier insertion. &nbsp;Suggest that the following is run beforehand to identify which names are amended\r\n	<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;SELECT pr_id, organisation_code, organisation_name\r\nFROM nh_national_gp\r\nWHERE parent_organisation_code IN\r\n(SELECT pr_code FROM nh_gp_serPractice WHERE ser_id = 184)\r\nAND (left_parent_date = \'0000-00-00\'\r\nOR left_parent_date &amp;amp;gt; now())\r\n  AND organisation_name LIKE &amp;quot;%\'%&amp;quot;;\r\n&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Create a list of insert statements for nh_gp using the following query, replacing the service id (note that this uses the data just added to nh_gp_serPractice, so the above must be run first).\r\n	<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;SELECT\r\nconcat(&amp;quot;INSERT INTO `nh_gp` (`local_pr_id`, `ser_id`, `gp_code`, `gp_surname`, `gp_initials`, `updated_by`, `updated`, `pr_code`, `live`)\r\nVALUES (&amp;quot;,p.local_pr_id,&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;,184,&amp;quot;,\'&amp;quot;,organisation_code,&amp;quot;\',\'&amp;quot;,LEFT((REPLACE(organisation_name,&amp;quot;\'&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;&amp;quot;)),(POSITION(\' \' IN (REPLACE(organisation_name,&amp;quot;\'&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;&amp;quot;))))-1),&amp;quot;\',\'&amp;quot;,RIGHT((REPLACE(organisation_name,&amp;quot;\'&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;&amp;quot;)),(LENGTH((REPLACE(organisation_name,&amp;quot;\'&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;&amp;quot;)))-POSITION(\' \' IN (REPLACE(organisation_name,&amp;quot;\'&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;&amp;quot;))))),&amp;quot;\', 0,\'&amp;quot;, now(),&amp;quot;\', \'&amp;quot;,parent_organisation_code,&amp;quot;\',1);&amp;quot;)\r\nFROM nh_national_gp gp&lt;/code&gt;\r\n&lt;code&gt;JOIN nh_gp_serPractice p ON gp.pr_id = p.pr_id\r\nWHERE parent_organisation_code IN\r\n(SELECT pr_code FROM nh_gp_serPractice WHERE ser_id = 184)\r\nAND (left_parent_date = \'0000-00-00\'\r\n    OR left_parent_date &amp;amp;gt; now());&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the resulting rows to query editor and run. &nbsp;This will add the GPs to nh_gp</li>\r\n	<li>If necessary, manually re-add any apostrophes in names identified in step 3.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','bulk-addition-of-gp-practices',30,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:05:18','2016-09-20 19:05:18',NULL),(97,32,'How to: Vagrant virtual machine for IAPTus','Created\r\n23 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury\r\nASK ROSS TO UPDATE','<p>Initial Software Installation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Download and install Vagrant - <a href=\"https://www.vagrantup.com/downloads.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.vagrantup.com/downloads.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Windows Users</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Windows users need to install Git (if you don\'t already have ssh for windows) - <a href=\"http://git-scm.com/download/win\" target=\"_blank\">http://git-scm.com/download/win</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It\'s highly recommended that Windows users get ConEmu to make the windows command line much more user friendly - <a href=\"https://code.google.com/p/conemu-maximus5/wiki/Downloads?tm=2\" target=\"_blank\">https://code.google.com/p/conemu-maximus5/wiki/Downloads?tm=2</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tortoise SVN Users:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TURN OFF TORTOISE ICON CACHE (TortoiseSVN-&gt;settings-&gt;Icon Overlays-&gt;Status Cache set to None). If you don’t it causes conflicts with file locking on the synced folders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vagrant It</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SVN:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check out IAPTus Vagrant from <a href=\"https://mayden.slsapp.com/source/iaptus-vm/\" target=\"_blank\">https://mayden.slsapp.com/source/iaptus-vm/</a> to a location of your choice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Git:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clone https://github.com/may-den/vagrant-vms</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll need to keep this working copy around for when there are updates but it’s not where you will install your Vagrant box. Once it’s checked out you will find a folder for each of the projects containing versions of the vagrant boxes:-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; php55</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Vagrantfile</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; bootstrap</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Vagrantfile and the bootstrap folder are what you need to set up a given vagrant VM.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy the Vagrantfile and entire bootstrap folder into a new folder wherever you wish to have the Virtual Machine installed and run from, for example copy them into C:Vagrant BoxesCentos 6.5 IAPTus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From a command prompt in that folder (AS ADMINISTRATOR/SUDO):</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant plugin install vagrant-vbguest</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then once installed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant up</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once it\'s finished you can use the command</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant ssh</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>to ssh into the machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Set up your Git ssh keys at this point!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://help.github.com/articles/generating-ssh-keys/\" target=\"_blank\">https://help.github.com/articles/generating-ssh-keys/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have your ssh keys for Git in place-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In your home directory you will find scripts to set-up iaptus or the postroom code, you can run one or both depending on what you need. For example to set up iaptus:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>./build-iaptus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will checkout/update develop and build it. Mac/Linux users may find they have to chmod +x ./build-iaptus first to add executable permission to the file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Common Commands</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Starting the VM<br />\r\nvagrant up</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stopping the VM</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant halt</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suspending the VM</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant suspend</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Resuming the VM<br />\r\nvagrant resume</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other Commands</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant destroy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This command will remove your VM. It will not remove any files from the synced folders, so your working copies are safe. HOWEVER it will lose any custom databases you have so back these up first. This command is the best course of action when anything goes wrong with your VM, use vagrant up and ./run-me afterwards to quickly rebuild everything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>./run-me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When ssh’d into the vagrant box this is a link from your home directory to /vagrant/bootstrap/postbuild.sh, a script that checks out/updates a copy of IAPTus trunk and then runs the build file on trunk and any branches it finds. This should be run after the initial build or after rebuilding the VM.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advanced Commands</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant reload --provision</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will halt the vagrant box and start it again, but it will run the vagrant setup script to make sure everything is setup as required. This is the command to use when a new version of the Vagrantfile has been made available. However as we are creating our own vagrant base boxes it is unlikely you will need to use this command, more often you would simply update the box instead (see Updating section).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant box list</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>List the box images (with version numbers) that your vagrant is aware of</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant box update</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check version of box images and update them if needed. We are using versioned box images that we store locally so this command will get you the latest version of our box.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daily Usage</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before you shutdown your computer you should issue the vagrant halt command to gracefully shutdown the Vagrant box. You can then vagrant up again the next morning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you hibernate your computer you can leave vagrant boxes running.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Updating</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If any improvements or changes are made to the base box then you will be asked to upgrade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This involves using vagrant destroy to clear your existing box, remember that vagrant destroy will lose any custom databases you have so back these up first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To update you run 5 commands</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant destroy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant box update</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant up</p>\r\n\r\n<p>vagrant ssh</p>\r\n\r\n<p>./run-me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Branch Tool</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a branch tool in the IAPTus tools folder, to use it type ./createbranch.sh and follow the instructions. It will create a new working copy from the working copy you run it from so it will maintain changes you have made locally. This can be useful, or mean you need to do a revert before you start using it. We recommend using the branch tool to create and remove all branches you need.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Customisation<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you find there are settings or software that you need but isn’t needed in the base box that everyone uses then you can add custom commands (e.g. sudo yum -y install my_fav_text_editor) to the customconfig.sh file in the bootstrap folder. This file will get run when you use ./run-me. Mac/Linux users may need to chmod +x /vagrant/bootstrap/customconfig.sh to add executable permission to the file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>KNOWN GOTCHAS AND ISSUES:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have problems mounting your shared folders, this could be because you have updated the software on your virtual machine. To fix this, run the following command:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;sudo /etc/init.d/vboxadd setup&lt;/code&gt;&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>If this command fails, try to run the following command, then run the above command again:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;sudo yum install kernel-devel-2.6.32-504.23.4.el6.x86_64&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>If this results in an error stating that the package was not found, you must download the package manually. This can be done via:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nwget ftp://mirror.switch.ch/pool/4/mirror/scientificlinux/6.6/x86_64/updates/security/kernel-devel-2.6.32-504.23.4.el6.x86_64.rpm</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>or any equivalent URL that will return the correct rpm. Then run:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsudo rpm kernel-devel-2.6.32-504.23.4.el6.x86_64.rpm --install</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>to install the package. Then run the vboxadd setup command above, exit and reload your vagrant machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some windows machines have visualization turned off by default in the BIOS, if you cannot ssh into your box during vagrant up, restart your laptop, enter BIOS and ensure that visualization is on, then do vagrant up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you dared to put a space in your Windows account username then the vagrant plugin command will fail. To remedy this we have to tell Vagrant to store it\'s settings somewhere without spaces. To do this we run two commands in the Windows command prompt:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IF NOT EXIST C:VagrantHome MKDIR C:VagrantHome</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SET VAGRANT_HOME=C:VagrantHome<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Windows users may find that VBoxManage or ssh have not been added to the windows path automatically, these may need adding manually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you use vagrant suspend or hibernate your computer it will suspend the clock in the VM until it resumes but don’t worry as when you vagrant ssh into the VM it automatically runs a command to update the time and date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you/Windows mess around with the Virtual Machine files then Vagrant may bail out when you try to vagrant destroy. If this happens then delete the .vagrant folder for the vagrant machine and vagrant up again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If it’s gone really badly wrong you may need to find the Virtual Box VM files and remove them (you’ll know you need to do this because the error you get will tell you where the files it can’t remove/move/rename are located).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have zombie VMs or need to control a VM that\'s gone rogue you can use VBoxManage to control them:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>List running machines (returns name and UUID):</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nVBoxManage list runningvms</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stop running VMs by \"hibernating\" them</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nVBoxManage controlvm  savestate</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Poweroff running VMs</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nVBoxManage controlvm  poweroff</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Use ACPI in an ACPI-aware guest OS (preferable to poweroff for graceful shutdown of guests)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nVBoxManage controlvm  acpipowerbutton .</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have issues with the networking (hibernating the host OS often makes it fail you can try issuing this VBox command (replacing VM name with the name of the VM):</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&amp;nbsp;VBoxManage modifyvm &quot;VM name&quot; --natdnshostresolver1 on</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>TIPS FOR WINDOWS USERS</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are using our Vagrant virtual machines on a Windows host operating system there are some complications worth noting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;Git on Host or Guest?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A lot of Windows users have found that git commands run very slowly from the guest machine (e.g. 10 seconds for git status). It appears to be something to do with the shared drives on the Windows box as git commands run at normal speed if a repo is created outside the shared drives. If you find speed an issue from the guest box it is usually better to use git (e.g. gitBash) from the Windows host machine. This has the added advantage of not destroying your .ssh keys when you vagrant destroy as they reside on the Windows box (but must be copied to new Vagrant machines - see below).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>gitBash and .bashrc</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are using gitBash from Windows it is a good idea to create a&nbsp;<strong>.bashrc file in your users directory</strong>&nbsp;and put a script there run the ssh-agent automatically to avoid the need to keep entering your ssh key password every time you communicate with gitHub during the session. Instead you will just enter it once at the start of the gitBash session - see&nbsp;<a href=\"https://help.github.com/articles/working-with-ssh-key-passphrases/#platform-windows\" target=\"_blank\">https://help.github.com/articles/working-with-ssh-key-passphrases/#platform-windows</a>for full details.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open a Windows terminal and create the file:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd C:Users\r\ntouch .bashrc</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Then open the .bashrc file in an editor and paste in the following code:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nenv=~/.ssh/agent.env\r\n\r\nagent_is_running() {\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; if [ &quot;$SSH_AUTH_SOCK&quot; ]; then\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; # ssh-add returns:\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; #&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 0 = agent running, has keys\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; #&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 1 = agent running, no keys\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; #&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 2 = agent not running\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; ssh-add -l &amp;gt;/dev/null 2&amp;gt;&amp;amp;1 || [ $? -eq 1 ]\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; else\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; false\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; fi\r\n}\r\n\r\nagent_has_keys() {\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; ssh-add -l &amp;gt;/dev/null 2&amp;gt;&amp;amp;1\r\n}\r\n\r\nagent_load_env() {\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; . &quot;$env&quot; &amp;gt;/dev/null\r\n}\r\n\r\nagent_start() {\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; (umask 077; ssh-agent &amp;gt;&quot;$env&quot;)\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; . &quot;$env&quot; &amp;gt;/dev/null\r\n}\r\n\r\nif ! agent_is_running; then\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; agent_load_env\r\nfi\r\n\r\n# if your keys are not stored in ~/.ssh/id_rsa or ~/.ssh/id_dsa, you\'ll need\r\n# to paste the proper path after ssh-add\r\nif ! agent_is_running; then\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; agent_start\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; ssh-add\r\nelif ! agent_has_keys; then\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; ssh-add\r\nfi\r\n\r\nunset env</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>This script may need amending with the correct path to your ssh keys as described in the comments if your ssh keys aren\'t at&nbsp;<strong>~/.ssh/id_rsa</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then close and reopen the terminal, or type the commands below to make sure the script takes effect.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;source ~/.bashrc&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;Git and line endings</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Git tries to be helpful with automatic line endings conversion and different operating systems (see&nbsp;<a href=\"http://adaptivepatchwork.com/2012/03/01/mind-the-end-of-your-line/\" target=\"_blank\">http://adaptivepatchwork.com/2012/03/01/mind-the-end-of-your-line/</a>&nbsp;for more details). However this can cause problems if we are working on files and git repos using gitBash and IDEs in Windows, but then seeking to copy files such as Vagrant files to linux virtual machines and run them there. Our coding standards should specify project level .gitattributes files to avoid problems, however it is also a good idea to set git config settings to make sure that line endings are converted to Linux LF endings (in accordance with PSR-2) when committed to a repository and NOT converted back to CRLF when checking out working copies of the file on your Windows machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can check your gitconfig setting for automatic line conversion by typing</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ngit config core.autocrlf\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>If the result of this command is not \"input\" then edit the global git config as follows (which should have the desired effect as long as there isn\'t a conflicting project specific git config setting to override it)</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ngit config --global core.autocrlf input</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>You can check this has worked by repeating the first command. The input setting should ensure that any stray CRLFs are converted to LF when you commit to the repository, but git does not convert from LF to CRLF when you checkout files to your working directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should also look at your editor / IDE settings and make sure they are set to LF line endings too.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Even with all these settings done correctly there are sometimes problems on existing repositories where mixed line endings already exist</strong>which can confuse the autocrlf functionality. When setting up a new Vagrant box you usually copy the Vagrantfile and bootstrap folder to the shared drive, then open a terminal and \"vagrant up\" from that folder.&nbsp;<strong>It is worth navigating to the folder where you are about to \"vagrant up\" and opening the files in your editor and checking what line endings it says are used in the files</strong>. You can then manually change them to LF if they are showing as CRLF before you run the \"vagrant up\" command.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>git ssh keys</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>When you vagrant up for the first time the automated process attempts to run iaptus_postbuild.sh and postroon_postbuild.sh to clone iaptus and the postroom and set the local project environment up. In order to do this you need to have your ssh keys for Git available - however these are on your Windows box and it isn\'t easy to pass them through.&nbsp;<strong>You should therefore copy the keys across and then run the postbuild.sh scripts again afterwards</strong>. The following commands (with the necessary path adjustments) should achieve this:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From Windows terminal copy from user folder to the shared drive so they will be available on Vagrant machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncp /c/Users/.ssh/id_rsa /c/Vagrantboxes/iaptus56/id_rsa\r\ncp /c/Users/.ssh/id_rsa.pub /c/Vagrantboxes/iaptus56/id_rsa.pub</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Then do vagrant ssh to open terminal to the Linux machine and move the keys to the appropriate folder with the necessary file permissions:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd /vagrant/</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n(you should now see your keypairs)\r\nmv id_rsa ~/.ssh/id_rsa\r\nmv id_rsa.pub ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub\r\n\r\nsudo chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa\r\nsudo chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>You can now go to the /vagrant/bootstrap folder and run iaptus_postbuild.sh and postroom_postbuild.sh successfully.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>git hooks</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are committing from gitBash (or another program) from the Windows end then the githooks won\'t run properly and you may get error messages. In order to fix this you need to make the git-hooks script available to Windows and add it to the Windows %PATH% environment variable. To do this open a Vagrant terminal :</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To make sure you have git hooks installed properly on the Linux machine (should happen with the postbuild and composer commands) go to the iaptus repo and type:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ngit hooks\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>You should then get a message saying \"Git hooks ARE installed in this repository\". (If you don\'t then there could be problems with your composer.json or iaptus_postbuild.sh hasn\'t run properly).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then navigate to ~/.composer/vendor/git-hooks and copy the git-hooks to /vagrant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd ~/.composer/vendor/bin/\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>cp git-hooks /vagrant/git-hooks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Find the file in Windows through file explorer and copy it to somewhere that is on your Windows PATH environment variable, or update the Windows PATH ev to include it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To see the content of the PATH environment variable&nbsp; type the following in a terminal in Windows:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\necho %PATH%\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>To edit the path environment variable in Windows through the gui interfaces see&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.computerhope.com/issues/ch000549.htm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.computerhope.com/issues/ch000549.htm</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','how-to-vagrant-virtual-machine-for-iaptus',31,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:07:43','2016-09-20 19:07:43',NULL),(98,32,'Enabling Webforms - Adding / Editing custom image and/or email settings','Created\r\n49 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n13 months ago by Louis Rickman\r\nCHECK','<p>The webforms system allows each service to have their own logo appear at the top when the patient opens a webform and to have custom text for the email sent to the patient.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To enable a custom logo:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Save the logo file as logoSERVICE_ID.png e.g. logo26.png. It must be a PNG and the size should be no higher than 100px to look right.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Upload it to the images folder on the webforms server - webforms/public/css/themes/iaptus/images/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If a logo for the service exists in this folder it will be used, otherwise it will use the default logo file (logo.png)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To&nbsp; add/edit custom email content:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Either add if needed or edit the existing entry in the webforms table email_templates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the link to the form, put the following placeholder&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/library/959/%FULLLINK%\">%FULLLINK%</a>&nbsp;</strong>wherever this may be</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The entry needs the service id and then any of the fields that are filled in will replace the default text, so you can just add a new subject and this will be used while the rest of the email will still use the default settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is usually best to create a html file locally to test it looks as expected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To turn it on via the Control Panel</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whilst logged into the relevant&nbsp;<strong>iaptus</strong>&nbsp;live site go the Questionnaires sub-section of the superuser Control Panel and set the entry for enabling the electronic sending of questionnaires via email to \'enabled\' and save.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE</strong>: If you don\'t have access you can still do all of this offline. See Andy, Louis, Dave or Matt to upload this if you don\'t have access.</p>\r\n','enabling-webforms-adding-editing-custom-image-andor-email-settings',32,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:09:02','2016-09-20 19:09:02',NULL),(99,32,'Adding new webform','Created\r\n50 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n23 months ago by Louis Rickman\r\nCHECK','<p>In IAPTus codebase using&nbsp;<strong>tools/webforms/questionnaireXmlExport/convertToWebform.php</strong>&nbsp;create a new phtml file for the questionnaire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will be the page you create in step 1 in the webforms section of this article.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to check the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check for typos and encoding issues and check layout. Correct if needed.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove any questions that are free text boxes. Webforms does not support these. Tell one of the account managers which ones you are removing so they can liaise with client.</li>\r\n	<li>If the questions that you removed were labelled as part of a numbered sequence you will need to change the questions in that section so numbering is sequential</li>\r\n	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>$this-&gt;answerData&nbsp;</strong>array needs to be sequentially numbered. If you have removed any of the questions then you will need to make sure that they are. It will be sequentially numbered per question. (It will make sense when you see what the conversion script generates)</li>\r\n	<li>If the questionnaire has section headers and these do not appear you need to add them manually.</li>\r\n	<li>Look for&nbsp;<strong>&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;</strong>&nbsp;as particular templates add this and it makes webforms display with unnecessary spacing</li>\r\n	<li>Check the webform is valid html - (i.e. parse through a validator)</li>\r\n	<li>If you want to double check or are experiencing problems with the webform, make sure that the format is similar to one that works already.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Webforms:</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Add new webform phtml file to&nbsp;<strong>applicationmodulesdefaultviewsscriptswebform</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Add webform id to if($formId != 300 &amp;&amp; $formId != 301 &amp;&amp; $formId != 302 etc in public static function initial in&nbsp;<strong>libraryIaptusApiRequest.php</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Add entry to switch ($webformSession-&gt;iaptus_id_webform) in sessionAction() function in&nbsp;<strong>applicationmodulesdefaultcontrollersWebformController.php</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Add entry to $grouping = array with svy_id and question range in&nbsp;<strong>applicationmodulesdefaultcontrollersWebformController.php</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>IAPTus:</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Add entry to array in RemoteForms.class.php::availableWebforms() with svy_id and name.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','adding-new-webform',33,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:10:05','2016-09-20 19:10:05',NULL),(100,32,'GP Update Procedure','Created\r\n66 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n40 months ago by Matt Ellis','<ol>\r\n	<li>Tell the support staff that they should not update any practices using the National Practice Manager till you have finished the update</li>\r\n	<li>Check you have the latest version of the nh_national_practice and nh_national_gp tables by downloading them from a live global database</li>\r\n	<li>Download the latest Practice, GP, and Branches zip files from&nbsp;<a href=\"http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/gppractice\" target=\"_blank\">http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/gppractice</a><br />\r\n	Direct links (will probably break at some point):<br />\r\n	Practices:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/epraccur.zip\" target=\"_blank\">http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/epraccur.zip</a><br />\r\n	GPs:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/egpcur.zip\" target=\"_blank\">http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/egpcur.zip</a><br />\r\n	Branches:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/ebranchs.zip\" target=\"_blank\">http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/data-files/ebranchs.zip</a></li>\r\n	<li>Extract the files and rename them to&nbsp;<br />\r\n	&nbsp;practiceImport.csv<br />\r\n	&nbsp;gpImport.csv<br />\r\n	&nbsp;branchesImport.csv\r\n	<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Copy them into the csv folder in the practice import tool -&nbsp;<strong>iaptustrunktoolspracticeUpdatepractice_update_toolcsv</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Open the&nbsp;<strong>iaptustrunktoolspracticeUpdatepractice_update_tool</strong>&nbsp;through a browser and go to Import latest practices from CSV files</li>\r\n	<li>Tick all the check boxes and click Submit</li>\r\n	<li>Wait<br />\r\n	<em>Time&nbsp;passes...</em></li>\r\n	<li>Look<br />\r\n	<em>The tool has finished processing. There is a cave to the south west.</em></li>\r\n	<li>sw<br />\r\n	<em>You enter the cave. It is pitch black. You are likely to be eaten by a grue.</em></li>\r\n	<li>Now your nh_national_practice and nh_national_gp tables contain the latest data, your nh_national_bak and nh_national_gp_bak contain the previous version. These all need to be uploaded to demo, live globals, staging, and any other IAPTus versions kicking about.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','gp-update-procedure',34,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:11:18','2016-09-20 19:11:18',NULL),(101,32,'Verification Status code mapping table','Created\r\n48 months ago by Richard He\r\nLast Updated\r\n48 months ago by Richard He\r\nUPDATE FOR NEW MDS CODE FOR MHSDS','<p><strong>What\'s displayed in the boarding card and used as hypercube reports filters</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Default status (NHS Number Validation hasn\'t been done):&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;Number present but not traced</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Verified: &nbsp;<strong>Number present and verified</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Request has timed out: &nbsp;<strong>Number present but not traced (request has timed out)</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Tried to verify but couldn\'t find a match:&nbsp;<strong>Trace attempted - No match found</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Tried to verify but found multiple matches (results can\'t be returned according to IG):&nbsp;<strong>Trace attempted - multiple match found</strong></li>\r\n	<li>If NHS number is blank (this is only set in the batch&nbsp;verification&nbsp;process):&nbsp;<strong>Invalid, NHS Number is blank</strong></li>\r\n	<li>If NHS number is invalid (this is only set in the batch verification process):&nbsp;<strong>Invalid, NHS Number is Invalid</strong></li>\r\n	<li>There was something unexpected happened (e.g. service was down on our end):&nbsp;<strong>Invalid, unknown reason</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>NHS Number verification status column in the IDB - Person export</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Number present but not traced</strong>&nbsp;:&nbsp;&nbsp;02 - Number present but not traced</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Number present but not traced (request has timed out)</strong>&nbsp;: 02 -&nbsp; Number present but not traced&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Number present and verified:&nbsp;</strong>01 - Number present and verified</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Trace attempted - No match found</strong>&nbsp;: 04 - Trace attempted - No match or multiple matches found</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Trace attempted - multiple match found:&nbsp;</strong>04 -&nbsp;Trace attempted - No match or multiple matches found</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Invalid, NHS Number is blank:&nbsp;</strong>04 -&nbsp;Trace attempted - No match or multiple matches found</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Invalid, unknown reason:&nbsp;</strong>04 -&nbsp;Trace attempted - No match or multiple matches found&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','verification-status-code-mapping-table',35,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:12:42','2016-09-20 19:12:42',NULL),(102,32,'Add new dataset','Created\r\n56 months ago by Richard He\r\nLast Updated\r\n55 months ago by Richard He\r\nUPDATE FOR TREATMENT TYPES CHANGES','<p><strong>!For developers only!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>in the TreatmentTypes class&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Define a new constant in the format of DATASET_[&nbsp;<strong>**datasetName**</strong>&nbsp;]</li>\r\n		<li>Add this constant to $_permittedDatasets &amp; &nbsp;$_datasetNames</li>\r\n		<li>Add a new Treatment type and associate it with the new dataset in the&nbsp;_init() method.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;In the SessionExtraFields class\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Create a new private method with a name _setSessMultiple<strong>[**datasetName**]</strong>Fields() to define clinical session level fields for this dataset. The&nbsp;easiest&nbsp;way to do this is by looking at the way it has been done on one of the existing dataset.\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>You must define a EventType field which will be used in the Diary. i.e. the Consultation medium field from the IAPT service.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>You must define a EventPurpose field which will be used in the Diary. i.e. The Appointment Purpose field from the IAPT service.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>You can define a field that controls other fields. E.g. the Attendance field will make other selected fields mandatory depending on selected options. For details. please refer to the Attendance field from the PCLN dataset.</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Add the fieldKey of your EventType field into the&nbsp;getEventTypeDataItemKey() method.</li>\r\n		<li>Add the fieldKey of your EventPurpose field into the getEventPurposeDataItemKey() method.</li>\r\n		<li>Add the fieldKey of your Attendance field into the getAttendanceDataItemKey() method</li>\r\n		<li>You cannot define a new Location field or the diary will not work in the expected way. The IAPT location field must always be used.</li>\r\n		<li>To make Outcome graph work, ???working in progress???</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>In the SessConfig class\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Define the displaying layout of your fields in the configureDisplayFields() method.&nbsp;</li>\r\n		<li>Define the editing layout of your fields in the&nbsp;configureEditFields() method.&nbsp;</li>\r\n		<li>Define the outcome layout of your fields in the&nbsp;configureSessInfoFields() method for fields aren\'t scores.</li>\r\n		<li>Define the outcome layout of your fields in the&nbsp;configureOutcomeScoreFields() method for fields are scores.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>For the nh_fields &amp; nh_fieldsSer table (all those changes need to be in a patch file)\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>all fields defined in the&nbsp; SessionExtraFields&nbsp; class will need to be added into the nh_fields table.&nbsp;\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>The fieldName attribute from the defined field will need to go into the `field` column in the nh_fields table.</li>\r\n			<li>\'nh_sessMultiple\' is always the one needs to go into the `table_desc` column in the nh_fields table.</li>\r\n			<li>The fieldTitle attribute from the define field will need to go into the `desc` column in the nh_fields table. However you&nbsp;<strong>must</strong>&nbsp;also add a prefix which is&nbsp;preferably&nbsp;the name of the dataset at the from of each defined field. The prefix is only something needs to go into the nh_fields table but not added to the `fieldTitle` attribute.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>Add all new fields into the nh_fieldsSer table and link them to the new dataset (`type` = new dataset) and make fields mandatory where applicable. Note all new fields with a `table_desc` of \'nh_sessMultiple\' will need to go into the nh_fieldsSer table no matter they are mandatory or not.</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Report changes\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>The new dataset does not have any reports by default, you will need to add all existing Demographic &amp;&nbsp;Referral&nbsp;level reports to your new dataset. This can be determined by nh_new_reports.category_id IN (1,2).&nbsp;</li>\r\n		<li>For all other reports, we can\'t use what we already have but to create new ones. The two we need straight away are the Activity by No. of Sessions report and the Activity by No. of Referrals report. To add a new report, you also need to add the correlated filters/ group by&nbsp;options. Here is how\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>Add your new reports in the `nh_new_reports` table. The category id needs to be 3 if they are session level reports</li>\r\n			<li>Add group by option filter in the `nh_new_reports_filters` table. Make sure the `isGroupFilter` column is set to 1 or they won\'t work.</li>\r\n			<li>Add 4 child level group by option filter in the `nh_new_reports_filter_children` table. Use existing group by options as examples.</li>\r\n			<li>Link appropriate group by options to the new filters in the `nh_new_reports_group_by_link` table. Note that you always need to link the special group by option \'Session Multiple special group by option (ID 107) to the new group by option, this will automatically work with your new fields.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>Link appropriate filters for the report you add in the `nh_new_reports_selectedFilters` table. Again, always link the \'Sess Multiple Fields (ID 148)\' filter which will add all applicable fields as filters automatically.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>Add your reports into the `nh_new_reports_service` table and link them to your new dataset only. If this report is applicable for all service, use ser_id 0.&nbsp;</li>\r\n			<li>Followed by all those sql changes, there is also a code change required in RunReportLibrary.class.php. Activity by No. of sessions add the new report id next to where id 52 is. For Activity by No. of Referrals, add the new report id next to where id 53 is.</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li><strong>A quick way to add the two session level reports is by duplicating what\'s in the \'20120228-cyp-froehling-reports.sql\' patch for your new dataset, but don\'t forget the required code changes.</strong></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n','add-new-dataset',36,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:14:11','2016-09-20 19:14:11',NULL),(103,32,'Data Import Tool','Created\r\n73 months ago by Richard He\r\nLast Updated\r\n60 months ago by Steve Exley','<p>This tool has been built to achieve fast and reliable data importation from our new clients. The data doesn\'t have to be in a standard format as long as it has identical data fields compare to IAPTus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The actual code in svn is located in&nbsp;<strong>tools/importTool</strong>. You will need a new database with name \"Data_Import\" (databases with other names wouldn\'t work) created before running all the DB patches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following steps will guide you through the whole process,</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Step 1 – Prepare the Data</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>You need to make sure the LIVE site for this service has already been setup before continuing.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Login to the DEMO site and go to Care Pathway Tool (Mayden Only).</li>\r\n	<li>Check with Claire and make sure she isn\'t currently changing the care pathway on demo site (just for this service) as well as making sure there are no changes currently sitting on demo site that are not expected to go live. &nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><strong>ONLY CONTINUE IF NO. 3 IS CHECKED</strong>. &nbsp;Add a new stage called&nbsp;<strong>IMPORTED DATA</strong>&nbsp;and link it as specified below,\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Referral Received -&gt; IMPORTED DATA</li>\r\n		<li>IMPORTED DATA -&gt; Discharge Planning (Step 0)</li>\r\n		<li>Archive the link \"Referral Received\"-&gt; \"IMPORTED DATA\". P.s. this is because we don\'t want people to use this link any more, it\'s just a link built for imported data.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Apply those care pathway changes to the live system using Care Pathway Tool. (Import the .sql file).</li>\r\n	<li>Dump the following tables from LIVE site to the new database \"Data_Import\" .&nbsp;Make sure tables with the same name are always dropped before importing new ones.\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>nh_actions (structure only)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_global (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_gp (structure only)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_gp_practice (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_list (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_service (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_stage (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_stage_process (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_team (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_therapist (structure and content)</li>\r\n		<li>nh_user (structure and content)</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Download the Data to be imported (normally uploaded to their live system and attached to Dummy Patient) and put it into an encrypted drive (by TrueCrypt).</li>\r\n	<li>In most cases, the data is spited into three levels: Patient, Referral and Contacts. You will need to duplicate the document first as quite a few changes will be made to the document.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the duplicated document. For each level of data, change the heading names in the document to match column names in table “RawPatientData”, “RawReferralData” or “RawContactData”. Please make sure the patient identifier in the old system is always mapped to “local_pat_id” (Please note we can only import the data if we have unique identifiers to each patient). For any data you think are necessary to be imported but not available in any of the Raw tables. Please contact Richard He for more information. Remove all unused columns in the documents (otherwise the import would fail) and import the data into the appropriate table using the Import Excel function in MySQL Front.</li>\r\n	<li>Up until now, we should have “RawPatientData”, “RawReferralData” and “RawContactData” contains the imported data.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Additional preparation may be needed</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If no available therapist data on contact level (who did each contact)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DO THIS: create a new&nbsp;<strong>therapist</strong>&nbsp;user called “Data Import” on the LIVE system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AND THIS: In&nbsp;<strong>RawContactData</strong>,<strong>&nbsp;</strong>replace&nbsp;<strong>clin_id&nbsp;</strong>using the created<strong>&nbsp;th_id&nbsp;</strong>(from nh_therapist table) and&nbsp;<strong>user_id&nbsp;with the&nbsp;equivalent&nbsp;user_id (id from nh_user table)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Step 2 – Map the Data (USE Firefox, DIDN\'T TEST IN OTHER BROWSERS)</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Open the browser and go to web directory to your working copy.</li>\r\n	<li>The first thing you would see is what shows in figure -1. It asks you to select the service you are about to do the data import.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"file:///C:/DOCUME~1/Richard/LOCALS~1/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image002.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"dataImportF1\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/data_import/dataImportF1.jpg\" style=\"height:67px; width:181px\" /><br />\r\nFigure - 1</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The mapping table in figure -2 should be visible to you after a service is selected.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"file:///C:/DOCUME~1/Richard/LOCALS~1/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image004.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"dataImportF2\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/data_import/dataImportF2.jpg\" style=\"height:174px; width:601px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure - 2</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The drop down on the very top is the stage you need to select in order to automatically generate the care pathway data. This includes 4 automated actions</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>REG -&gt; Referral</li>\r\n		<li>Referral -&gt; IMPORTED DATA</li>\r\n		<li>IMPORTED DATA -&gt; Discharge Planning (discharged patient only)</li>\r\n		<li>Discharge Planning -&gt; Actual Discharge stage (discharged patient only).&nbsp;Please note that “Actual Discharge stage” should be selected in the mapping table like figure – 3 shows. Please always use Step 0 options or the ones without the prefix “Step”</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"file:///C:/DOCUME~1/Richard/LOCALS~1/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image006.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"dataImportF3\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/data_import/dataImportF3.jpg\" style=\"height:236px; width:601px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure - 3</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mapping table compares the old entry and the new list Item automatically using Soundex match, which means quite a few items may have been mapped automatically. However, you will need to click the “Mark as checked” button on those items to do a double check, or otherwise if you change the mapping manually, the Mapping Tool would assume it has already been checked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IMPORTANT: Depending on the quality of data we receive, sometimes a referral with discharge date doesn\'t have a discharge reason,&nbsp; for referrals like this or vice versa (has discharge reason but no discharge date) we need to fix the data in database before proceed&nbsp; any further by changing both columns to NULL.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Once all items are mapped across, the system will through up a message telling you everything is ready and the “Convert Data” button on the very top of the page should be ready to use.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>IMPORTANT:&nbsp;</strong>There seems to be a bug that the \'convert data\' button is available while there are still things haven\'t been mapped (caused by&nbsp;inconsistent&nbsp;ajax requests). Always reload the page and search for the keyword \'<strong>Value in DB missing\'.&nbsp;</strong>If you couldn\'t find it, it\'s safe to click the \'convert data\' button, otherwise there must be data that haven\'t been mapped, please map them first. A proper code fix needs to be done later.</li>\r\n	<li>Double check the “Treatment Stage” drop-down next to the “Convert Data” button and make sure it’s selected. Then click “Convert Data”.</li>\r\n	<li>The convert process will take approximately 30 seconds to 1 minute depending on amount of data. A confirmation message will appear on the page when the conversion is completed.</li>\r\n	<li>You may want to add some generic data if they have some of the fields missing. e.g.&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>UPDATE&nbsp;ReadyContactData SET&nbsp;sess_time = @SessionTime;</li>\r\n		<li>UPDATE&nbsp;ReadyContactData SET&nbsp;sess_app_purpose= @SessionAppPurpose;</li>\r\n		<li>UPDATE&nbsp;ReadyContactData SET&nbsp;sess_clin_time= @SessionClinTime;</li>\r\n		<li>UPDATE&nbsp;ReadyContactData SET&nbsp;sess_type= @SessionType;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Step 3 – Testing and Completion</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>All data should have been converted at this stage. The mapping tool should now become a checking tool where you can see the converted results as shown in figure – 4.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"file:///C:/DOCUME~1/Richard/LOCALS~1/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image008.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"dataImportF4\" src=\"https://beta-crm.mayden.co.uk/upload/library/iaptus/data_import/dataImportF4.jpg\" style=\"height:263px; width:497px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure - 4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Make sure you go through all messages appeared on the page as there are things like&nbsp;<strong>GP Practices</strong>&nbsp;could have a few entries missing which will need to be added into the&nbsp;<strong>LIVE</strong>&nbsp;system manually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you run through the mapping results, the numbers with Green color are definitely correct whereas the ones with Red color need attention. It’s not necessary that Red is definitely wrong (it will be red if multiple items in the old dataset were mapped into a single new option) but a quick check wouldn’t do any harm.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If there are any problems you found, such as one mapping option was wrong in the first place. You will need to close the browser and start from&nbsp;<strong>Step 2</strong>. Don’t panic, all mapped entries have been saved. You only need to correct the mistakes not start all over again.</li>\r\n	<li>Once you are certain all data has been converted correctly, at last we need to do the following things to complete the data import,\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Replace&nbsp;<strong>user_id</strong>&nbsp;from&nbsp;<strong>nh_actions</strong>&nbsp;with user id for “Data Import”.</li>\r\n		<li>Export data from the following tables into a Excel Document,\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>ReadyPatientData</li>\r\n			<li>ReadyReferralData</li>\r\n			<li>ReadyContactData</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Export data from the following tables into a SQL File,</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>nh_actions</li>\r\n			<li>nh_gp</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If there are any live data already in the system or our client has started using the system,&nbsp;USE THE CENTRAL DATABASE TO DO YOUR TEST IMPORT UNTILL ALL DATA IS VERIFIED.&nbsp;Otherwise, import the data directly back into the actual live database.</li>\r\n		<li>Optimize all tables\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>Optimize table nh_patient;</li>\r\n			<li>Optimize&nbsp;table nh_treatment;</li>\r\n			<li>Optimize&nbsp;table nh_session;</li>\r\n			<li>Optimize&nbsp;table nh_actions;</li>\r\n			<li>Optimize&nbsp;table nh_gp;</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Please find at least another person to check the data.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other useful queries:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyPatientData set pat_id = (pat_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyReferralData set pat_id = (pat_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyReferralData set treat_id = (treat_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyContactData set pat_id = (pat_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyContactData set epis_id = (epis_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update ReadyContactData set sess_id = (sess_id + 100000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update nh_actions set id = (id + 100000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update nh_actions set pat_id = (pat_id + 10000);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>update nh_actions set epis_id = (epis_id + 10000);</p>\r\n','data-import-tool',37,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:15:28','2016-09-20 19:15:28',NULL),(104,32,'Exports','Created\r\n43 months ago by Steve Exley\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury','<h3>This section can be deleted once copied and amended version has been approved. Keeping for the moment just for reference until new CAE main section checked and approved.&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Database Exports for clients</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The IAPTus export process is designed to allow clients access to their data via an automated process.&nbsp; This is done via a set of pre-defined tables which IAPTus generates on the fly for download to the client.&nbsp; Most clients have MSSQL databases which they want to import into and the process is geared up for this although it could be extended to support other end systems if required.&nbsp; The pre-defined tables are all configured via PHP and can be tailored to individual client needs - although modifying existing configs is dangerous.&nbsp; Read on to understand this and how to safely make changes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Client Documentation&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The latest copy of the client documentation is kept on the Mayden Google Drive under IAPTus-&gt;exports-&gt;webportal.&nbsp; There is also another copy in the docs folder of IAPTus on SVN.&nbsp; There are three client documents to maintain.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The schema document, this must reflect what appears in the export tables for the relevant export version.</li>\r\n	<li>The export process summary, this outlines the process for setting up exports from IAPTus into MSSQL on 2005 or 2008 server.</li>\r\n	<li>The certificate process, this outlines in detail the client certificate setup needed to for each client machine to authenticate with IAPTus</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Data Export Overview</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The data export system is accessed via https://*.iaptus.nhs.uk/export.&nbsp; The system can only be accessed via N3 since the Internet proxy interferes with the security steps.&nbsp; The actual code for the exports is in html/inc/class/export.&nbsp; There are three files required to generate exports.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Export.class.php&nbsp; This is the main export code and handles retrieval of data from the db and conversion into the requested download format, it also generates the download scripts for the client</li>\r\n	<li>ExportAuth.class.php&nbsp; This class handles the connection authentication process</li>\r\n	<li>ExportConfig_*.class.php&nbsp; These files contain different versions of the export data, configuration is very simple in the form of select queries that generate the required data for download</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The export data is made available to download in the requested format, currently only XML is supported, CSV would be an easy development.&nbsp; All the configuration comes from the ExportConfig class.&nbsp; This is interrogated by the Export class to provide the requested download.&nbsp; As well as downloading data, the export system call also generate the sample code required by the client to automate the process.&nbsp; This code includes lists of tables and database schemas and so will change for each version of the ExportConfig file.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Authentication</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Two way SSL certification is used to authentication exports.&nbsp; IAPTus already has Server-&gt;Client authentication via the https certificate issued by Thawte to IAPTus, this is the same technology used by on-link banking and e-commerce etc to authenticate servers.&nbsp; Client-&gt;Server authentication is much less common and although all the tools are available in Windows, they are much less common.&nbsp; To make SSL certificates work, a number of components are required.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A Certificate Authority (CA) - this is a trusted body used to create SSL certificates.&nbsp; Mayden is it\'s own CA on behalf of our clients.&nbsp; We issue them certificates and they must trust our CA in order to use them,</li>\r\n	<li>A Private Key (PK) - this is held only by the client and is like a password for the certificate.&nbsp; They send a Certificate Request to us based on this PK.&nbsp; In Windows, this PK is normally dealt with via the OS so the user is not directly aware of it, however a Certificate from our CA will only work on the machine used to generate the Certificate Request because the PK also needs to be present.</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate Request (CR) - this is the file generated by the client to our CA specifying the Certificate they want.&nbsp; Mayden reviews these before issuing the Certificate</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate - this is the file sent automatically by the client with each request to our server.&nbsp; It will only work if the PK is also present on the client machine and if it has been issued by our CA.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Critically, the export process will only work if all the above has been correctly setup.&nbsp; The initial stage of authentication where the incoming Certificate is validated against our CA is done by Apache, if this authentication fails then the user will get an error in their browser related to SSL failure and the request will fail at that point.&nbsp; If Apache validates the certificate then it will reach the PHP code and a further double check is done by ExportAuth.class.php.&nbsp; This class also validates the Common Name (CN) of the certificate against the specific database &amp; service they want to download from.&nbsp; This prevents a client from one service using their valid certificate to download data from another.&nbsp; The presence of these checks also makes development more of a challenge as there is no backdoor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TODO - we need to set up a CA on the demo site or internally for development purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>New client setup</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>When a new client requests access or an existing client needs changes.&nbsp; First ensure they have the latest documentation from the Google Drive.&nbsp; This will take them through the requirements and onto making their certificate request.&nbsp; Clients with Windows Server 2003 usually can\'t make CRs due to a quirk in Windows where the menu item is missing.&nbsp; In these cases Mayden will make the request for them although this means Mayden holds the PK and presents a small risk allowing us to impersonate them when accessing the export system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CA is access via the cmd line on iaptusvnode14 in /var/www/ca</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Normal Process:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n# Upload the CR to /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/client.csr\r\ncd /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/\r\n# Read &amp;amp; review the certificate request, specifically check the CN field contains the clients org name, this must be unique for each CSR\r\nopenssl req -noout -text -in request.csr\r\n\r\n# Generate a certificate\r\nopenssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in client.csr -out client.crt\r\n\r\n# Check the Certificate has worked\r\nopenssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt\r\n\r\n# Download the client.crt file to send to client\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Windows 2003 Server Process</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd /var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/\r\n# Make a PK\r\n# Choose a passphrase first, you will need to provide this to the client later - over the phone\r\nopenssl genrsa -des3 -out client.key 2048\r\n\r\n# Make a Certificate Request from the Key\r\n# Use the clients org name as the Common Name (CN) in the request\r\nopenssl req -new -config ../../openssl.cnf -key client.key -out client.csr \r\n\r\n# Generate a Certificate from the Request\r\nopenssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in client.csr -out client.crt\r\n\r\n# Generate a combined Certificate and Private Key file - use the same passphrase as before\r\nopenssl pkcs12 -export -clcerts -in client.crt -inkey client.key -out client.p12\r\n\r\n# Check the combined file\r\nopenssl pkcs12 -info -in client.p12\r\n\r\n# Download the client.p12 file to send to client - do not send the passphrase electronically, provide it over the phone instead\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>If you see the error:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nSign the certificate? [y/n]:y\r\nfailed to update database\r\nTXT_DB error number 2&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Then there has been a collision in the CA index file. Find the X509 path in /var/www/ca/index.txt, and match using the \'Subject\' line (you will need to modify it) from the certificate request (the part sent in the Orbit ticket). It\'ll look like this:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nC=GB, ST=Wiltshire, O=Mayden, CN=MyClientSite/emailAddress=rob.andrews@mayden.co.uk&amp;nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>You\'ll need to reformat it to look like this:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n/C=GB/ST=Wiltshire/O=Mayden/CN=BSMHFT/emailAddress=Ananda.Situnayake@bsmhft.nhs.uk</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Find it in /var/www/ca/index.txt and remove the line. Once you have saved the file, re-run the \'openssl ca -cert...\' command and it should work happily.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Sending the Client Files</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The client requires a number of files for their import process.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Certificate *.crt or Certificate + Key *.p12 file</li>\r\n	<li>Our CA Certificate which they must trust as a Root CA</li>\r\n	<li>Windows Powershell script to automate download of the xml files to their local machine</li>\r\n	<li>MSSQL script to import content from XML files into MSSQL</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>These files are all put into a pre-defined ZIP file for the client to use.&nbsp; *.nhs.uk mail strips zip files so we upload them to https://welcome.iaptus.nhs.uk/CLIENT_NAME/mayden.zip&nbsp; We also remove the file once the client has completed the setup process.&nbsp; The path to this location is /var/www/html/iaptus-welcome/CLIENT_NAME/&nbsp;<strong>on iaptusvnode14</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A sample ZIP file has been attached to this page. &nbsp;We now keep the current export files in subversion, they can be found in IAPTus trunk under docs/exports/ with each version having it\'s own folder. To create a new zip you need to zip everything inside the relevant version folder. However a number of key changes are required before sending to client.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The export.ps1 file needs the correct URL for the client adding into the $source variable at the top of the file</li>\r\n	<li>The client.crt or client.p12 file needs adding alongside the ca.crt file in the certs folder</li>\r\n	<li>Version 4 on-wards - Update and remove any service specific exports (and associated comments) files from the bottom of \"export.ps1\" file</li>\r\n	<li>Version 4 on-wards -&nbsp;Update and remove any service specific&nbsp;exports (and associated comments)&nbsp;from the \"scripts/all.sql\" file</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>If the content of the exports changes, then the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts will all need regenerating to reflect the changes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Export Users - Common Name</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You also need to update the database with the common name from the certificate.&nbsp; Go to the live database and find nh_exportusers.&nbsp; Add an entry with the service_id and certificate common name.&nbsp; The common name can be found by typing: cat client.crt&nbsp;&nbsp; from the command prompt when in the client\'s certificate folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Limitations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The current export system assumes the client is only downloading data for one service, this is because the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts overwrite any pre-existing data with new as part of the process.&nbsp; The current workaround is to manually create the export.ps1 and all.sql scripts to avoid overwriting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The export process does require Apache config changes to handle the incoming certificate process.&nbsp; All sites on ivnode1 have been created with this in place.&nbsp; Older sites on node1 may not have this in place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The system only works when the connection to the server is direct.&nbsp; The RSA/Blackshield gateway break this, less obvious is that many of the migrated IAPTus sites are actually being proxied from node1 to ivnode1 as this avoids DNS hassle when moving sites around, this proxy also breaks the authentication and will need migrating properly before exports will work.&nbsp; Typing \'host CLIENT.iaptus.nhs.uk\' on the node1 command line will tell you where the DNS currently points and then you need to see if this is different to where the actual code is for that site.&nbsp; node1 is 10.191.213.132, ivnode1 is 10.191.213.140.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n','exports',38,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:19:52','2016-09-20 19:19:52',NULL),(105,32,'Database Duplication','Created\r\n55 months ago by Steve Exley\r\nLast Updated\r\n19 months ago by Matt Ellis','<p>SET @source = \'IAPTus_src\';<br />\r\nSET @target = \'IAPTus_copy\';<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n#local db<br />\r\n(<br />\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'CREATE TABLE `\',@target,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'` LIKE `\',@source,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'`;\') AS c1<br />\r\nFROM information_schema.TABLES WHERE TABLE_SCHEMA=@source AND TABLE_NAME NOT LIKE \'view_%\'&nbsp;AND TABLE_NAME NOT LIKE \'x_%\'<br />\r\nAND TABLE_NAME NOT IN (\'nh_reports\', \'nh_reports_filters\', \'nh_reports_filters_link\', \'nh_serReports\') )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UNION<br />\r\n(<br />\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'INSERT INTO `\',@target,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'` SELECT * FROM `\',@source,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'`;\') AS c1<br />\r\nFROM information_schema.TABLES WHERE TABLE_SCHEMA=@source<br />\r\nAND TABLE_NAME NOT IN (\'nh_stats\', \'nh_stats_history\',\'nh_stats_speed\',\'nh_user_activity\',\'nh_user_activity_view\',\'nh_user_activity_edit\',&nbsp;<br />\r\n\'nh_user_activity_edit\',\'nh_reports\', \'nh_reports_filters\', \'nh_reports_filters_link\', \'nh_serReports\')&nbsp;AND TABLE_NAME NOT LIKE \'view_%\'&nbsp;AND TABLE_NAME NOT LIKE \'x_%\'<br />\r\n)<br />\r\nUNION<br />\r\n(<br />\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'UPDATE&nbsp;`\',@target,\'`.`nh_global` SET `var_value` = 0 WHERE&nbsp;`var_name` = \'smsMasterswitch\'; UPDATE&nbsp;&nbsp;`\',@target,\'`.`nh_global` SET `var_value` = 0 WHERE&nbsp;`var_name` = \'remoteQuestionnairesEnabled\';\')<br />\r\n);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n#global db - if required<br />\r\nSET @source = \'IAPTus_Global\';<br />\r\nSET @target = \'IAPTus_copy\';<br />\r\n<br />\r\n(<br />\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'CREATE TABLE `\',@target,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'` LIKE `\',@source,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'`;\') AS c1<br />\r\nFROM information_schema.TABLES WHERE TABLE_SCHEMA=@source<br />\r\nAND TABLE_NAME NOT IN (\'db_patches\')<br />\r\n)<br />\r\nUNION<br />\r\n(<br />\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'INSERT INTO `\',@target,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'` SELECT * FROM `\',@source,\'`.`\',TABLE_NAME,\'`;\') AS c1<br />\r\nFROM information_schema.TABLES WHERE TABLE_SCHEMA=@source<br />\r\nAND TABLE_NAME NOT IN (\'db_patches\',\'nh_national_gp_import\',\'nh_national_practice_bak\',\'nh_national_practice_import\')<br />\r\n);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>&nbsp;- sometimes if a live database is messy and has some old global tables mixed in with the individual database tables you\'ll get errors when copying the global tables with the queries created by the global db query above having already copied the main database. In these cases you can run the queries below (substituting \"IAPTusTest_Live1\" for the appropriate db name) in between copying the main db and the global db to avoid problems:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`db_patches_global`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_fields_lookup`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_gp`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_gp_bak`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_gp_import`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_practice`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_practice_bak`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_practice_import`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_national_practice_log`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS&nbsp; `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_categories`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_filters`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_filter_category`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_filter_children`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_group_by_link`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_group_by_options`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_selectedFilters`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_selectedSubReports`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_service` ;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_subReports`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_new_reports_tabs`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_pathway_service`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_reports`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_reports_filters`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_reports_filters_link`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_rss_feed`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_searchFields`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_serReports`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_serSearchFields`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_sms_messages_status`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_tag`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_tagService`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_tag_old`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`practiceLink`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`nh_searchFields`;<br />\r\nDROP table IF EXISTS `IAPTusTest_Live1`.`practiceLink_bak`;</p>\r\n','database-duplication',39,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:21:49','2016-09-20 19:21:49',NULL),(106,32,'Automated Deploy (Bournemouth)','Created\r\n36 months ago by Steve Exley\r\nLast Updated\r\n24 months ago by Steve Exley','<p>The Deploy process in Bournemouth is identical to the Bracknell process with a few factual differences.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The path to the deploy code folder is:&nbsp;<strong>/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/build/live</strong></li>\r\n	<li>The url for the deploy test site is:&nbsp;<strong>deploy-b.iaptus.nhs.uk site</strong></li>\r\n	<li>There is no need at present to use ssh-add because there are no remote hosts in the cluster.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','automated-deploy-bournemouth',40,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:23:00','2016-09-20 19:23:00',NULL),(107,32,'Database views','Created\r\n73 months ago by Steve Exley\r\nLast Updated\r\n40 months ago by Steve Exley','<p><strong>DB Views are deprecated &amp; not in use by any clients - use exports instead</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting up db views:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The views are defined in the svn iaptus project under mysql/iaptus_views.sql.&nbsp; To change the procedures or users requires the root passwords for master and slave databases. Views can be changed by any user.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>To add or update views for a client:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Apply the iaptus_procedures.sql patch file to the relevant database on the master server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Apply the iaptus_views.sql patch file to the relevant database on the master database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Create a user and password combination - save these in the mayden kepass file</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Create a read only user on the slave database as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE USER \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\' IDENTIFIED BY \'*PASSWORD*\';</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_carepathways` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_assessments` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_medications` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_diagnosis` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_treatments` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_gps` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_gp_practices` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_users` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_sessions` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_patients` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_documents` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_results` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_result_answers` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_reference` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_disability` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_long_term_conditions` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Southwark`.`view_operational_tours` TO \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';\r\nGRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION `IAPTus_Southwark`.`strip_tags` TO&amp;nbsp; \'lreade102r\'@\'localhost\';</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>5. On the live database Add the view username to the view_user column for the service in the nh_service table.&nbsp; This is important as data in the views is limited to a specific service in this way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Log into the slave database using the user you have created and check the only tables visible are the views and that data is showing for the related service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Useful website on how to link MSSQL and MYSQL via ODBC:<br />\r\nhttp://www.codeproject.com/Articles/29106/Migrate-MySQL-to-Microsoft-SQL-Server</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is an error in the guide, in the OPENQUERY, you need to specify db name and table name:<br />\r\ne.g. SELECT * FROM&nbsp;openquery(SELECT * FROM IAPTus_Dorset.view_gps\')</p>\r\n','database-views',41,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:24:19','2016-09-21 14:15:56','2016-09-21 14:15:56'),(108,32,'BlackShield Instructions','Created\r\n46 months ago by Tim Brown\r\nLast Updated\r\n46 months ago by Tim Brown','<p><strong>Go to the Mayden Secure Portal by clicking on the link provided in your email.<br />\r\n<a href=\"https://tokens.mayden.co.uk:1752/\">https://tokens.mayden.co.uk:1752</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/PTE8ioH1-uvOdzjFlWk5nYJuksOQe1E2JPunhqzScCStTw9XwG6E6SY69aJYIExp2U3F8-fkEuomVEa1v3oXYhvNGbtr3TJ--bNHlvlIx_yPv0l3Aog9\" style=\"height:306px; width:406px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis will take you to the Email Token Self Service Site, click Request email Token to proceed.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/05lwRKOx0EO9YY0dfOpnr6MNaojS5yN9Yb3TmTi7cPD-tARpjpWRmOVt6qjQO_J-0K78XQJyx4jJ52ZXAF3pyr2-4E65P5VI9kpEzxnxNT0kWwuxqCL5\" style=\"height:163px; width:405px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nNext enter your User ID and your initial PIN in the boxes provided and click OK.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/_7I__20zV5KL_y278ZSoiT12hYa0BthZpK7CY9eqNIR6FyWqnnEz0PZq8Y7Ktgk5ObiwXXkTeiVH29dpBenTpK3FIVCzplv-dly82TSBsfkJIQqvlGBX\" style=\"height:173px; width:399px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHint - You will find your user name and Initial PIN at the bottom on the email sent to you.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/0_5ABOGzksLeEWG2OYRUP4o3J7KF-4TxjQ9Dcf7T3wV540jxP9w3jk3S9nbNk26F1N3ugGZBf6I953vyW_sXtQtn7hLzJN3wF_liSbTP2K-8LFvVBior\" style=\"height:182px; width:383px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter submitting your request you’ll receive a notification appear on your screen.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/ykmKQiKkoIBTFnh0Kj3mzvlTClUHkKfYX3Z3S4IPSEPD7w71VA2wwXKrkYdKXM2HsR8nR4vkFuZNPoPzuZrRDOHwsL2rVq7C1_PtOU8KRcrwydO5Ottd\" style=\"height:64px; width:401px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter receiving your email token code - go to second link in the first email received.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Age6t_-3Lz37pjYMucLPAuLMQQmdak_1BuKTanVJvaottxhIObkZ_j1ViD1QRazXc_Tcj20suiBSCTHNqLtTN0GEylW-lGzFYYBigYIqp_twc35ThWbi\" style=\"height:239px; width:406px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSelect the option Change PIN.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/XaJ3jE4ifH7twZBB-gqGaBE2GhMqz5SJ3f4LDOklVv3XOl_2go-CEI-OdtySVVQ0VVA3-eMCvZXvswzE3ydcOt-tKynHqOWb52hDCHMTr8B_fDwYVAl-\" style=\"height:131px; width:402px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis should display the screen below - select Email Token using the radio button.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/rEYwed0DHZd24EGR22PQmHblFRqEWFpb8y7x-hSeCiV_jJAR0rj5AWUkw0sW3igtBc9vJogfpkMzRI4Tf544vvaLWmTXxV0G_KW4V4ZirUYHZpCbaxav\" style=\"height:246px; width:385px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nNext enter your User ID and your initial PIN following by your TokenCode given to you on email and click OK.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/JhQJ3gIDEFWz2FL1KXUobOU0mH-aHEEwKkkYH1rrVB3lrUA_aM-v4FVkdcwNSQhLkg3a9_mrNtEYSE5TtwZm5MgjE_mL-xhH_A1o3BJnxByodK_RseZ-\" style=\"height:224px; width:375px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nEnter your new 4 digit PIN and verify the PIN before pressing the OK button.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/acdJvQAEcIAkyMPJDJZ-fX7IcjU7xYhoXApUUfw0BqcsA3b4q0o32J9git8F-fJE4EW2mMEkpQ3nvu0Koo24YSKD3WxaQBjHqH5zwR2nfGOcad5flinP\" style=\"height:170px; width:388px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen you’ve changed your PIN number go to your IAPTus website <a href=\"https://yourservice.iaptus.co.uk/\">https://yourservice.iaptus.co.uk</a> and enter your User name and Passcode , then click the Log on button. For example Avon\'s site is&nbsp;</strong><a href=\"https://avon.iaptus.co.uk/\">https://avon.iaptus.co.uk</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/raJaxUhigxNzwNQEeyTATQ0rGYb-I1W3u1ZMr9jK_Gm5gSdu_cPIXRcykSLxS_oNEbWGXtv-dqQtuVVMRXYqaMbK9vLPYJ0ZiRIZjXKrUwP_-ZHWgE2V\" style=\"height:271px; width:366px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hint - your Passcode is your PIN followed by the token code given to you on email. For example if your secret PIN is 2323 and the token code below was 454-5678, then your OTP would be 2323454-5678<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou will then be taken to the front page of IAPTus - enter your Username and Password and click on the Login button.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/iMGp22MfCaruuB-4-iELq8QJuDs497PA53jXwXGz_2UD0JZKeToAYMYfP0GuOBYwNBhoqn3cW5tyBRM2QtJvPnnBfBbLKewUS78ugOqkDCo3m2GCv--c\" style=\"height:254px; width:365px\" /></strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n','blackshield-instructions',42,NULL,15,'2016-09-20 19:25:23','2016-09-21 14:15:46','2016-09-21 14:15:46'),(109,32,'Turning on NHS Number (Spine Patient) Lookup for a live service','Created\r\n49 months ago by Matt Ellis\r\nLast Updated\r\n12 months ago by Erica Bradbury','<p><strong>Before turning on for the Service</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In plenty of time before you turn on spine lookup check that a key is available for the service you are turning on at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://test.iaptus.nhs.uk/smsp_keys/\">http://test.iaptus.nhs.uk/smsp_keys/</a>&nbsp;(username: mayden, password is our company password). If there is not one available then notify Matt in plenty of time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Turning it on</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Firstly, you need to find the key for the service you are about the enable Spine Lookup on from&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://test.iaptus.nhs.uk/smsp_keys/\">http://test.iaptus.nhs.uk/smsp_keys/</a>&nbsp;(username: mayden, password is our company password). Please note that the each key is associated with a single service. Make sure you get the key from the service you are going to turn Spine Patient Lookup on.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Secondly, login to the IAPTus service you wish to turn on the lookup for, and go to Mayden Control Panel. Find \'<strong>Enable or Disable spine lookup for a service using an authentication token\'&nbsp;</strong>under&nbsp;Patient Registration and enter the key you found from the previous step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Spine Patient Lookup service should now be turned on. Go to an existing patient and and click on their NHS number in the boarding card to test the verification process but DO NOT UPDATE their data. If you get \'There was an issue processing your request, please try again or contact customer support\'&nbsp;or \'Your request cannot be processed. The NHS Number lookup is currently unavailable due to maintenance\'. There is something wrong and please check the error log.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Run the batch tool to update NHS Verification status</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open a&nbsp;<strong>Screen&nbsp;</strong>session by typing in&nbsp;<strong>screen -R.&nbsp;</strong>With the -R parameter, it will try to resume a previously opened screen session, or create a new one if there is no running screen sessions. If you have multiple screen sessions opened in the past, it will give you a list of running sessions and you can choose which one to resume. Read the documentation on&nbsp;<strong>Screen&nbsp;</strong>if you need more help.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason we have to use a screen session is because we need to leave this running overnight. Closing the SSH client won\'t terminate your SSH session opened by&nbsp;<strong>Screen</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, &nbsp;Go to&nbsp;/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/tools/itk&nbsp;and run:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php spineMiniServicesBatchCaller.php http_host=[domain. e.g. mary.iaptus.nhs.uk]&nbsp;ser_id=[service id. E.g. 7]&nbsp;debug=1</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the debug mode and always run it in debug mode before doing the real thing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read what\'s on the screen and press OK to proceed in Debug mode. Debug mode will log what\'s been sent to the spine under<strong>&nbsp;logs/</strong>&nbsp;in the currently directory. Each request will open up a separate log file and Debug mode DOES NOT change any data.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you are ready, change the debug=1 to debug=0 and it will do the real thing. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the real batch update starts running, you would want to go to the database for the service you are running the tool on and check if number of patient found from the following query is decreasing overtime. It means it\'s running OK if it does and you can shut everything down and go home :)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;code&gt;SELECT COUNT(*),pat_spine_verified FROM nh_patient WHERE pat_spine_verified != 10 GROUP BY pat_spine_verified\r\n&lt;/code&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note:Remember to include area_id on &nbsp;the above query for shared services to avoid picking up patients from another service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>After running the tool</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Update the google doc to notify that the batch tool has been run -&nbsp;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/a/mayden.co.uk/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhG_8En5W53KdEhrT054bzJOdV9KeGlzeGt3b0RnR1E#gid=0\">https://docs.google.com/a/mayden.co.uk/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhG_8En5W53KdEhrT054bzJOdV9KeGlzeGt3b0RnR1E#gid=0</a></p>\r\n','turning-on-nhs-number-spine-patient-lookup-for-a-live-service',41,NULL,15,'2016-09-22 08:29:52','2016-09-22 08:29:52',NULL),(110,32,'Referral and Care Pathway Locking 4th Dimension ','Created\r\n64 months ago by Steve Exley\r\nLast Updated\r\n46 months ago by Steve Exley','<h2>Summary&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The general concept of 4D is to enable abstract data to be attached to different content, either patients, referrals or pathway stages.&nbsp; This data can be utilised to provide:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Locks - these would lock the related content to specific groups of users.&nbsp; These groups are dedicated to 4D and not related to any other permissions settings.</li>\r\n	<li>Labels - (Originally called flags, and coded as flags).&nbsp; These allow bits of information to be attached to the associated content</li>\r\n	<li>Alerts - these are a bit like automated labels</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The above three data types combined with the three content types makes nine combinations.&nbsp; There is another data type called \'function\' which is not associated with any content.&nbsp; This function type is used to enable or disable functionality such as the ability to set locks, and is assigned on a permissions group basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Automated Referral Locking</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>4D can be automated.&nbsp; This has been done with referral types to provide automatic locking.&nbsp; Once a referral is locked, it can only be viewed by users that are members of a permissions group with access to that particular lock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To set up automated locking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tick \'can create referrals\' function.&nbsp; This enables the referral type locking capability although nothing happens at this stage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In \'Tags Manager (Mayden Only), For \'Referral Type Lock\', Edit Groups -&gt; Add.&nbsp; Create a group called \'Treatment Type\'.&nbsp; Then add values to this group named after each treatment type that will be locked when selected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the database, find the \'Treatment Type\' row in the nh_tagValueGroups table for this service and add \'ttype\' to the dataKey field.&nbsp; This associates this tagValueGroup with the treatment type code.&nbsp; Make a note of the tagValueGroupId</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Likewise in the nh_tagValues table.&nbsp; Find the relevant values using the tagValueGroupId.&nbsp; In the dataKey field, add ttype_X.&nbsp; Where \'X\' is the number of the treatment type from the TreatmentTypes class.&nbsp; e.g.&nbsp; IAPT is ttype_1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That\'s it, treatment types will now be automatically locked&nbsp; when the treatment type is changed on the \'Referral Data\' patient tab.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To enable access to these new types requires setting up of permissions groups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to users and edit a user.&nbsp; Choose keys/permissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a group called \'Admin\', give it access to \'Can create referrals\' and also to view each of the new Treatment Type values you have created.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create additional groups named after the treatment types and assign each one access to the respective treatment type values.&nbsp; These groups do not need the \'Set Referral Lock\' permission as they will not be needing access to change the treatment type.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: 4D has referral locks and referral type locks.&nbsp; Although these are almost identical to setup, the appearance and user journey to set and unset locks is different for the users.&nbsp; Automated referral locking uses \'Referral Type\' locking and not simple \'Referral Locking\'.&nbsp; If you mix them up it will probably not work as you expect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note 2</strong>: It looks like there is currently a bug on the User Permissions tab which does not show up if only Referral Type locking is selected.&nbsp; This may need resolving at some point when a client requires this option without any of the other locking functions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','referral-and-care-pathway-locking-4th-dimension',42,NULL,15,'2016-09-22 08:31:59','2016-09-22 08:31:59',NULL);
