devops/db-replication-monitoring\">Db Replication Monitoring</a>&nbsp;for notes on how replication is monitored.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Connect to PRTG monitor vm ivnode14(BRCK) or ivnode7(BMTH)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Connect to db server reporting issue</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On monitor vm:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/monitoring/dbHeartbeat/</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nphp dbStatus.php</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Shows what the status monitor thinks is going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Marked down by monitoring - says iaptus cannot connect to those db&#39;s on that ip</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; The :1 after DB name&nbsp;is the connection type - positive numbers mean master r/w connections</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Negative numbers mean slave (ro) connections</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nphp dbControl.php</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Lets you override the automatic monitoring, you can remove and restore access to databases from here for maintaince</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; 2 - take a host out (it will ask you to confirm)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; 3 - put it back in (It will set it to failed by monitoring and will only restore when monitoring says all clear based on replication status)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; 4 - Reset status cache - wipes the monitoring status if it gets tangled up</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; 2 &amp; 3 are pretty safe, 4 is dangerous</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; There&#39;s another layer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Manual override is higher precedence than automated monitoring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; But iaptus has a lower precedence layer as well - in case monitoring isn&#39;t running.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; If iaptus detects a db down, it will &quot;mark down by iaptus&quot; for 60 seconds and then retry on the next request</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nphp dbMonitor.php id=ivnode19</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; This is the sensor - used by PRTG and monitoring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Measured lag is important, as is the Status</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Status is only [1] if all the following status are [1], so it&#39;s a quick visual check</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; If replication crashes, then the error will also be printed here which I find quicker than show slave status in the db and then scrolling right for 30s to find the column</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Also a status[0] triggers PRTG alert</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>connect to mysql in HeidiSQL</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Only kill select / read queries</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Killing queries that change data crashes replication and creates pain</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Copy the query first, then add query to task list&nbsp;<a href=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/tasks/52720/\">#52720</a>&nbsp;noting the service and run time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>you can check the db monitor tool logs at http://logs.iaptus.nhs.uk/#/dashboard/elasticsearch/Error%20Logs</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-08 15:57:21','2016-08-08 15:57:21',NULL),(31,18,19,'Db Replication monitoring','MySQL \'show slave status\' monitoring is very limited and can report erroneous results in some scenarios. We have developed in-house monitoring that uses replicated timestamps to measure true replication lag and also confirm the replication process is running normally.\r\n\r\nOn top of this, we have a status monitor which can trigger switching of live db traffic between multi-master configured databases. Traffic is only switched if both hosts are in sync at the time of the switch. Currently it\'s used by iaptus.','<h3>Heartbeat&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The replication monitor is called heartbeat. It generates a new timestamp on all master hosts every 5s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the master:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE DATABASE `heartbeat`&nbsp; COLLATE &#39;utf8_general_ci&#39;;\r\n\r\nCREATE USER &#39;heartbeat&#39;@&#39;%&#39; IDENTIFIED BY &#39;__PASSWORD__&#39;;\r\nGRANT REPLICATION CLIENT&nbsp; ON *.* TO &#39;heartbeat&#39;@&#39;%&#39;;\r\nGRANT SELECT, CREATE, DELETE, DROP, INDEX, INSERT, UPDATE&nbsp; ON `heartbeat`.* TO &#39;heartbeat&#39;@&#39;%&#39;;\r\nFLUSH PRIVILEGES;\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Make sure new hosts are in&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/monitoring/dbHeartbeat/hb_config.php \r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Restart the heartbeat by killing the master cron process</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncat /tmp/dbHeartbeat.pid to get pids\r\nsudo kill ....\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>(Cron will restart the heartbeat process and it will self recover)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Test sensors locally</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nphp dbMonitor.php id=__NAME_OF_NODE_IN_HB_CONFIG__\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Add sensors to PRTG using url</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n/dbMonitor.php?id=__NAME_OF_NODE_IN_HB_CONFIG__</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>StatusMonitor&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The status monitor continually checks the status of all db&#39;s and updates a list in memcached of permitted connections for master and slave use. When the application connects to the db, it has a preference list of databases which it compares with the list in memcached to find the first match. Applications may also update the memcached list if a connection is unavailable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Make sure new hosts are in</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/includes/dbhostsIaptus/dbhosts.inc on all deploy servers (vnode14, vnode7)</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Restart the db status monitoring</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncat /tmp/dbStatusMonitor.pid (to get pids)\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo kill ....</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Cron will restart the monitoring process and it will self recover)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check locally what the status monitor is seeing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/monitoring/dbHeartbeat/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php dbStatus.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>php showCache.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Cache values are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5: A value of 5 in the connection cache means that the connection is known good<br />\r\n0/unset: Zero means &#39;unknown&#39; or &#39;unset&#39;, it is assumed as good<br />\r\n-5: Minus five means that the connection code failed to connect and has marked the connection down for a period of 60s.<br />\r\n-10: Minus 10 means that the automated monitoring has detected an issue with the connection and marked it down until it determines the state has improved<br />\r\n-15: Minus 15 means the connection has been marked down indefinitely by manual intervention.&nbsp;The dbControl.php script will do this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lower number values have precedence over higher numbers. A connection that is marked down manually with -10 cannot be restored except by the automated monitoring tool that set that value. When a site is manually failed and restored, it will first go to -10 state and the monitoring tool will confirm the connection is ready before marking it as plus 5 (available).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The dbStatusMonitor.php monitoring tool checks the speed of the connection to the database as well as the replication lag and replication process state from the master. Master and slave connections are treated differently so a database with significant lag would be unsuitable to add to the list of available masters, but fully available as a reporting slave.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-08 15:57:23','2016-08-08 15:57:23',NULL),(32,19,19,'Setup new IAPTus live sites','Specificiation \r\nConfirm name of client & subdomain with account manager via Orbit task. Determine rough size of site and whether a migration or associate of an existing site.\r\n\r\n Determine best location / hosts for new site based on available information. New clients go into Bournemouth on set5. An existing client merging, splitting or expanding may justify adding to a different host for data/transfer or IP address range reasons. Many N3 connections used by iaptus clients restrict access to the N3 by IP address, re-using existing addresses that are already approved by client connections mitigates this. ','<h3>New Client Tool</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the new client tool within iaptus for creating the correct database credentials and config file. If it doesn&#39;t work then see the manual instructions in grey below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On iaptusvnode14 (bracknell) or iaptusvnode7 (bournemouth). There is a tool based on the Phing automated build tool which can create sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/build/live\r\nphing new-client</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Then follow the instructions. It may complain of a missing properties file, creating an empty file in your home dir with the correct name will probably fix it (Or update these instructions).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tool will create SQL queries required to make accounts on the live database server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You also need to run the queries on the relevant archive server and create an empty nh_stats_history table.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE TABLE `__DBNAME__`.nh_stats_history LIKE `IAPTus_Swindon`.nh_stats_history;&nbsp; (Use a different source DB Name if in Bournemouth).&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>The tool will finish by creating the configuration folder for the new client in /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/includes. This is nice, however it also immediately breaks some other tools which expect there to be finished iaptus sites in those locations. So the new folder in /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/includes needs prefixing with an underscore and re-deploying. The phing tool could also be pretty easily fixed if somebody wanted to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Database&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a new database username and password and store details in Mayden keepass under Projects-&gt;iaptus-&gt;Databases-&gt;Live Clients (note that somebody deleted most of these entries in 2015 so a lot are missing). &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus databases start with `IAPTus_`, iaptus usernames usually the first 2 or 3 characters are a phonetic reference to the database name so that it&#39;s easier to find the association between username and database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a new database on one host in the chosen set (note we allow access from both IP ranges as there are some cross datacentre features like monitoring that require this):</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE DATABASE `__DBNAME__` CHARACTER SET utf8 COLLATE utf8_general_ci;\r\n\r\nGRANT USAGE ON *.* TO &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;192.168.63.%&#39;;\r\nGRANT SELECT, CREATE TEMPORARY TABLES, DELETE, INSERT, UPDATE ON `__DBNAME__`.* TO &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;192.168.63.%&#39;;\r\nSET PASSWORD FOR &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;192.168.63.%&#39; = PASSWORD(&#39;__PASSWORD__&#39;);\r\n\r\nGRANT USAGE ON *.* TO &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;10.0.2.%&#39;;\r\nGRANT SELECT, CREATE TEMPORARY TABLES, DELETE, INSERT, UPDATE ON `__DBNAME__`.* TO &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;10.0.2.%&#39;;\r\nSET PASSWORD FOR &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;10.0.2.%&#39; = PASSWORD(&#39;__PASSWORD__&#39;);\r\n\r\nGRANT SELECT ON `IAPTus_Global`.* TO &#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;192.168.63.%&#39;,&#39;__USER__&#39;@&#39;10.0.2.%&#39;;\r\nFLUSH PRIVILEGES;&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a user with the same credentials on the archive host in the same datacentre (Bracknell 21, Bournemouth 10) Use the same query as above but omit the IAPTus_Global line.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add an empty stats history table as the archive tool does not create this (doesn&#39;t have sufficient privileges).</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE TABLE `__DBNAME__`.nh_stats_history LIKE `IAPTus_Swindon`.nh_stats_history;&nbsp;\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>(Use a different source DB Name if in Bournemouth).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>iaptus Configuration&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go back and add the archive database and user which you forgot to do in the previous step.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>in /var/www/html/iaptus-deploy/includes (Bracknell iaptusvnode14) or &nbsp;/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/includes (Bournemouth iaptusvnode7). Copy one of the existing iaptus folders to the name of the new site but prefix with an underscore. e.g.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&nbsp;cp -dpr iaptuscumbria _iaptusnewclient</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that the name must match the iaptus subdomain name. This rule is how iaptus determines which database to connect to based upon the incoming HTTP request. The reason for the underscore is that some tools iterate through the folder and process any configuration folders matching the iaptus* rule. Adding a configuration for an empty database will break those tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Edit the new &nbsp;/var/www/html/iaptus-deploy-b/inclues/_iaptusnewclient/db_data.inc file to use the new user credentials and specify which hosts to connect to using the set#x syntax. As a general rule sites are split to either use set#a or set#b in each pear so that all db servers are masters for some clients and the resources are maximised.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Later on when either the DevSupport team or a developer makes the site live, they will rename the folder and deploy if to the cluster. There is also a secondary configuration file because - well somebody made that decision once and now we have technical debt. What this all means though is that it&#39;s not possible to actually test anything at this stage, that is done by whoever makes the site live.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>DNS</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Take a break from config files and request the new domain from the N3/HSCIC DNS team, to date they have avoided publicity and don&#39;t have a phone number, however &#39;Rob&#39; is pretty helpful. Send them an email like this:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>dnsteam@hscic.gov.uk</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dear DNS team,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please could we have a new subdomain for iaptus:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>newclient.iaptus.nhs.uk IN 10.191.213.132 (For Bracknell clients)<br />\r\nnewclient.iaptus.nhs.uk IN&nbsp;10.207.128.10 (For Bournemouth clients)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many thanks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your name</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add an iaptus.co.uk subdomain on ige:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsudo vi &nbsp;/var/named/chroot/var/named/pz/iaptus.co.uk</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>newclient &nbsp; &nbsp; A &nbsp; &nbsp;135.196.187.240 (For Bracknell clients)<br />\r\nnewclient&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; A &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 31.25.9.100 &nbsp;(For Bournemouth clients)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember to change the serial number at the top of the file. Keep domains in alphabetical order, makes life easier later on.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsudo service named reload&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Hosting config (nhs domain)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Add the new site to nginx: 12 in Bracknell, 30 in Bournemouth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>/etc/nginx/conf/iaptus-cluster.conf</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep in alphabetical order, makes life easier later on</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsudo service nginx configtest\r\nsudo service nginx reload&nbsp;</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Check nothing broken on a live client site from the same datacentre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Really Important</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus traffic not hosted in the local DC must be forwarded to the remote DC. This is how Mayden staff access all live sites whilst only forwarding ports 80 &amp; 443 to one of the load balancers. To facilitate this, Bracknell maintains a specific list of sites to send to Bournemouth. Bournemouth will just send any unmatched traffic to Bracknell. Any unmatched traffic in Bracknell is sent to iaptusvnode14 preventing circular loops for sites that do not exist in either location.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you understand those rules, you&#39;ll see that adding a new service to Bracknell requires no forwarding changes as the existing rules can handle it.&nbsp;<strong>When adding a new service to Bournemouth, then loadbalancer in Bracknell needs it&#39;s forwarding rules updating</strong>. Add the new Bournemouth domain to the &quot;/etc/nginx/config/iaptus-bourne.conf&quot; file on lbvnode12.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy the config to the hot spare load balance (13 in Bracknell, 31 in Bournemouth). Assumes you have your ssh key set up with ssh-agent or similar. Also be careful not to delete the root /etc folder</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;lbvnode12</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd ~\r\nsudo tar -cvf nginx.tar /etc/nginx/</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>lbvnode13</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd ~\r\nscp 10.0.2.40:nginx.tar .\r\nsudo rm -rf etc (CAREFUL)\r\nsudo tar -xvf nginx.tar\r\nsudo cp -dpr etc/nginx/conf.d /etc/nginx\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>sudo service nginx configtest sudo service nginx reload&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OR if in Bournemouth scp as follows on lblvnode31</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nscp -P 2263 192.168.63.30:nginx.tar .</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Check URL works on local network:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://miltonkeynes.iaptus.nhs.uk/\">http://miltonkeynes.iaptus.nhs.uk/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Page should display &quot;An unexpected database error occurred, please ask an admin to check the log files&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Hosting configuration: Internet / 2FA&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>For Bracknell use mayden2fanode26, for Bournemouth use mayden2fanode70</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Edit /var/www/gateway/gateway/config.setup.php Add a line for the new host in alphabetical order. Keep the format of the existing lines. The line specifies the incoming domain and maps it to the internal domain along with an IP address to proxy requests to. Requests are sent to the N3 load balancers which we configured in the previous step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Save the file and clear the PHP cache on the server: This should return an affirmative of the caches cleared.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncurl 127.0.0.1/clear-cache.php</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Check that the test domains work so that you know you have not broken anything. The test sites load from code in /var/www/gateway/gateway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>testing-a1.iaptus.co.uk (Bracknell)<br />\r\ntesting-b1.iaptus.co.uk (Bournemouth)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Assuming those pages load without error, then deploy the code to the live portals. In Bournemouth, ssh access via ssh-agent is required to deploy to both localhost and mayden2fanode73.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncd /var/www/gateway/gateway/build \r\nphing deploy-cluster</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Check again that the live sites are not broken</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Let people know you are finished&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Update iaptus analysis page on crm with new hosting details, It seems that not all clients make this list, but if they are on it then add the server name to the page.<br />\r\n<a href=\"https://crm.mayden.co.uk/analysis/#iaptus\">https://crm.mayden.co.uk/analysis/#iaptus</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Update the task.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-08 15:57:25','2016-08-08 15:57:25',NULL),(33,22,16,'Testing Online Self-Referral Forms','The flow required in order to test an online self-referral form server-side.','<h2>Testing on a testing server hosted on N3</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Follow these instructions on setting up a test site:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/curation/new\">http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/curation/new</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Copying live data to a test site:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Find which data center the service is located by looking at the <a href=\"/p/mayden/servers/server-details\">&#39;Servers&#39;</a> page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SSH into that server in the data center.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL, get permission from devOps to see if you are allowed to copy it across.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run:&nbsp;<code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Check live site <a href=\"testing-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk:8000\">testing-a3</a> is up and running:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Testing an online Self-Referral form&nbsp;on a Bournemouth server with a Bracknell Postroom</h2>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>On B test server go to the cron_live folder:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-b1/cron_live</code></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Change postroom URL to use a3 or whatever Postroom is set up in Bracknell to talk to the Paywall:&nbsp;<code>vim cron_setup.php</code></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Postroom URL, needs to URL rather than relative directory for CURL:&nbsp;<code>define(&#39;POSTROOM_URL&#39;, &#39;https://postroomtest-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk/&#39;);</code></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Add service ID of B test server into service_config:&nbsp;<code>​​INSERT INTO `service_config` (`id`, `service_id`, `self_referral_key`, `self_referral_id`) VALUES (366, 189, &#39;8fabfe8e-a44b-5555-92b0-982a2ead29fb&#39;, &#39;IAPTUSWIRRAL&#39;);</code></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Fill in the form.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Run the crons.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-08 16:11:11','2016-08-08 16:11:11',NULL),(34,22,16,'Testing Online Self-Referral Forms','The flow required in order to test an online self-referral form server-side.','<h2>Follow these instructions on setting up a test site:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/curation/new\">http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/curation/new</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Copying live data to a test site:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Find which data center the service is located by looking at the <a href=\"/p/mayden/servers/server-details\">&#39;Servers&#39;</a> page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SSH into that server in the data center.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL, get permission from devOps to see if you are allowed to copy it across.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Run:&nbsp;<code>php co