,1,'2016-08-09 09:44:20','2016-08-09 09:44:20',NULL),(40,26,4,'How To Sensu','An overview of how to create sensors and run them with Sensu.','<h3>First Things First</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Read the wikis for <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/sensor-manager/wiki\">sensor-manager</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/sensor-services/wiki\">sensor-services</a>. &nbsp;The sensor-manager allows you to run a sensor from the command line while the sensor-services repo contains interfaces and classes that must be implemented by your sensors. Also look at the sensu <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1O7G4-pjmZ2bSiuj1CJV_4O-wOtt80D5MMIW36-DONp8/\">document</a> for conventions relating to checks and metrics.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>How To Make A Sensor</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Go to the sensor repo of the product that you&rsquo;re writing a sensor for e.g <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/postroom-sensors\">postroom-sensors</a>. &nbsp;The <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/master/README.md\">readme</a> should give you instructions on how to create a sensor.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Here is an example of a <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/80663-sensu-updates-checks/src/Sms/Metrics/SmsCount.php\">sensor</a> in iaptus-sensors.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You can write helpers to handle common functionality sensors might need like connecting to all <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus-sensors/blob/master/src/Databases/PdoConnectionIterator.php\">databases</a>.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Iaptus Sensors</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new Metric or Check file for your sensor.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Take a look at existing sensors to see how they are written.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a query for your sensor using the $sensorQuery property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a .json config file in the same directory as your sensor (take a look at other .json config files for reference)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to give your sensor a name using the $sensorName property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Add your sensor to config/di-config.php file.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Postroom Sensor</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Create a new Metric or Check file for your sensor.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Take a look at existing sensors to see how they are written.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a query for your sensor using the $sensorQuery property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to give your sensor a name using the $sensorName property.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>You will need to add a .json config file in the same directory as your sensor (take a look at other .json config files for reference)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Add your sensor to config/di-config.php file.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>How To Test</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Use TDD! Write tests as you go to make sure your sensor is behaving as you would expect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can also copy changes into the sensor-manager version of your sensor repo in the vendor directory and run the sensor from your console.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Running Sensu</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code>php SensorManager.php run Iaptus Users\\\\Metrics\\\\UniqueUserLoginsPerService</code></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Running Tests</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Run &lsquo;<code>composer test</code>&rsquo; from either the iaptus-sensors or postroom-sensors repo.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-09 11:04:52','2016-08-09 11:04:52',NULL),(41,6,7,'Signing Exports Certificates','Instructions for how to process and sign CAE certificate requests for clients','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass</li>\r\n	<li>An FTP connection to the server the client lives on</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the client&#39;s certificate request from the relevant Orbit task and upload it to the <code>/var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/</code> directory on <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">the client&#39;s server</a> via FTP</li>\r\n	<li>Open and read the certificate using the <code>openssl req -noout -text -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr</code> command, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; with the file name of the certificate request that you uploaded.</li>\r\n	<li>Chech the &#39;common name&#39; in the open certificate request againt that service&#39;s nh_export_users. If the common name from the certificate is already in this table, the certificate request should be discarded and the client needs to be asked to supply another with a unique common name.</li>\r\n	<li>Generate a signed certificate from your uploaded certificate request by running <code>openssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr -out CERT_REQUEST_NAME.crt</code>, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; again.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the newly created signed certificate by running <code>openssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt</code>. Ensure the contents look logical/not corrupted or empty.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the certificate via FTP and send it via Skype to the support team member who is assigned to the task.</li>\r\n	<li>Add a patch to the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> directory which stores the common name from the certificate request to the service&#39;s <code>nh_export_users</code> table:<br />\r\n	<code>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;date_database_patch_name.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The certificate request you download may have a <code>.csr</code> file extension OR a <code>.req</code> file extension. Either is&nbsp;valid.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-10 13:54:03','2016-08-10 13:54:03',NULL),(42,6,7,'Signing Exports Certificates','Instructions for how to process and sign CAE certificate requests for clients','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass</li>\r\n	<li>An SFTP connection to ivnode14</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the client&#39;s certificate request from the relevant Orbit task and upload it to the <code>/var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/</code> directory on <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">ivnode14</a>&nbsp;via SFTP</li>\r\n	<li>Open and read the certificate using the <code>openssl req -noout -text -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr</code> command, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; with the file name of the certificate request that you uploaded.</li>\r\n	<li>Check the certificate details against the criteria below, if <strong>anything</strong> does not meet the criteria, the task needs to go back to support to contact the client.</li>\r\n	<li>Generate a signed certificate from your uploaded certificate request by running <code>openssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr -out CERT_REQUEST_NAME.crt</code>, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; again.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the newly created signed certificate by running <code>openssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt</code>. Ensure the contents look logical/not corrupted or empty.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the certificate via SFTP and send it via Skype to the support team member who is assigned to the task.</li>\r\n	<li>Add a patch to the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> directory which stores the common name from the certificate request to the service&#39;s <code>nh_export_users</code> table:<br />\r\n	<code>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;date_database_patch_name.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The certificate request you download may have a <code>.csr</code> file extension OR a <code>.req</code> file extension. Either is&nbsp;valid.</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate Details:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>O=Mayden</li>\r\n		<li>L=Bath</li>\r\n		<li>S=Wiltshire</li>\r\n		<li>C=GB</li>\r\n		<li>CN: This&nbsp;<strong>must</strong>&nbsp;contain the name of, or some means of identifying the service that it is being used for\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>The CN<strong> must be</strong>&nbsp;<strong>unique</strong>, that is, no other signed certificate may be using it. The list of all currently signed certficates on ivnode14&nbsp;can be found in /var/www/ca/index.txt</li>\r\n			<li>Alternatively, you can look at the nh_export_users table in each clients database, to see if it has been used (the client name in the certificate name should prevent inter-service clashes).</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,24,'2016-08-10 14:15:48','2016-08-11 14:27:24',NULL),(43,6,7,'Signing Exports Certificates','Instructions for how to process and sign CAE certificate requests for clients','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass / 1Password</li>\r\n	<li>An FTP connection to the server the client lives on</li>\r\n	<li>To be VPN&#39;d into Bracknell</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the client&#39;s certificate request from the relevant Orbit task and upload it to the <code>/var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/</code> directory on `iaptusvnode14`&nbsp;via FTP</li>\r\n	<li>Open and read the certificate using the <code>openssl req -noout -text -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr</code> command, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; with the file name of the certificate request that you uploaded.</li>\r\n	<li>Chech the &#39;common name&#39; in the open certificate request againt that service&#39;s nh_export_users. If the common name from the certificate is already in this table, the certificate request should be discarded and the client needs to be asked to supply another with a unique common name.</li>\r\n	<li>Generate a signed certificate from your uploaded certificate request by running <code>openssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr -out CERT_REQUEST_NAME.crt</code>, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; again.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the newly created signed certificate by running <code>openssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt</code>. Ensure the contents look logical/not corrupted or empty.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the certificate via FTP and attach&nbsp;it&nbsp;to the Orbit task, notifying the support team member who is assigned to the task.</li>\r\n	<li>Add a patch to the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> directory which stores the common name from the certificate request to the service&#39;s <code>nh_export_users</code> table:<br />\r\n	<code>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;date_database_patch_name.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The certificate request you download may have a <code>.csr</code> file extension OR a <code>.req</code> file extension. Either is&nbsp;valid.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',0,25,'2016-08-11 10:18:42','2016-08-11 14:35:20',NULL),(44,25,1,'Copying Live Data to Test Sites','Instructions for how to copy a live database to a test site','<p>1.&nbsp;Find which data center the service is located by looking at the <a href=\"/p/mayden/servers/server-details\">&#39;Servers&#39;</a> page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. VPN into the relevant&nbsp;datacenter and&nbsp;SSH into the relevant&nbsp;server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL and double check with&nbsp;devOps that it is an appropriate size/time to copy it accross.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Run the command which will copy the database you need to the test server:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.&nbsp;Follow the prompts from the script to complete the process:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Check live site <a href=\"testing-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk:8000\">testing-a3</a> is up and running:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#aaa;font-style:italic;\">Copying Bournmouth Site To Bracknell Testing Server</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Please make sure you read and understand all these commands before executing them. This is the safest way of getting a bournmoth site to bracknell. This can be done at any time of the day as providing you do everything right there is very minimal risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please replace the &lt;TOKENS&gt; in the below commands with the details below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SERVICE_DB_NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Name of the DB you need to copy</li>\r\n	<li>e.g. IAPTus_IOW</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>DB_USER_NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your master DB user name</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>PORT:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>3306 for Set 4</li>\r\n	<li>3312 for Set 5</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ ssh iaptusvnode26</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ cd ~/</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ mysqldump &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt; -u &lt;DB_USER_NAME&gt; -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &lt;PORT&gt; --add-drop-table --skip-lock-tables --skip-add-locks --compress --skip-triggers --ignore-table=&lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.nh_stats_history --ignore-table=&lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.nh_stats --ignore-table=&lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.nh_user_activity_view --ignore-table=&lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.nh_user_activity_edit &gt; &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ mysqldump &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt; -u &lt;DB_USER_NAME&gt; -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &lt;PORT&gt;&nbsp;--add-drop-table --compress --no-data nh_stats --no-data nh_stats_history --no-data nh_user_activity_view --no-data nh_user_activity_edit &gt;&gt; &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ mysqldump IAPTus_Global -u &lt;DB_USER_NAME&gt; -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &lt;PORT&gt;&nbsp;--add-drop-table --skip-lock-tables --skip-add-locks --compress --skip-triggers --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_gp_bak --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_gp_import --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_practice_bak --ignore-table=IAPTus_Global.nh_national_practice_import &gt; IAPTus_Global.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ mysql &lt;TEST_SITE_DB_NAME&gt; -u -p &lt;DB_USER_NAME&gt; -h 10.0.2.54 -P 3306 &lt; &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ mysql &lt;GLOBAL_TEST_SITE_DB_NAME&gt; -u &lt;DB_USER_NAME&gt; -p -h 10.0.2.54 -P 3306 &lt; IAPTus_Global.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ rm &lt;SERVICE_DB_NAME&gt;.sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee;border:1px solid #ccc;padding:5px 10px;\">$ rm IAPTus_Global.sql</div>\r\n',1,6,'2016-08-11 11:18:55','2016-08-11 14:42:23',NULL),(45,6,7,'Signing Exports Certificates','Instructions for how to process and sign CAE certificate requests for clients','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass/1 Password</li>\r\n	<li>An SFTP connection to ivnode14</li>\r\n	<li>A VPN connection to ivnode14</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the client&#39;s certificate request from the relevant Orbit task and upload it to the <code>/var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/</code> directory on <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">ivnode14</a>&nbsp;via SFTP</li>\r\n	<li>Open and read the certificate using the <code>openssl req -noout -text -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr</code> command, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; with the file name of the certificate request that you uploaded.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Check the certificate details against the criteria in the &#39;notes&#39; section below, if <strong>anything</strong> does not meet the criteria, the certificate request needs to be discarded and the&nbsp;task needs to go back to Support.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Generate a signed certificate from your uploaded certificate request by running <code>openssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr -out CERT_REQUEST_NAME.crt</code>, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; again.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the newly created signed certificate by running <code>openssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt</code>. Ensure the contents look logical/not corrupted or empty.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the certificate via SFTP and send it via Skype to the support team member who is assigned to the task.</li>\r\n	<li>Add a patch to the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> directory which stores the common name from the certificate request to the service&#39;s <code>nh_export_users</code> table:<br />\r\n	<code>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;date_database_patch_name.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The certificate request you download may have a <code>.csr</code> file extension OR a <code>.req</code> file extension. Either is&nbsp;valid.</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate Details:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>O=Mayden</li>\r\n		<li>L=Bath</li>\r\n		<li>S=Wiltshire</li>\r\n		<li>C=GB</li>\r\n		<li>CN: This&nbsp;<strong>must</strong>&nbsp;contain the name of, or some means of identifying the service that it is being used for\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>The CN<strong> must be</strong>&nbsp;<strong>unique</strong>, that is, no other signed certificate may be using it. The list of all currently signed certficates on ivnode14&nbsp;can be found in /var/www/ca/index.txt</li>\r\n			<li>Alternatively, you can look at the nh_export_users table in each clients database, to see if it has been used (the client name in the certificate name should prevent inter-service clashes).</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-11 14:33:16','2016-08-11 14:33:16',NULL),(46,6,7,'Signing Exports Certificates','Instructions for how to process and sign CAE certificate requests for clients','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass/1 Password</li>\r\n	<li>An SFTP connection to ivnode14</li>\r\n	<li>A VPN connection to ivnode14</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the client&#39;s certificate request from the relevant Orbit task and upload it to the <code>/var/www/ca/clients/CLIENT_NAME/</code> directory on <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">ivnode14</a>&nbsp;via SFTP</li>\r\n	<li>Open and read the certificate using the <code>openssl req -noout -text -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr</code> command, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; with the file name of the certificate request that you uploaded.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Check the certificate details against the criteria in the &#39;notes&#39; section below, if <strong>anything</strong> does not meet the criteria, the certificate request needs to be discarded and the&nbsp;task needs to go back to Support.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Generate a signed certificate from your uploaded certificate request by running <code>openssl ca -cert ../../ca/ca.crt -keyfile ../../ca/ca.key -config ../../openssl.cnf -in CERT_REQUEST_NAME.csr -out CERT_REQUEST_NAME.crt</code>, replacing &#39;CERT_REQUEST_NAME&#39; again.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the newly created signed certificate by running <code>openssl x509 -noout -text -in client.crt</code>. Ensure the contents look logical/not corrupted or empty.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the certificate via SFTP and send it via Skype to the support team member who is assigned to the task.</li>\r\n	<li>Add a patch to the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> directory which stores the common name from the certificate request to the service&#39;s <code>nh_export_users</code> table:<br />\r\n	<code>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;date_database_patch_name.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The certificate request you download may have a <code>.csr</code> file extension OR a <code>.req</code> file extension. Either is&nbsp;valid.</li>\r\n	<li>Certificate Details:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>O=Mayden</li>\r\n		<li>L=Bath</li>\r\n		<li>S=Wiltshire</li>\r\n		<li>C=GB</li>\r\n		<li>CN: This&nbsp;<strong>must</strong>&nbsp;contain the name of, or some means of identifying the service that it is being used for\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>The CN<strong> must be</strong>&nbsp;<strong>unique</strong>, that is, no other signed certificate may be using it. The list of all currently signed certficates on ivnode14&nbsp;can be found in /var/www/ca/index.txt</li>\r\n			<li>Alternatively, you can look at the nh_export_users table in each clients database, to see if it has been used (the client name in the certificate name should prevent inter-service clashes).</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-11 14:33:31','2016-08-11 14:33:31',NULL),(47,30,1,'Copying Data to Test Sites (Bmth to Brck)','Instructions for how to copy a live database from Bournemouth to a test site on Bracknell','\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#aaa; font-style:italic\">Copying Bournmouth Site To Bracknell Testing Server</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Please make sure you read and understand all these commands before executing them. This is the safest way of getting a bournmoth site to bracknell. This can be done at any time of the day as providing you do everything right there is very minimal risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please replace the in the below commands with the details below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SERVICE_DB_NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Name of the DB you need to copy</li>\r\n	<li>e.g. IAPTus_IOW</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>DB_USER_NAME</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your master DB user name</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>PORT:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>3306 for Set 4</li>\r\n	<li>3312 for Set 5</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee; border:1px solid #ccc; padding:5px 10px\">$ ssh iaptusvnode26</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee; border:1px solid #ccc; padding:5px 10px\">$ cd ~/</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee; border:1px solid #ccc; padding:5px 10px\">$ mysqldump -u -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P --add-drop-table --skip-lock-tables --skip-add-locks --compress --skip-triggers --ignore-table=.nh_stats_history --ignore-table=.nh_stats --ignore-table=.nh_user_activity_view --ignore-table=.nh_user_activity_edit &gt; .sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:#eee; border:1px solid #ccc; padding:5px 10px\">$ mysqldump -u -p -h 10.0.2.55 -P &nbsp;--add-drop-table --compress --no-data nh_stats --no-data nh_stats_history --no-data nh_user_activity_view --no-data nh_user_activity_edit &gt;&gt; .sql</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=