pservice.class.php&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). &lt;strong&gt;Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;Instructions for Running Locally&lt;/h2&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Configure the setup &amp;amp; database&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;There is a setup.php file at &lt;code&gt;tools/webtools/inc/setup.php&lt;/code&gt; that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at &lt;code&gt;/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Change permissions on the backups folder&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Go to &lt;code&gt;iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript&lt;/code&gt; and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;chmod 777 backups&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;Change the &amp;#39;generic&amp;#39; service to copy from&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;$copy_ser_id = 101;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;&lt;br /&gt;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &amp;quot;&amp;quot;;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;h3&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-18 15:37:41','2016-08-18 15:37:41',NULL),(72,36,6,'New Service On Demo','Information about the script on demo that creates a new service on the demo database given some basic details such as name of the new service. ','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create New Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at <a href=\"http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools</a>. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &#39;Create New Service&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the &#39;Create New Service&#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script allows you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Code and script</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by <strong>copying the settings of an existing &#39;generic&#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &nbsp;(service name &quot;generic&quot;&nbsp;on the demo site).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setupservice class</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). <strong>Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&nbsp;</strong>to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Instructions for Running Locally</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>Configure the setup &amp; database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a setup.php file at <code>tools/webtools/inc/setup.php</code> that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-18 15:51:39','2016-08-18 15:51:39',NULL),(73,36,6,'New Service On Demo','Information about the script on demo that creates a new service on the demo database given some basic details such as name of the new service. ','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create New Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at <a href=\"http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools</a>. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &#39;Create New Service&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the &#39;Create New Service&#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script allows you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Code and script</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by <strong>copying the settings of an existing &#39;generic&#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &nbsp;(service name &quot;generic&quot;&nbsp;on the demo site).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setupservice class</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). <strong>Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&nbsp;</strong>to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Instructions for Running Locally</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>Configure the setup &amp; database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a setup.php file at <code>tools/webtools/inc/setup.php</code> that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-18 15:51:59','2016-08-18 15:51:59',NULL),(74,36,6,'Adding a New Service to Demo','Information about the script on demo that creates a new service on the demo database given some basic details such as name of the new service. ','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create New Service on Demo with Webtools</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step in setting up a new iaptus client is creating a new service on the demo site and database. This is usually done by the support team via a tools script that is accessible from the browser at <a href=\"http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools\" target=\"_blank\">http://demo.iaptus.co.uk/webtools</a>. Once logged in one of the choices in the webtools menu is &#39;Create New Service&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the &#39;Create New Service&#39; link is clicked it runs the following code from the iaptus codebase:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>iaptus/tools/webtools/new_client_setup_live.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The script allows you to back up existing demo tables, then displays a form for you to specify the service name and shortname and how many dummy users you want to create. You can also choose to create either an IAPT service or a CYP service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Code and script</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;script creates a new service with the specified name by <strong>copying the settings of an existing &#39;generic&#39; service which has classic miniumum dataset settings. This generic service is hardcoded to service_id 6 &nbsp;(service name &quot;generic&quot;&nbsp;on the demo site).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setupservice class</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The script instantiates an instance of class SetupService.class.php:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>tools/webtools/setupscript/Setupservice.class.php</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The script calls individual methods in this class to insert entries into each relevant table (e.g. nh_service, nh_fieldsSer, nh_list etc). <strong>Changes to this class may be needed when new required settings or tables are added to iaptus&nbsp;</strong>to ensure that new clients created by the script have the necessary data that will be added in patches for existing clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Instructions for Running Locally</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>Configure the setup &amp; database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a setup.php file at <code>tools/webtools/inc/setup.php</code> that gets created from setup_example.php when the build script runs. This file includes a require_once for a database file on our development setup at <code>/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to the db_data_old_style.inc file which sets up old style $db and $dbGlobal database connections. The build script currently sets both of these to the same database - the iaptus branch database. However our local setup now splits up the local and global iaptus databases to mirror the arrangement on our live servers. Change the following lines to the appropriate names of your local global and iaptus databases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>... $dbs = [name of iaptus global database]<br />\r\n... $database = [name of iaptus database]</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change permissions on the backups folder</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to <code>iaptus/tools/webtools/setupscript</code> and run the following (from host machine rather than in Vagrant box) to set the permissions to 777</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>chmod 777 backups</code></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Change the &#39;generic&#39; service to copy from</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Service id 6 does not exist on our local testing iaptus databases so you need to change the following variables that appear near the top of new_client_setup_live.php</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>$copy_ser_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_team_id = 102;&nbsp;<br />\r\n$copy_area_id = 101;<br />\r\n$copy_shortName = &quot;&quot;;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should now be able to run the Create New Service script locally without any errors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-18 16:17:20','2016-08-18 16:17:20',NULL),(75,25,1,'Test Sites: Copying Databases (Same Datacenter)','Instructions for how to copy a live database to a test site','<ol>\r\n	<li>Find which data center the service is located on by looking at the <a href=\"/p/mayden/servers/server-details\">&#39;Servers&#39;</a> page.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you allocate the testing site you are using to yourself in the &#39;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1HO9zfbEycSBxlsYeKikhzh3N8jBJrkwTljcG4kxx3FA/edit#gid=9\">Developer Portal&#39;</a></li>\r\n	<li>VPN into the relevant&nbsp;datacenter and&nbsp;SSH into the relevant&nbsp;server.</li>\r\n	<li>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL and double check with&nbsp;devOps that it is an appropriate size/time to copy it accross.</li>\r\n	<li>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the command which will copy the database you need to the test server:&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Follow the prompts from the script to complete the process:</li>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n	<li>Check live site <a href=\"testing-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk:8000\">testing-a3</a> is up and running:</li>\r\n	<li>Login with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-19 10:38:14','2016-08-19 10:38:14',NULL),(76,25,1,'Test Sites: Copying Databases (Same Datacenter)','Instructions for how to copy a live database to a test site','<ol>\r\n	<li>Find which data center the service is located on by looking at the <a href=\"/p/mayden/servers/server-details\">&#39;Servers&#39;</a> page.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you allocate the testing site you are using to yourself in the &#39;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1HO9zfbEycSBxlsYeKikhzh3N8jBJrkwTljcG4kxx3FA/edit#gid=9\">Developer Portal&#39;</a></li>\r\n	<li>VPN into the relevant&nbsp;datacenter and&nbsp;SSH into the relevant&nbsp;server.</li>\r\n	<li>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL and double check with&nbsp;devOps that it is an appropriate size/time to copy it accross.</li>\r\n	<li>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the command which will copy the database you need to the test server:&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Follow the prompts from the script to complete the process:</li>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n	<li>Check test site you selected&nbsp;is up and running by logging in&nbsp;with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-19 10:38:41','2016-08-19 10:38:41',NULL),(77,25,1,'Test Sites: Copying Databases (Same Datacenter)','Instructions for how to copy a live database to a test site','<ol>\r\n	<li>Find which data center the service is located on by looking at the <a href=\"/p/iaptus/services/service-list\">&#39;Services&#39;</a> page.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you allocate the testing site you are using to yourself in the &#39;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1HO9zfbEycSBxlsYeKikhzh3N8jBJrkwTljcG4kxx3FA/edit#gid=9\">Developer Portal&#39;</a></li>\r\n	<li>VPN into the relevant&nbsp;datacenter and&nbsp;SSH into the relevant&nbsp;server.</li>\r\n	<li>Get the size of the database by looking it up in HeidiSQL and double check with&nbsp;devOps that it is an appropriate size/time to copy it accross.</li>\r\n	<li>Navigate to:&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptus/tools</code></li>\r\n	<li>Run the command which will copy the database you need to the test server:&nbsp;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><code>php copy_db_to_test.php</code></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Follow the prompts from the script to complete the process:</li>\r\n	<li>Enter admin level credentials for the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the source database when prompted.</li>\r\n	<li>Select the destination when prompted</li>\r\n	<li>Check test site you selected&nbsp;is up and running by logging in&nbsp;with your service credentials:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>mayden.{initials}.{servicename}</li>\r\n		<li>password allocated to you by devOps</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-19 10:40:36','2016-08-19 10:40:36',NULL),(78,38,7,'Manual Client Advanced Exports','How to download and transfer client advanced exports manually to clients.','<h1>Exports Ran Correctly - Data On Live Server</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Download the export data&nbsp;from the live server using SFTP\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>On ivnode14, this can be found in:&nbsp;/mnt/nfs_vnode20_docs/docs0/IAPTus_Documents/all_docs/documentService134/exports</li>\r\n		<li>On ivnode7, this can be found in:&nbsp;/mnt/iaptus_docs/IAPTus_Documents/all_docs/documentServiceZZZ/exports, w<span style=\"line-height:1.6\">here ZZZ is their service ID</span></li>\r\n		<li>We keep three days worth of data, so pick the one for the day you need</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use Teamviewer 10</strong>&nbsp;in file transfer mode to transfer the data to the client\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>You will need to telephone the client to get their Teamviewer credentials</li>\r\n		<li>Note, this&nbsp;<strong>must</strong>&nbsp;be Teamviewer 10, as per the ISMS documents</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Exports Did Not Run</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Put the master branch on a test site and deploy, using the services database.</li>\r\n	<li>Go into the Control Panel on the front end, turn exports on</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the folder html_live/documents/documentServiceZZZ/exports/ exists and has write permissions, where ZZZ is their service ID</li>\r\n	<li>Go to cron_live/cron-config.php and uncomment the lines for &quot;CronExports&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>Run the following command in the cron_live folder: &quot;php cron.php&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>Once the cron has run, comment the lines in cron-config.php again</li>\r\n	<li>Grab the data files and place them in the location detailed in the instructions above</li>\r\n	<li>If they can&#39;t download it from their own link, follow the steps above to transfer manually</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-19 12:32:16','2016-08-19 12:32:16',NULL),(79,40,18,'UPS Monitoring','All the UPS monitoring is done via apcupsd service that runs on fileserver.may. You can ssh to the fileserver and do the usual service stuff: service apcupsd restart etc. All the config files are in /etc/apcupsd/. The /etc/apcupsd/hosts.conf file lists the various devices you see on power.may so this is were you could add/update devices if necessary.  To actually setup a new ups on the monitoring takes more work, you need to attach it to something (you\'ll note the little old Samsung notebooks in the cupboard, they are setup with an ip and running centos with apcupsd, then connected via usb to the UPS.','<p>All the UPS monitoring is done via apcupsd service that runs on fileserver.may. You can ssh to the fileserver and do the usual service stuff: service apcupsd restart etc. All the config files are in /etc/apcupsd/. The /etc/apcupsd/hosts.conf&nbsp;file lists the various devices you see on power.may so this is were you could add/update devices if necessary.&nbsp; To actually setup a new ups on the monitoring takes more work, you need to attach it to something (you&#39;ll note the little old Samsung notebooks in the cupboard, they are setup with an ip and running centos with apcupsd, then connected via usb to the UPS.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>If UPS reports &#39;No communications&#39;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>After checking both the UPS is on and the attached device is working,&nbsp; try unplugging the usb data cable between UPS &amp; device, then re-plug.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If it still fails try a self test - press button front of UPS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Set up SNMP on a centos server&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p># install packages</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nyum install net-snmp net-snmp-utils net-snmp-devel </pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# create user</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnet-snmp-config --create-snmpv3-user -A SHA -a &#39;PASSWORD&#39; -x AES -X &#39;PASSWORD&#39; -ro maydensnmp</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Autostart SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nchkconfig snmpd on\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>#or centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl enable snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Backup snmpd.conf first</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncp /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf.ori</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# then append the config</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>rocommunity public5T88kl prtg.may:161<br />\r\nrocommunity public5T88kl 127.0.0.1:161<br />\r\nincludeAllDisks 10%<br />\r\ndisk&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5%<br />\r\nsyslocation Bat. C2<br />\r\nsyscontact system@mayden.co.uk<br />\r\nrouser maydensnmp priv</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Start SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nservice snmpd start\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p># centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl start snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Verify it works on localhost</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsnmpwalk -v 3 -l authPriv -a sha -A &#39;PASSWORD&#39; -x AES -X &#39;PASSWORD&#39; -u maydensnmp localhost | less</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# SNMP iptables rules (if required)</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\niptables -A INPUT -p udp -m udp -s 0/0 --dport 161:162 -j ACCEPT</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Add device and sensors to PRTG</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Add device&#39; at bottom of device view &gt; select a group</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add name &amp; DNS name (keep them the same if possible)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set sensor management to: Automatic device id (standard) &gt; Continue</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leave it 5 minutes to scan the device, it will add a load of sensors, everything it can find, then trim them back to what you need.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-23 13:19:42','2016-08-23 13:19:42',NULL),(80,32,23,'New Developer Setup','A few things to cover when getting a new starter set up in an iaptus team.','<h1>​Github and Virtual Machines</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Register with Mayden 1Password and get set up to save passwords.</li>\r\n	<li>Create Github account if you do not already have one\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Ask a Github admin to add your account to the Mayden developers group</li>\r\n		<li>Generate and install SSH key to access the Mayden repos (<a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-mac\">Mac</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/\">Windows</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-linux\">Linux</a>).</li>\r\n		<li>Ask someone to explain some of the major Mayden&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/may-den\">repositories</a>&nbsp;(eg.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/iaptus\">iaptus</a>, <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/postroom\">Postroom</a>, <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/paywall\">Paywall </a>etc)</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Set up your local Vagrant environment</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>iaptus</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Build&nbsp;iaptus using the phing commands</li>\r\n	<li>Get the development front end logins from someone</li>\r\n	<li>Explore the repo - ask someone for a quick rundown of the key areas to look at</li>\r\n	<li>Talk through the different types of tests, how to run them</li>\r\n	<li>Get set up with a Database tool\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Set up local database credentials</li>\r\n		<li>Log into database and point out key tables</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Mention Dev Standards, branch naming conventions etc&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Jira and Bamboo</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Ask Jira admin to create Jira account</li>\r\n	<li>Explain the dashboard</li>\r\n	<li>Go to an issue (preferrably a well documented one!)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the different types of issues</li>\r\n		<li>Explain which issues branch off where</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the workflow diagram</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the different fields</li>\r\n		<li>Definition of Done</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Bamboo admin to create Bamboo account\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the difference between the different plans</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-23 14:06:09','2016-08-23 14:06:09',NULL),(81,42,19,'Building Mayden PHP MySQL RPM','How tobuild the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus:','<p>This is how we build the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus, it uses a git repo from Rob Andrews.</p>\r\n<hr>\r\n<p>git clone https://github.com/borb/c6buildenv</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nmkdir -p ~/rpmbuild/{BUILD,RPMS,SOURCES,SPECS,SRPMS}</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>yum install -y https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-6.noarch.rpm http://rpms.remirepo.net/enterprise/remi-release-6.rpm http://repo.mysql.com/yum/mysql-community/el/6/x86_64/mysql-community-release-el6-5.noarch.rpm</p>\r\n\r\n<p>yum install -y figlet rpm-build redhat-rpm-config</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SPECS/php56.spec&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SOURCES/*&nbsp;&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SOURCES</p>\r\n\r\n<p>yum-builddep&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS/php56.spec</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-23 14:07:12','2016-08-23 14:07:12',NULL),(82,42,19,'Building Mayden PHP MySQL RPM','How tobuild the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus:','<p>This is how we build the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus, it uses a git repo from Rob Andrews.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><code>git clone https://github.com/borb/c6buildenv</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir -p ~/rpmbuild/{BUILD,RPMS,SOURCES,SPECS,SRPMS}</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum install -y https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-6.noarch.rpm http://rpms.remirepo.net/enterprise/remi-release-6.rpm http://repo.mysql.com/yum/mysql-community/el/6/x86_64/mysql-community-release-el6-5.noarch.rpm</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum install -y figlet rpm-build redhat-rpm-config</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SPECS/php56.spec&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cp&nbsp;c6buildenv/SOURCES/*&nbsp;&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SOURCES</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>yum-builddep&nbsp;~/rpmbuild/SPECS/php56.spec</code></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-23 14:07:37','2016-08-23 14:07:37',NULL),(83,42,19,'Building Mayden PHP MySQL RPM','How tobuild the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus:','<p>This is how we build the custom MySQL RPM for Iaptus, it uses a git repo from 