agrant Commands</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant halt</code> - stops the vagrant box running</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant provision</code> - resets and reconfigures the box&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant reload&nbsp;</code>- halts and restarts the box</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant destroy</code> - halts and destroys the box so you will not be able to use it any more</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Never interrupt your vagrant box after you run the <code>vagrant&nbsp;up</code> command. This can cause Irritating and Unspecified Problems which will usually result in you having to destroy your vagrant box and set it up all over again. If &#39;destroying&#39; sounds dramatic to you, it is nothing compared to doing this whole process all over.&nbsp;Just don&#39;t do it.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Troubleshooting:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If your box starting fails with&nbsp;&#39;<code>/sbin/mount.vboxsf: mounting failed with error: No such device&#39;,&nbsp;</code>you may need to update your box&#39;s package manager and then reload the vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>sudo yum update</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>exit</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant reload</code></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 13:03:22','2016-08-24 13:03:22',NULL),(100,41,24,'Setting Up Vagrant','Instructions for how to set up vagrant on your local machine','<p>Vagrant is a software which facilitates the provisioning of virtual machines (VMs). Whilst the virtual machine itself runs on VirtualBox, the set up and configuration is overseen by Vagrant, which creates an environment for your code based off a configuration file named &#39;Vagrantfile&#39;. You can think of a virtual machine as an isolated&nbsp;computer and operating system&nbsp;running on your own laptop, but separate from your own operating system&#39;s setup and configuration. At Mayden we use our company vagrant boxes to run projects like iaptus locally, and the