,22,16,'Configuring Test Sites For Self Referral Testing','Setup steps for test sites in order to test Self Referrals','<p>1. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/deploying-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on setting up a test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/copying-live-data-to-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on copying a live database to the test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Configure the test site for use with self referrals (datacentre agnostic)</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your chosen iaptus test site, go to&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live and in cron_setup.php modify the Postroom URL to point at a testing postroom, e.g.&nbsp;https://postroomtest-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk</code></li>\r\n	<li><font face=\"monospace\">Edit&nbsp;cron_config.php and uncomment the &quot;CronSelfReferrals&quot; lines</font></li>\r\n	<li><font face=\"monospace\">On the server containing your test postroom (note, MAY be a different server to where your test site is), go to /var/www/html/postroomtest-xx/cron</font></li>\r\n	<li><font face=\"monospace\">Modify postroom_cron_config.php and uncomment the lines regarding &quot;SelfReferralsMaydenTask&quot;</font></li>\r\n	<li><font face=\"monospace\">In the test postroom database, add the service id and the form UUID (see other article) to the service_config table</font><font face=\"monospace\">​</font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Once the test referral has been submitted, run the following command in the test postroom root folder: &quot;php index.php cron process&quot;. Once run successfully the data will appear in the collection_box table of the database. Re-comment the postroom_cron_config.php.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Go back to your iaptus test site and go to /var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live and run: &quot;php cron.php&quot;. Then recomment the lines in cron config</p>\r\n',1,24,'2016-08-24 13:30:38','2016-08-24 15:11:56',NULL),(107,43,24,'Setting Up GitHub','How to get set up with GitHub so you can access the Mayden Repositories','<p>GitHub is service which Mayden uses to store and keep track of work done to the various projects (repositories) we work on, which uses Git version control. You can read more about Git version control and GitHub <a href=\"https://jahya.net/blog/git-vs-github/\">here</a>. To get set up with the system for work at Mayden, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create an Account on GitHub</li>\r\n	<li>Configure Your SSH Keys</li>\r\n	<li>Get&nbsp;Familiar with the Git Commands</li>\r\n	<li>Creating New Branches</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>1. Creating an Account on GitHub</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If you already have a GitHub&nbsp;account and you would also like to use this for work, you can do so. If not, create a personal account on GitHub <a href=\"https://github.com/join?source=header-home\">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have a username and are all signed up, ask a GitHub admin to add you to the Mayden developers group on the company GitHub.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Configuring Your SSH Keys</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to create a set of SSH keys for your laptop and add them to your GitHub account in order to be able to interact with the Mayden repositories. If you&#39;re not sure how, there are some really great instructions here:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-mac\">Mac</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/\">Windows</a>, <a href=\"http://help.github.com/articles/generating-a-new-ssh-key-and-adding-it-to-the-ssh-agent/#platform-linux\">Linux</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Getting Familiar with the Git Commands</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Git has a number of terminal commands to help you read and write from a repository. You may wish to do some further reading on these, but <a href=\"https://www.git-tower.com/blog/git-cheat-sheet/\">here is a cheatsheet</a> of most of the commands. In particular, make sure you are familiar with:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>git clone</li>\r\n	<li>git add</li>\r\n	<li>git commit</li>\r\n	<li>git push</li>\r\n	<li>git pull</li>\r\n	<li>git fetch</li>\r\n	<li>git checkout</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>4. Creating New Branches</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All work should be done on a new git branch. This branch should be named according to this convention:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>[issue-type]/[jira-task-id]/[short-summary]</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>feature/jira-111/care-pathway-go-live-for-sunderland</code></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 14:13:01','2016-08-24 14:13:01',NULL),(108,5,29,'Putting a Care Pathway Live','Instructions for how to transfer a care pathway from demo to a live site','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the Bournemouth server</li>\r\n	<li>Log into <a href=\"https://demo.iaptus.co.uk\">https://demo.iaptus.co.uk</a> using &#39;superuser&#39; followed by the service needing the care pathway as the username, e.g. <code>superuserhull</code>. You can find the password in Keepass under <code>Projects &gt; IAPTus &gt; Websites &gt; Demo</code>.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the &#39;Care Pathway (Mayden Only)&#39; link under the Superuser menu.</li>\r\n	<li>Scroll to the &#39;Care Pathway Sync Tool&#39; section of the page, which will be close to the bottom. Ensure that the dropdown says &#39;LIVE&#39; and then click &#39;Export&#39;.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the downloaded file in a text editor and add the following insert statement to the top, to log the patch running:<br />\r\n	<code># Changing &#39;PATCH_FILENAME_HERE&#39; to the name you will save this patch under<br />\r\n	INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;PATCH_FILENAME_HERE.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</code></li>\r\n	<li>Check the patch file and make sure the value of&nbsp;<strong>id&nbsp;</strong>column in&nbsp;<strong>nh_stage</strong>&nbsp;table and<strong>&nbsp;id, stage_from</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>stage_to</strong>&nbsp;columns in&nbsp;<strong>nh_stage_process</strong>&nbsp;table are always less than&nbsp;<strong>100,000</strong>. Double check that the ser_id values in the patch match the ser_id in the nh_service table of the live database to confirm you have picked up the right care pathway from demo.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the nh_stage_process and nh_stage table from the live customer&#39;s database. &nbsp;Import them into a local database.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the Care Pathway patch (leaving out the last four queries where tables get dropped and renamed) on your local database server, in the same database as the customer&#39;s imported tables.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the following query on your local database:\r\n	<pre>\r\nSELECT * \r\nFROM nh_stage_process\r\nLEFT JOIN nh_stage_process_tempVersion ON nh_stage_process.`id` = nh_stage_process_tempVersion.`id`\r\nWHERE nh_stage_process.stage_from != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_from\r\nOR nh_stage_process.stage_to != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_to</pre>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>If any results are returned, new process IDs that link stage_from and stage_to together no longer hold the same stages as they did on the live site. &nbsp;This will lead to data corruption. &nbsp;If rows are returned DO NOT DEPLOY THE CARE PATHWAY. &nbsp;Instead revert the broken Care Pathway on the demo site to a previously stable version.</li>\r\n	<li>Save the patch in the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> folder.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The patch filename should be the current timestamp with no delimiter, followed by the service name, followed by a brief description of the patch (all separated by dashes):<br />\r\n	<code># For example:<br />\r\n	20160505-hull-care-pathway-to-go-live.sql</code></li>\r\n	<li>Don&#39;t forget to make a note on Jira that the patch will need to be run manually</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 14:17:51','2016-08-24 14:17:51',NULL),(109,48,29,'Manually Removing CP Links','How to remove a link from a care pathway so it no longer appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually remove links from care pathways. This must be done on the Demo site and the link itself must <strong>not&nbsp;</strong>be deleted - only archived/&#39;olded&#39;.&nbsp;To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs deleting. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be removed, making note of the ID for the &#39;from&#39; stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the &#39;to&#39; stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, use these IDs to find the link in the nh_stage_process table and change the archived column from <code>0</code> to <code>1</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>UPDATE nh_stage_process SET archived=1 WHERE stage_from=STAGE_FROM_ID AND stage_to=STAGE_TO_ID;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to set the link in the XML to archived too. You can find the XML in the&nbsp;nh_diagram table. Open the XML in a text editor and locate&nbsp;the link which needs archiving. You will be able to find it by removing the service id from the beginning of the STAGE_FROM&nbsp;ID and&nbsp;STAGE_TO_ID and looking for the link with a source and target with this number in it. For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>SERVICE_ID = 160</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>STAGE_FROM_ID = 16022</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>STAGE_TO_ID = 16044</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To archive the link, simply replace the&nbsp;<code>archived=&quot;0&quot;</code> part with&nbsp;<code>archived=&quot;0&quot;:</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to check that it is no longer possible travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus. When you have a patient in the &#39;stage from&#39; stage, it should not be possible to process the patient onto the &#39;to stage&#39; as you removed the link.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 14:36:51','2016-08-24 14:36:51',NULL),(110,5,29,'Putting a CP Live','Instructions for how to transfer a care pathway from demo to a live site','<h3>You will need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Access to Keepass</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>How To</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into the Bournemouth server</li>\r\n	<li>Log into <a href=\"https://demo.iaptus.co.uk\">https://demo.iaptus.co.uk</a> using &#39;superuser&#39; followed by the service needing the care pathway as the username, e.g. <code>superuserhull</code>. You can find the password in Keepass under <code>Projects &gt; IAPTus &gt; Websites &gt; Demo</code>.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the &#39;Care Pathway (Mayden Only)&#39; link under the Superuser menu.</li>\r\n	<li>Scroll to the &#39;Care Pathway Sync Tool&#39; section of the page, which will be close to the bottom. Ensure that the dropdown says &#39;LIVE&#39; and then click &#39;Export&#39;.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the downloaded file in a text editor and add the following insert statement to the top, to log the patch running:<br />\r\n	<code># Changing &#39;PATCH_FILENAME_HERE&#39; to the name you will save this patch under<br />\r\n	INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (&#39;PATCH_FILENAME_HERE.sql&#39;, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), &#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;);</