re the test site for use with self referrals (datacentre agnostic)</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your chosen iaptus test site, go to&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live and in cron_setup.php modify the Postroom URL to point at a testing postroom, e.g.&nbsp;https://postroomtest-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk</code></li>\r\n	<li>Edit&nbsp;cron_config.php and uncomment the &quot;CronSelfReferrals&quot; lines</li>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your test postroom (note, MAY be a different server to where your test site is), go to /var/www/html/postroomtest-xx/cron</li>\r\n	<li>Modify postroom_cron_config.php and uncomment the lines regarding &quot;SelfReferralsMaydenTask&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>In the test postroom database, add the service id and the form UUID (see other article) to the service_config table​</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Once the test referral has been submitted, run the following command in the test postroom root folder: &quot;php index.php cron process&quot;. Once run successfully the data will appear in the collection_box table of the database. Re-comment the postroom_cron_config.php.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Go back to your iaptus test site and go to <code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live</code> and run: &quot;php cron.php&quot;. Then recomment the lines in cron config</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:13:05','2016-08-24 15:13:05',NULL),(121,22,16,'Configuring Test Sites For Self Referral Testing','Setup steps for test sites in order to test Self Referrals','<p>1. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/deploying-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on setting up a test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/copying-live-data-to-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on copying a live database to the test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Configure the test site for use with self referrals (datacentre agnostic)</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your chosen iaptus test site, go to&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live </code>and in<code> cron_setup.php </code>modify the Postroom URL to point at a testing postroom, e.g.&nbsp;https://postroomtest-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk</li>\r\n	<li>Edit&nbsp;cron_config.php and uncomment the &quot;CronSelfReferrals&quot; lines</li>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your test postroom (note, MAY be a different server to where your test site is), go to /var/www/html/postroomtest-xx/cron</li>\r\n	<li>Modify postroom_cron_config.php and uncomment the lines regarding &quot;SelfReferralsMaydenTask&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>In the test postroom database, add the service id and the form UUID (see other article) to the service_config table​</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Once the test referral has been submitted, run the following command in the test postroom root folder: &quot;php index.php cron process&quot;. Once run successfully the data will appear in the collection_box table of the database. Re-comment the postroom_cron_config.php.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Go back to your iaptus test site and go to <code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live</code> and run: &quot;php cron.php&quot;. Then recomment the lines in cron config</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:13:30','2016-08-24 15:13:30',NULL),(122,22,16,'Configuring Test Sites For Self Referral Testing','Setup steps for test sites in order to test Self Referrals','<p>1. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/deploying-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on setting up a test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Follow <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/mayden/servers/copying-live-data-to-test-sites\">these instructions</a> on copying a live database to the test site</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Configure the test site for use with self referrals (datacentre agnostic)</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your chosen iaptus test site, go to&nbsp;<code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live </code>and in<code> cron_setup.php </code>modify the Postroom URL to point at a testing postroom, e.g.&nbsp;https://postroomtest-a3.iaptus.nhs.uk</li>\r\n	<li>Edit&nbsp;<code>cron_config.php</code> and uncomment the &quot;<code>CronSelfReferrals</code>&quot; lines</li>\r\n	<li>On the server containing your test postroom (note, MAY be a different server to where your test site is), go to<code> /var/www/html/postroomtest-xx/cron</code></li>\r\n	<li>Modify <code>postroom_cron_config.php</code> and uncomment the lines regarding &quot;<code>SelfReferralsMaydenTask</code>&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>In the test postroom database, add the service id and the form UUID (see other article) to the service_config table​</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Once the test referral has been submitted, run the following command in the test postroom root folder: &quot;<code>php index.php cron process</code>&quot;. Once run successfully the data will appear in the collection_box table of the database. Re-comment the <code>postroom_cron_config.php</code>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Go back to your iaptus test site and go to <code>/var/www/html/iaptustest-testing-XX/cron_live</code> and run: &quot;<code>php cron.php</code>&quot;. When done, re-comment out the lines in cron config.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:14:33','2016-08-24 15:14:33',NULL),(123,46,16,'Testing A New Self Referral Form','The process for testing a Self Referral Form prior to go-live that is completely new.','<h1>You Need:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>An internet connection.</li>\r\n	<li>The specification documents (Design Elemends and Form Fields) from Fi</li>\r\n	<li>Live Access for the steps in <strong>bold</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Some way of noting down issues, that should be relayed back to Fi<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Steps:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Go to the form URL.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>If this has not been provided on the task, the URL is&nbsp;https://test-gateway.mayden.co.uk/referral-v2/{UUID} where UUID can be found in the form_configs table of the test Paywall database for each form</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check, against the specification document. that the fields appear in the correct order.</li>\r\n	<li>Check the field types for each field are correct&nbsp;against the specification (e.g. Radio, Select, Text Box)</li>\r\n	<li>Check the Notes / Informational Texts on the form match those in the spec</li>\r\n	<li>Check the visuals - e.g. look for dodgy CSS / misplaced or badly sized logos, etc</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Check List IDS</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><strong>​</strong>For a lot of the fields that are Selects, Radios or Checkboxes, the values may link directly to the list IDs used in the services iaptus</li>\r\n		<li>For these elements, check that each front-end option (where the list ID is the back end value)&nbsp;relates to a realistic list ID in iaptus</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check &quot;requiredness&quot; - if a field is required, it shouldn&#39;t allow you to submit the form without it. If it&#39;s not required, then it should be ignored if empty.&nbsp;If a field is &quot;conditionally required&quot; (see below), then it should not be required by default.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>When you hit &quot;submit&quot;, if a required field isn&#39;t filled in, the form should flag it up in a pop up.&nbsp;So, you can fill in one field at a time, hitting submit after each to check that the next required field that is empty gets flagged up.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check front end validation\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><span class=\"marker\"><em>Every</em></span> field should have &quot;SafeCharacters&quot; validation at minimum, that is, it should reject the following characters\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>#</li>\r\n			<li>-- (double hyphen)</li>\r\n			<li>&lt;</li>\r\n			<li>&gt;</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is a date field, it should only accept a date in the format&nbsp;dd/mm/yyyy</li>\r\n		<li>Conditional requirement, in the spec there will be a number of fields that are &quot;required if field X is filled in&quot;, &quot;either X or Y must be filled in&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;required if field X = Yes&quot;, check that these fields are required&nbsp;<em>only&nbsp;</em>when the conditions are met.</li>\r\n		<li>Phone numbers should only be accepted if they contain 11 digits and if a mobile, must start with &quot;07&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Other special validation requirements will be on the specification.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>End To End Test</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Set up an iaptus test site and postroom, as detailed in another article in this chapter</li>\r\n		<li>Fill in the form on the<strong>&nbsp;<em>test paywall site</em></strong>&nbsp;and submit (<strong>TAKE A SCREENSHOT OF WHAT YOU SUBMIT BEFORE YOU PUSH THE BUTTON)</strong></li>\r\n		<li>Log into the test iaptus and accept the new referral by creating a patient</li>\r\n		<li>Go to the Referral Data page and check that all the details showing are the same as what you submitted (and hopefully screenshotted)</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:15:00','2016-08-24 15:15:00',NULL),(124,47,16,'Testing Changes to Self Referral Forms','A slightly shorter test plan for use only when testing updates to an existing form.','<h2><var><span class=\"marker\">NOTE: This test plan may *ONLY* be used when testing updates to an existing form that has been approved as a suitable base with which to compare changes. Speak to FD if you&#39;re not sure whether its use is appropriate.&nbsp;</span></var></h2>\r\n\r\n<h1>You Will Need:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access.</li>\r\n	<li>Access to bpvnode13 (Paywall/Bacpac&nbsp;Testing) and bpvnode14 (Paywall Live)</li>\r\n	<li>Access to the databases on the aforementioned servers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Steps:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;base&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table (`spec` column)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>This will, in most cases, be from the&nbsp;<strong>LIVE</strong>&nbsp;Paywall Database.</li>\r\n		<li>However, if you&#39;re updating a form that has not yet gone live, then someone should have taken a backup copy as a base from the testing database&nbsp;before updates were made&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;updated&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table of the Paywall Test database</li>\r\n	<li>Run both JSONs through the&nbsp;<strong>same&nbsp;</strong>JSON prettyfier, so that you get two lots of data that have the same formatting</li>\r\n	<li>Perform a file diff between the two files, to see what changes have been made\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>If there&#39;s a lot of fields changed that you weren&#39;t expecting or can&#39;t sufficently explain, &nbsp;refer this back to FD and discuss whether a full test may be more appropriate</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>For each element changed, check that the element still works as you would expect it to against the spec by using the updated version of the form:\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Check the &quot;requiredness&quot; - if a field is required, the form shouldn&#39;t allow successful submission without it</li>\r\n		<li>Check ordering on the form</li>\r\n		<li>Check the fields label and type\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>In the case of Select/Radio, check the value options and their order (including the back-end &quot;submitted&quot; value) are the same as the old version</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check validation\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>No field on the form should accept -- (double hyphen), #, &lt; or &gt; due to SQL injection concerns.</li>\r\n			<li>If the specification mentions special validation rules, check those too</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check dependencies\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>In a case where the field can be required as a result of another field being filled in, or having a certain value, make sure this link still works</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Perform an End to End test - as per that described in the &quot;New Forms&quot; testing guide.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Notes:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Especially on the older forms, it is likely that &quot;priority&quot; of fields may change, this is&nbsp;<strong>fine</strong>, provided the rule below still holds.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements on the form may have the same priority, if this has happened, there&#39;s a bug with the form builder and this needs to be raised ASAP.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements may have the same &quot;name&quot;, otherwise data in the second element will overwrite that in the first.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:15:28','2016-08-24 15:15:28',NULL),(125,46,16,'Testing New Self Referral Forms','The process for testing a Self Referral Form prior to go-live that is completely new.','<h1>You Need:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>An internet connection.</li>\r\n	<li>The specification documents (Design Elemends and Form Fields) from Fi</li>\r\n	<li>Live Access for the steps in <strong>bold</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Some way of noting down issues, that should be relayed back to Fi<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Steps:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Go to the form URL.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>If this has not been provided on the task, the URL is&nbsp;https://test-gateway.mayden.co.uk/referral-v2/{UUID} where UUID can be found in the form_configs table of the test Paywall database for each form</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check, against the specification document. that the fields appear in the correct order.</li>\r\n	<li>Check the field types for each field are correct&nbsp;against the specification (e.g. Radio, Select, Text Box)</li>\r\n	<li>Check the Notes / Informational Texts on the form match those in the spec</li>\r\n	<li>Check the visuals - e.g. look for dodgy CSS / misplaced or badly sized logos, etc</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Check List IDS</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><strong>​</strong>For a lot of the fields that are Selects, Radios or Checkboxes, the values may link directly to the list IDs used in the services iaptus</li>\r\n		<li>For these elements, check that each front-end option (where the list ID is the back end value)&nbsp;relates to a realistic list ID in iaptus</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check &quot;requiredness&quot; - if a field is required, it shouldn&#39;t allow you to submit the form without it. If it&#39;s not required, then it should be ignored if empty.&nbsp;If a field is &quot;conditionally required&quot; (see below), then it should not be required by default.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>When you hit &quot;submit&quot;, if a required field isn&#39;t filled in, the form should flag it up in a pop up.&nbsp;So, you can fill in one field at a time, hitting submit after each to check that the next required field that is empty gets flagged up.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check front end validation\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><span class=\"marker\"><em>Every</em></span> field should have &quot;SafeCharacters&quot; validation at minimum, that is, it should reject the following characters\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>#</li>\r\n			<li>-- (double hyphen)</li>\r\n			<li>&lt;</li>\r\n			<li>&gt;</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is a date field, it should only accept a date in the format&nbsp;dd/mm/yyyy</li>\r\n		<li>Conditional requirement, in the spec there will be a number of fields that are &quot;required if field X is filled in&quot;, &quot;either X or Y must be filled in&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;required if field X = Yes&quot;, check that these fields are required&nbsp;<em>only&nbsp;</em>when the conditions are met.</li>\r\n		<li>Phone numbers should only be accepted if they contain 11 digits and if a mobile, must start with &quot;07&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Other special validation requirements will be on the specification.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>End To End Test</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Set up an iaptus test site and postroom, as detailed in another article in this chapter</li>\r\n		<li>Fill in the form on the<strong>&nbsp;<em>test paywall site</em></strong>&nbsp;and submit (<strong>TAKE A SCREENSHOT OF WHAT YOU SUBMIT BEFORE YOU PUSH THE BUTTON)</strong></li>\r\n		<li>Log into the test iaptus and accept the new referral by creating a patient</li>\r\n		<li>Go to the Referral Data page and check that all the details showing are the same as what you submitted (and hopefully screenshotted)</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:15:40','2016-08-24 15:15:40',NULL),(126,46,16,'Testing New Self Referral Forms','The process for testing a Self Referral Form prior to go-live that is completely new.','<h1>You Need:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>An internet connection.</li>\r\n	<li>The specification documents (Design Elements and Form Fields) from Fi</li>\r\n	<li>Live Access for the steps in <strong>bold</strong></li>\r\n	<li>Some way of noting down issues&nbsp;that should be relayed back to Fi<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Steps:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Go to the form URL.\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If this has not been provided on the task, the URL is&nbsp;https://test-gateway.mayden.co.uk/referral-v2/{UUID} where UUID can be found in the form_configs table of the test Paywall database for each form</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check the following against the specification document:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>That the fields appear in the correct order</li>\r\n		<li>That&nbsp;the field types for each field are correct (e.g. radio, select, text box)</li>\r\n		<li>That the Notes / Informational Texts on the form match</li>\r\n		<li>That&nbsp;the visuals are correct - e.g. look for dodgy CSS / misplaced or badly sized logos, etc</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Check form element list IDs&nbsp;against database list IDs for this service</strong>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li><strong>​</strong>For a lot of the fields that are selects, radios or checkboxes, the values may link directly to the list IDs used in the services iaptus</li>\r\n		<li>For these elements, check that each front-end option (where the list ID is a list ID)&nbsp;relates to a realistic list ID in iaptus</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check that the right fields are &quot;required&quot;:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If a field is required, it shouldn&#39;t allow you to submit the form without it</li>\r\n		<li>If it&#39;s not required, then it should be ignored if empty</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is &quot;conditionally required&quot; (see below), then it should not be required by default</li>\r\n		<li>When you hit &quot;submit&quot;, if a required field isn&#39;t filled in, the form should flag it up in a pop up. To test requiredness of all fields, you can fill in one field at a time, hitting submit after each to check that the next required field that is empty gets flagged up.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Check front end validation\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><span class=\"marker\"><em>Every</em></span> field should have &quot;SafeCharacters&quot; validation at minimum, that is, it should reject the following characters\r\n		<ol>\r\n			<li>#</li>\r\n			<li>-- (double hyphen)</li>\r\n			<li>&lt;</li>\r\n			<li>&gt;</li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>If a field is a date field, it should only accept a date in the format&nbsp;dd/mm/yyyy</li>\r\n		<li>Conditional requirement, in the spec there will be a number of fields that are &quot;required if field X is filled in&quot;, &quot;either X or Y must be filled in&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;required if field X = Yes&quot;. Check that these fields are required&nbsp;<em>only&nbsp;</em>when the conditions are met.</li>\r\n		<li>Phone numbers should only be accepted if they contain 11 digits and if a mobile, must start with &quot;07&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Other special validation requirements will be on the specification.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>End To End Test</strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Set up an iaptus test site and postroom, as detailed <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/iaptus/self-referrals/configuring-test-sites-for-self-referral-testing\">here</a></li>\r\n		<li>Fill in the form on the<strong>&nbsp;<em>test paywall site</em></strong>&nbsp;and submit it (<strong>TAKE A SCREENSHOT OF WHAT YOU SUBMIT BEFORE YOU PUSH THE BUTTON)</strong></li>\r\n		<li>Log into the test iaptus and accept the new referral by creating a patient from it</li>\r\n		<li>Go to the Referral Data page and check that all the details showing match the data you submitted (and hopefully screenshotted)</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Cheer/have a drink</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:23:21','2016-08-24 15:23:21',NULL),(127,47,16,'Testing Changes to Self Referral Forms','A slightly shorter test plan for use only when testing updates to an existing form.','<h3><var><span class=\"marker\">NOTE: This test plan may *ONLY* be used when testing updates to an existing form that has been approved as a suitable base with which to compare changes. Speak to FD if you&#39;re not sure whether its use is appropriate.&nbsp;</span></var></h3>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>You Will Need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to bpvnode13 (Paywall/Bacpac&nbsp;Testing) and bpvnode14 (Paywall Live)</li>\r\n	<li>Access to the databases on the aforementioned servers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;base&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table (`spec` column)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>This will, in most cases, be from the&nbsp;<strong>LIVE</strong>&nbsp;Paywall Database.</li>\r\n		<li>However, if you&#39;re updating a form that has not yet gone live, then someone should have taken a backup copy as a base from the testing database&nbsp;before updates were made&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;updated&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table of the Paywall Test database</li>\r\n	<li>Run both JSONs through the&nbsp;<strong>same&nbsp;</strong>JSON prettyfier, so that you get two lots of data that have the same formatting</li>\r\n	<li>Perform a file diff between the two files, to see what changes have been made\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If there&#39;s a lot of fields changed that you weren&#39;t expecting or can&#39;t sufficently explain,&nbsp;refer this back to FD and discuss whether a full test may be more appropriate</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>For each element changed, check that the element still works as you would expect it to against the spec by using the updated version of the form:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Check that the right fields are &quot;required&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Check element ordering on the form</li>\r\n		<li>Check the fields labels and types:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In the case of select/radio, check the option values&nbsp;and their order (including the back-end &quot;submitted&quot; value) are the same as the old version</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check validation:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>No field on the form should accept -- (double hyphen), #, &lt; or &gt; due to SQL injection concerns.</li>\r\n			<li>If the specification mentions special validation rules, check those too</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check dependencies\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In a case where the field can be required as a result of another field being filled in, or having a certain value, make sure this link still works</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Perform an End to End test as described <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/iaptus/self-referrals/testing-new-self-referral-forms\">here</a></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Notes:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Especially on the older forms, it is likely that &quot;priority&quot; of fields may change, this is&nbsp;<strong>fine</strong>, provided the rule below still holds.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements on the form may have the same priority, if this has happened, there&#39;s a bug with the form builder and this needs to be raised ASAP.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements may have the same &quot;name&quot;, otherwise data in the second element will overwrite that in the first.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:28:20','2016-08-24 15:28:20',NULL),(128,47,16,'Testing Changes to Self Referral Forms','A slightly shorter test plan for use only when testing updates to an existing form.','<p><var><span class=\"marker\">NOTE: This test plan may *ONLY* be used when testing updates to an existing form that has been approved as a suitable base with which to compare changes. Speak to FD if you&#39;re not sure whether its use is appropriate.&nbsp;</span></var></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>You Will Need:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n	<li>Access to bpvnode13 (Paywall/Bacpac&nbsp;Testing) and bpvnode14 (Paywall Live)</li>\r\n	<li>Access to the databases on the aforementioned servers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;base&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table (`spec` column)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>This will, in most cases, be from the&nbsp;<strong>LIVE</strong>&nbsp;Paywall Database.</li>\r\n		<li>However, if you&#39;re updating a form that has not yet gone live, then someone should have taken a backup copy as a base from the testing database&nbsp;before updates were made&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Grab the &quot;updated&quot; form JSON from the form_configs table of the Paywall Test database</li>\r\n	<li>Run both JSONs through the&nbsp;<strong>same&nbsp;</strong>JSON prettyfier, so that you get two lots of data that have the same formatting</li>\r\n	<li>Perform a file diff between the two files, to see what changes have been made\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>If there&#39;s a lot of fields changed that you weren&#39;t expecting or can&#39;t sufficently explain,&nbsp;refer this back to FD and discuss whether a full test may be more appropriate</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>For each element changed, check that the element still works as you would expect it to against the spec by using the updated version of the form:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Check that the right fields are &quot;required&quot;</li>\r\n		<li>Check element ordering on the form</li>\r\n		<li>Check the fields labels and types:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In the case of select/radio, check the option values&nbsp;and their order (including the back-end &quot;submitted&quot; value) are the same as the old version</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check validation:\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>No field on the form should accept -- (double hyphen), #, &lt; or &gt; due to SQL injection concerns.</li>\r\n			<li>If the specification mentions special validation rules, check those too</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Check dependencies\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>In a case where the field can be required as a result of another field being filled in, or having a certain value, make sure this link still works</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>Perform an End to End test as described <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/iaptus/self-referrals/testing-new-self-referral-forms\">here</a></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h1>Notes:</h1>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Especially on the older forms, it is likely that &quot;priority&quot; of fields may change, this is&nbsp;<strong>fine</strong>, provided the rule below still holds.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements on the form may have the same priority, if this has happened, there&#39;s a bug with the form builder and this needs to be raised ASAP.</li>\r\n	<li>No two elements may have the same &quot;name&quot;, otherwise data in the second element will overwrite that in the first.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:28:30','2016-08-24 15:28:30',NULL),(129,50,26,'iaptus','How to get a local version of iaptus running and work with it','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What is iaptus?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus is the core product here at Mayden and assumes the majority of all development time. It is a patient management system for mental health services and, among other things, allows services to track and report on&nbsp;patient care, accept referrals from patients and refer them on to othert mental health care providers, and communicate with patients via letters and SMSs. If you&#39;re new to iaptus, you will probably have some dedicated iaptus training which will inform you more fully on the capabilities of the iaptus system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;For the First Time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These instructions assume that you have a working vagrant VM in which to run iaptus. If you do not, follow the instructions layed out in the <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Setting Up Vagrant</a> article before continuing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step to setting iaptus up locally is cloning the iaptus repository inside an <code>html</code>&nbsp;directory inside&nbsp;your PHP 5.6 vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /path/to/your/php56/vagrant/box</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir html</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>git clone&nbsp;git@github.com:may-den/iaptus.git</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the dependencies have finished installing, you need to SSH into your vagrant box and run the iaptus&nbsp;build scripts:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to select a &#39;build and create&#39; type, select whichever option you prefer. &#39;1&#39; will suffix database names with whichever git branch you are on, &#39;2&#39; won&#39;t&nbsp;so each time iaptus is built, your local databases will be dropped and rebuilt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to continue connecting with the given RSA fingerprint, enter &#39;yes&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also be asked for a GitHub Token. You will find this in the Mayden 1Password vault and it should be pasted into the terminal now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the build script finishes, you should be able to go to&nbsp;<code><a href=\"http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php\">http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php</a></code> in your browser and access the aptus login page. You can use the username &#39;superuser&#39; and password &#39;biddestone4211&#39; to log in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;After Checking Out&nbsp;a New Branch</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each time you checkout a different branch of the iaptus repository, iaptus will need to be rebuilt:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessing Your Local Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to download a database tool such as SequelPro, Heidi or MySQL Workbench. On a PHP 5.6 box, you should be able to access your database using the following credentials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Host:&nbsp;192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Username: root</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What To Do Next</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol><br />\r\n	<li>Explore the codebase and ask someone to explain the key parts of the iaptus repository to you</li>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<li>Log into your local database and ask someone to explain the key tables to you</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:52:11','2016-08-24 15:52:11',NULL),(130,50,26,'iaptus','How to get a local version of iaptus running and work with it','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What is iaptus?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus is the core product here at Mayden and assumes the majority of all development time. It is a patient management system for mental health services and, among other things, allows services to track and report on&nbsp;patient care, accept referrals from patients and refer them on to othert mental health care providers, and communicate with patients via letters and SMSs. If you&#39;re new to iaptus, you will probably have some dedicated iaptus training which will inform you more fully on the capabilities of the iaptus system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;For the First Time</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>These instructions assume that you have a working vagrant VM in which to run iaptus. If you do not, follow the instructions layed out in the <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Setting Up Vagrant</a> article before continuing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step to setting iaptus up locally is cloning the iaptus repository inside an <code>html</code>&nbsp;directory inside&nbsp;your PHP 5.6 vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /path/to/your/php56/vagrant/box</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir html</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>git clone&nbsp;git@github.com:may-den/iaptus.git</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the dependencies have finished installing, you need to SSH into your vagrant box and run the iaptus&nbsp;build scripts:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to select a &#39;build and create&#39; type, select whichever option you prefer. &#39;1&#39; will suffix database names with whichever git branch you are on, &#39;2&#39; won&#39;t&nbsp;so each time iaptus is built, your local databases will be dropped and rebuilt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to continue connecting with the given RSA fingerprint, enter &#39;yes&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also be asked for a GitHub Token. You will find this in the Mayden 1Password vault and it should be pasted into the terminal now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the build script finishes, you should be able to go to&nbsp;<code><a href=\"http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php\">http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php</a></code> in your browser and access the aptus login page. You can use the username &#39;superuser&#39; and password &#39;biddestone4211&#39; to log in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;After Checking Out&nbsp;a New Branch</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each time you checkout a different branch of the iaptus repository, iaptus will need to be rebuilt:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessing Your Local Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to download a database tool such as SequelPro, Heidi or MySQL Workbench. On a PHP 5.6 box, you should be able to access your database using the following credentials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Host:&nbsp;192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Username: root</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What To Do Next</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol><br />\r\n	<li>Explore the codebase and ask someone to explain the key parts of the iaptus repository to you</li>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<li>Log into your local database and ask someone to explain the key tables to you</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:52:26','2016-08-24 15:52:26',NULL),(131,50,26,'iaptus','How to get a local version of iaptus running and work with it','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What is iaptus?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>iaptus is the core product here at Mayden and assumes the majority of all development time. It is a patient management system for mental health services and, among other things, allows services to track and report on&nbsp;patient care, accept referrals from patients and refer them on to othert mental health care providers, and communicate with patients via letters and SMSs. If you&#39;re new to iaptus, you will probably have some dedicated iaptus training which will inform you more fully on the capabilities of the iaptus system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;For the First Time</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>These instructions assume that you have a working vagrant VM in which to run iaptus. If you do not, follow the instructions layed out in the <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Setting Up Vagrant</a> article before continuing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first step to setting iaptus up locally is cloning the iaptus repository inside an <code>html</code>&nbsp;directory inside&nbsp;your PHP 5.6 vagrant box:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /path/to/your/php56/vagrant/box</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>mkdir html</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>git clone&nbsp;git@github.com:may-den/iaptus.git</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the dependencies have finished installing, you need to SSH into your vagrant box and run the iaptus&nbsp;build scripts:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to select a &#39;build and create&#39; type, select whichever option you prefer. &#39;1&#39; will suffix database names with whichever git branch you are on, &#39;2&#39; won&#39;t&nbsp;so each time iaptus is built, your local databases will be dropped and rebuilt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When prompted to continue connecting with the given RSA fingerprint, enter &#39;yes&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also be asked for a GitHub Token. You will find this in the Mayden 1Password vault and it should be pasted into the terminal now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the build script finishes, you should be able to go to&nbsp;<code><a href=\"http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php\">http://192.168.20.56/iaptus/html/index.php</a></code> in your browser and access the aptus login page. You can use the username &#39;superuser&#39; and password &#39;biddestone4211&#39; to log in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting Up iaptus:&nbsp;After Checking Out&nbsp;a New Branch</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each time you checkout a different branch of the iaptus repository, iaptus will need to be rebuilt:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>vagrant ssh</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html/iaptus/build/dev</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>phing build</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessing Your Local Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to download a database tool such as SequelPro, Heidi or MySQL Workbench. On a PHP 5.6 box, you should be able to access your database using the following credentials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Host:&nbsp;192.168.20.56</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Username: root</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What To Do Next</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol><br />\r\n	<li>Explore the codebase and ask someone to explain the key parts of the iaptus repository to you</li>\r\n	<li>Log into your local database and ask someone to explain the key tables to you</li>\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-24 15:52:39','2016-08-24 15:52:39',NULL),(132,49,29,'Manually Adding Care Pathway Links','How to add a link from a care pathway so it appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually add links to care pathways. This must be done on the Demo. To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs adding. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be added, making note of the ID for the &#39;from&#39; stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the &#39;to&#39; stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also need to find your next LINK_ID -&nbsp;this should be the next autoincrement value in the nh_stage_process table, e.g. if the highest existing id is 2000, your link ID will be 2001&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, you need to write the XML for your new link:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&amp;lt;link id=&amp;quot;LINK_ID&amp;quot; name=&amp;quot;lineLINK_ID&amp;quot; direction=&amp;quot;down&amp;quot; source=&amp;quot;rectangleSTAGE_FROM_ID&amp;quot; target=&amp;quot;rectangleSTAGE_TO_ID&amp;quot; xCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; yCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; hidden=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; archived=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot;/&amp;gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&amp;lt;link id=&amp;quot;200&amp;quot; name=&amp;quot;line200&amp;quot; direction=&amp;quot;down&amp;quot; source=&amp;quot;rectangle22&amp;quot; target=&amp;quot;rectangle44&amp;quot; xCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; yCoords=&amp;quot;0,0&amp;quot; hidden=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; archived=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot;/&amp;gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These links then need to be added to the XML file for this service in the latest non-auto-saved nh_diagram row. It should be appended to the section with the other links in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This adds the links to the care pathway diagram tool. To carry these changes over to the iaptus care pathway section, you should&nbsp;export the SQL from the Mayden Care Pathway Tool (as you would when putting a care pathway live) and run the resulting SQL on demo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to check that it is now possible to travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus using your link. When you have a patient in the &#39;stage from&#39; stage, it should now&nbsp;be possible to process the patient onto the &#39;to stage&#39; as you removed the link.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 08:48:07','2016-08-25 08:48:07',NULL),(133,21,1,'Sequel Pro DB Connection Favourites','Database favourites that can be imported into Sequel Pro.','<p>This file contains a series of connections compatible with the openssh port forwardings found in developer-standards. Copy and paste these into an editor and save as &quot;favourites.plist&quot;, then import into Sequel Pro by clicking the cog icon on the bottom left of the connections list, and selecting the file we just created.</p>\r\