ition of Done</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Bamboo admin to create Bamboo account\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the difference between the different plans</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 14:49:35','2016-08-25 14:49:35',NULL),(143,32,23,'New Developer Setup','A few things to cover when getting a new starter set up in an iaptus team.','<h3>Get Set Up With the Core Mayden Tools:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/set-up-1password\">Set up 1Password</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-github\">Set up a GitHub account and SSH keys</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">Set up your local Vagrant environment</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Set Up the Main Mayden Projects Locally:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/projects/iaptus\">iaptus</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Get Familiar With Jira and Bamboo</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Ask Jira admin to create Jira account</li>\r\n	<li>Explain the dashboard</li>\r\n	<li>Go to an issue (preferrably a well documented one!)\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the different types of issues</li>\r\n		<li>Explain which issues branch off where</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the workflow diagram</li>\r\n		<li>Explain the different fields</li>\r\n		<li>Definition of Done</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Bamboo admin to create Bamboo account\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Explain the difference between the different plans</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 14:55:19','2016-08-25 14:55:19',NULL),(144,52,31,'Set up Local Development Environment','how to get a local copy of the bacpac application on a virtual machine and get everything working','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>A Springloops account</li>\r\n	<li>SSH keys set up on Springloops for the bacpac project</li>\r\n	<li>Appropriate permissions on Springloops for bacpac dependent modules (listed in composer.json)</li>\r\n	<li>A working <a href=\"http://black-box.mayden.co.uk/p/new-starters/set-up/setting-up-vagrant\">vagrant virtual machine</a> on your laptop&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create a folder in an appropriate place on your computer called &#39;bacpac&#39; and move into that directory</li>\r\n	<li>Create a folder within the bacpac folder called html and move into that directory</li>\r\n	<li>Do <code>git clone&nbsp;ssh://sls@slsapp.com:1234/mayden/bacpac.git</code> in the html&nbsp;directory&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Go to up to date copy of the Mayden vagrant-vms repository and get a copy of the Vagrantfile from the bacpac directory in that repository. Copy the vagrantfile into the bacpac directory created at step 1. above.</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the Vagrantfile from step 3. as follows:&nbsp;<code>config.vm.network &quot;private_network&quot;, ip: &quot;192.168.20.31&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Use the <code>vagrant up</code> command to start the vagrant box from inside the top level bacpac directory created at step 1.</li>\r\n	<li>When the machine is up and ready (you will need to enter your password to permit the file syncing with the Vagrant box) go to the bacpac code folder (<em>still in your host machine</em>) and do composer install <code>cd html/bacpac; </code>chmod +x composer.phar;&nbsp;<code>./composer.phar install; cd -</code></li>\r\n	<li>Use the <code>vagrant ssh</code> command to start a shell session to the vagrant box</li>\r\n	<li>From within the vagrant box go to /var/www/html/bacpac/build directory and create a new file <code>build.properties</code> at the same level as the build.properties.example file. Copy the contents from the section below (build.properties) into the new build.properties file.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>From within the build file in the vagrant box run <code>ant rebuild</code></li>\r\n	<li>Still in the vagrant box go to /etc/httpd/conf.d and edit the bacpac.conf file so that the DocumentRoot is <code>/var/www/html/bacpac/public</code> and change the Directory path two lines below to match</li>\r\n	<li>Restart the apache server for the changes in step 11 to take effect. You should now be able to go to &nbsp;the URL 192.168.20.31 in a browser on your host machine and see the bacpac login page.</li>\r\n	<li>To connect to the bacpac databases running in the vagrant box (for example with Sequel Pro) on your host machine use host: 127.0.0.1 &nbsp;port: 4040 &nbsp;username: root &nbsp;password: vagrant</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>build.properties</h3>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><code>db.username=root<br />\r\ndb.ip=127.0.0.1<br />\r\ndb.host=localhost<br />\r\ndb.password=vagrant<br />\r\ndb.database=bacp_trunk<br />\r\ndb.test_database=bacp_trunk_test<br />\r\ndb.app.username=root<br />\r\ndb.app.password=vagrant<br />\r\nowner=rick<br />\r\ngroup=wheel<br />\r\nbuild.dir=.<br />\r\nroot.dir=/var/www/html/bacpac<br />\r\nbase.url=<br />\r\nemail.bacp.support.username=noreply.bacpac@mayden.co.uk<br />\r\nemail.bacp.support.password=MyP2NdzzGRsZe7tHPedR<br />\r\nfunctionaltest_url=http://bacpac.test<br />\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://jenkins.may:4444/wd/hub<br />\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://10.1.16.28:4444/wd/hub<br />\r\n#functionaltest_hub_url=http://192.168.20.1:4444/wd/hub<br />\r\nfunctionaltest_hub_url=http://10.0.2.2:4444/wd/hub<br />\r\n#unctionaltest_hub_url=http://rick.hewes@dWxKNVWWd6F1GShQXbKm@hub.browserstack.com/wd/hub<br />\r\nselenium.host=bacpac.test<br />\r\nenvironment=development<br />\r\nradius.ip=10.1.16.208<br />\r\nradius.api_key=sdfdfgRJnKyd6abQsdfsdfsdfsdfZf4BhF3Dqu06hhAZxJsdf<br />\r\nbacp.api_username = MaydenBacPac<br />\r\nbacp.api_password = ja9REbRu<br />\r\nrecurly.url=https://mayden-test.recurly.com<br />\r\nrecurly.api_key=4c969b92f7604533989f79a6dfa4bb3b<br />\r\nmonitor.url=http://external.may/bacpac_mon/portal.php<br />\r\nadmin.delete_key=rick<br />\r\n#gpdata.url=http://localhost/Pathways/paywall/public/gpdata<br />\r\ngpdata.url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk/gpdata<br />\r\ngpdata.api_key=tyuibghjkbyt7uy7804688nkhu579y78y7606708y7ubyhuyu2<br />\r\ndoctrine.generate.proxies=Doctrine\\\\Common\\\\Proxy\\\\AbstractProxyFactory::AUTOGENERATE_ALWAYS<br />\r\npaywall.url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk<br />\r\nmayselfreferral.paywall_self_referral_api_key=a439bb7e-d4dc-47d3-8ff4-208a8c275a2f<br />\r\nmayselfreferral.paywall_self_referral_url=localhost/Pathways/paywall/referral-api<br />\r\nmayselfreferral.referral_form_base_url=https://test-signup.bac-pac.co.uk/referral/</code></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 15:24:02','2016-08-25 15:24:02',NULL),(145,53,17,'Core Iaptus Databases','Information on the core databases for the iaptus application ','<h3>Core iaptus databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The iaptus application uses 3 core databases:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><code>iaptus</code> database&nbsp;-&nbsp;for which there is normally one database per iaptus service containing data for that service</li>\r\n	<li><code>global&nbsp;</code>database&nbsp;-&nbsp;where there is one per live server/server&nbsp;cluster&nbsp;which contains data that is common for all iaptus clients (e.g. definitions of reports or tags used in iaptus). All global databases need to be kept in sync.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><code>shared </code>database -<strong>&nbsp;</strong>a single database instance containing common data that could potentially&nbsp;be used by other mayden applications&nbsp;(e.g. national gp practice data, national healthcare provider data). The shared database for live sites is located in the Bracknell datacentre.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>* See multi-service databases below however</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Multi-Service Databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There are however some cases where you find multiple services sharing a single iaptus database:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Demo - all iaptus services start off with a demo site so the<strong> demo iaptus database contains all the iaptus services</strong> <strong>ever created,</strong> and is also the source of the iaptus service id numbers&nbsp;(auto-increment on nh_service demo database table). &nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Local Development - on our local development environment the database contains several services so we can easily test code in a multi-service scenario and also log-in as different services with different sets of test data.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Live Sites - there are a few instances where two or even three related clients have been set up on a single live site database. This is not being done going forward and some have since been separated out, but at the time of writing there is at least one live site iaptus database that contains three separate services.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Demo Database Missing Global Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A further anomaly worth noting is that for historical reasons the iaptus demo site has no separate global database - instead the tables from the iaptus database and the iaptus global database are mixed together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 15:30:46','2016-08-25 15:30:46',NULL),(146,53,17,'Core Iaptus Databases','Information on the core databases for the iaptus application ','<h3>Core iaptus databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The iaptus application uses 3 core databases:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><code>iaptus</code> database&nbsp;-&nbsp;for which there is normally one database per iaptus service containing data for that service</li>\r\n	<li><code>global</code>&nbsp;database&nbsp;-&nbsp;where there is one per live server/server&nbsp;cluster&nbsp;which contains data that is common for all iaptus clients (e.g. definitions of reports or tags used in iaptus). All global databases need to be kept in sync.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><code>shared</code> database -<strong>&nbsp;</strong>a single database instance containing common data that could potentially&nbsp;be used by other mayden applications&nbsp;(e.g. national gp practice data, national healthcare provider data). The shared database for live sites is located in the Bracknell datacentre.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>* See multi-service databases below however</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Multi-Service Databases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There are however some cases where you find multiple services sharing a single iaptus database:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Demo - all iaptus services start off with a demo site so the<strong> demo iaptus database contains all the iaptus services</strong> <strong>ever created,</strong> and is also the source of the iaptus service id numbers&nbsp;(auto-increment on nh_service demo database table). &nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Local Development - on our local development environment the database contains several services so we can easily test code in a multi-service scenario and also log-in as different services with different sets of test data.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>Live Sites - there are a few instances where two or even three related clients have been set up on a single live site database. This is not being done going forward and some have since been separated out, but at the time of writing there is at least one live site iaptus database that contains three separate services.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Demo Database Missing Global Database</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A further anomaly worth noting is that for historical reasons the iaptus demo site has no separate global database - instead the tables from the iaptus database and the iaptus global database are mixed together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-25 15:32:17','2016-08-25 15:32:17',NULL),(147,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server&nbsp;as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n	<li>Rename local copy demo database to &quot;i<code>aptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new empty local database called&nbsp; &quot;i<code>aptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database&nbsp;details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;file at&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code>&nbsp;by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n	<li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n	<li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or&nbsp;CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code><!--?php<br /--> require(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc&#39;);<br />\r\nrequire(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;SCORING_CLASS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/&#39;); define(&#39;MYSQL_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;IAPTUS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/iaptus/trunk/html&#39;);<br />\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)<br />\r\n{<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(&#39;/var/www/html/&#39;, &#39;&#39;, $trace[0][&#39;file&#39;]).&#39; Line: &#39;.$trace[0][&#39;line&#39;].&#39; Msg: &#39;.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\nerror_log(&#39;MySQL Error: &#39;.$report);<br />\r\ndie(&#39;An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files&#39;);<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br />\r\n}</code></p>\r\n',1,30,'2016-08-25 16:45:14','2016-08-25 16:45:14',NULL),(148,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server&nbsp;as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n	<li>Rename local copy demo database to &quot;i<code>aptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new empty local database called&nbsp; &quot;i<code>aptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database&nbsp;details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;file at&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code>&nbsp;by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n	<li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n	<li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or&nbsp;CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code><!--?php<br /--> require(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc&#39;);<br />\r\nrequire(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;SCORING_CLASS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/&#39;); define(&#39;MYSQL_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;IAPTUS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/iaptus/trunk/html&#39;);<br />\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)<br />\r\n{<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(&#39;/var/www/html/&#39;, &#39;&#39;, $trace[0][&#39;file&#39;]).&#39; Line: &#39;.$trace[0][&#39;line&#39;].&#39; Msg: &#39;.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\nerror_log(&#39;MySQL Error: &#39;.$report);<br />\r\ndie(&#39;An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files&#39;);<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br />\r\n}</code></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-26 09:04:35','2016-08-26 09:04:35',NULL),(149,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server&nbsp;as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n	<li>Rename local copy demo database to &quot;i<code>aptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new empty local database called&nbsp; &quot;i<code>aptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database&nbsp;details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to&nbsp;file at&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file&nbsp;<code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code>&nbsp;by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n	<li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n	<li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or&nbsp;CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><code><!--?php<br /--> require(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc&#39;);<br />\r\nrequire(&#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;SCORING_CLASS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/&#39;); define(&#39;MYSQL_PATH&#39;, &#39;/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/&#39;);<br />\r\ndefine(&#39;IAPTUS_PATH&#39;, &#39;/iaptus/trunk/html&#39;);<br />\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)<br />\r\n{<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(&#39;/var/www/html/&#39;, &#39;&#39;, $trace[0][&#39;file&#39;]).&#39; Line: &#39;.$trace[0][&#39;line&#39;].&#39; Msg: &#39;.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\nerror_log(&#39;MySQL Error: &#39;.$report);<br />\r\ndie(&#39;An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files&#39;);<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br />\r\n}</code></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-08-26 09:04:51','2016-08-26 09:04:51',NULL),(150,8,3,'Features of Valuable Tests','A description of the types of things whihc make a test \'valuable\' and worth running on Mayden code.','<p><strong>General:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Should actually test something &mdash; if you change functionality then the test should break</li>\r\n	<li>Should always pass regardless of the order tests are run in</li>\r\n	<li>Should always pass regardless of the order tests are created&nbsp;in</li>\r\n	<li>Should be completely independant of the rest of the suite</li>\r\n	<li>Must always contain at least one assertion</li>\r\n	<li>Should never be skipped (even conditionally skipped) without a good reason</li>\r\n	<li>Should contain minimal (preferably no) outside dependencies, in both tests and code under test</li>\r\n	<li>Should not share state between tests &mdash; this increases the risk of tests interfering with each other and results in much more brittle tests</li>\r\n	<li>Should have good, descriptive names &mdash; no one is going to type it so make it as long as you need to fully explain what the test is doing</li>\r\n	<li>Test method names should be camelCased as this is PSR-2, even if some frameworks (e.g. PHPSpec) like snake case</li>\r\n	<li>When using PHPUnit (includes Codeception unit &amp; integration/functional) always start test methods with &lsquo;test&rsquo; rather than use PHPUnit&rsquo;s @test annotation</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain the pyramid &mdash; don&rsquo;t write 10 acceptance tests and 1 unit test for a feature</li>\r\n	<li>Use the variable names &ldquo;actual&rdquo; and &ldquo;expected&rdquo; in assertions</li>\r\n	<li>Use the &ldquo;expected&rdquo; and &ldquo;actual&rdquo; parameters to assertions correctly &mdash; in PHPUnit assertions are assertion($expected, $actual), in almost every other testing framework it&rsquo;s assertion(actual, expected)</li>\r\n	<li>Employ common sense &mdash; if you have a good reason to do something then it&rsquo;s probably ok, so long as it&rsquo;s a good reason</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Unit Tests:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Ideally one assertion per test &mdash; having to use more than one assertion may indicate your unit is doing too much and should be split up. There are exceptions to this and partial refactors of legacy code may not be perfect so sometimes multiple exceptions may be acceptable</li>\r\n	<li>Use PHPUnit Data Providers liberally (where it makes sense to &mdash; common sense etc&hellip;)</li>\r\n	<li>Test a unit at a time</li>\r\n	<li>Use Prophecy rather than PHPUnit mocking</li>\r\n	<li>Don&rsquo;t mock the class you&rsquo;re testing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Integration Tests:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Don&rsquo;t mock anything, you should be testing in as close to a live environment as possible</li>\r\n	<li>Try to always test a combination of units as the goal is to check a piece of functionality works in its entirety</li>\r\n	<li>Don&rsquo;t just repeat a unit test but without using mocks as this provides very little additional value</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Acceptance Tests:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Must only be a high level check of a feature (i.e. saving the New Patient form &amp; checking it stored the patient record correctly)</li>\r\n	<li>Don&rsquo;t test validation &mdash; use unit &amp; integration tests for this</li>\r\n	<li>Test combinations of conditionals in unit &amp; integration tests</li>\r\n	<li>Only write new acceptance tests as a last resort if a feature can&rsquo;t be unit or integration tested, but consider if the value added by the acceptance test is worth it</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,16,'2016-08-26 12:53:47','2016-08-30 09:15:04',NULL),(151,52,31,'Set up Local Development Environment','how to get a local copy of the bacpac application with a virtual machine and get everything working','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>A Springloops account</li>\r\n	<li>SSH keys set up on Springloops for the bacpac project</li>\r\n	<li>Appropriate permissions on Springloops for bacpac dependent modules (listed in composer.json)</li>\r\n	<li>Vagrant software installed on your laptop</li>\r\n	<li>Copy of the Mayden <a href=\"https://github.com/may-den/vagrant-vms\" target=\"_blank\">vagrant-vms</a> repository from GitHub</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Create a folder in an appropriate place on your computer called &#39;bacpac&#39; and move into that directory</li>\r\n	<li>Create a folder within the bacpac folder called html and move into that directory</li>\r\n	<li>Do <code>git clone&nbsp;ssh://sls@slsapp.com:1234/mayden/bacpac.git</code> in the html&nbsp;directory&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Go to up to date copy of the Mayden vagrant-vms repository and get a copy of the Vagrantfile from the bacpac directory in that repository. Copy the vagrantfile into the bacpac directory created at ste