omething like this:\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>$globalsConfig[\'myNewAwesomeGlobalName\'] = array(\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'description\' =&gt; \'Enable the new awesome global\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'formFieldType\' =&gt; \'radio\'\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'varValues\' =&gt; array(\'enabled\' =&gt; \'1\', \'disabled\' =&gt; \'0\')\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; \'var_type\' =&gt; \'copyName\'\r\n);</pre></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 15:57:28','2016-09-13 15:57:28',NULL),(186,56,7,'Adding/Changing Patient Tab Navigation','How to add or change the patient tabs','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Adding a New Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Adding a new tab usually involves writing a patch to update some data in a service\'s database, since there are a finite number of tabs and \'adding\' a new one usually actually involves editing an existing one. Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table, and will have a <code>per_tabName</code> column which tells you what type of tab you\'re looking at. The tab you\'ll find yourself changing the most often will be the Assessment tabs for example, whose type is \'assessment\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Editing an Existing Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table. You should locate the one you want to change and use its ID to make a patch which updates this row. From this table, you can change the tab\'s name and display order. The following is an example of a patch which changes the order. TYhese kinds of patches should be stored in the <code>mysql/service_patches</code> directory and include the audit log query that inserts a row into <code>db_patches</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (\'20160830-NAME_OF_THE_PATCH.sql\', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), \'YOUR_MYSQL_USERNAME\', \'\');\r\nUPDATE `nh_userPermission` SET `per_order`=NEW_ORDER&nbsp;where `per_id`=PERMISSION_ID;</pre><br />\r\n </p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 15:58:15','2016-09-13 15:58:15',NULL),(187,56,7,'Adding/Changing Patient Tab Navigation','How to add or change the patient tabs','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Live access</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Adding a New Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Adding a new tab usually involves writing a patch to update some data in a service\'s database, since there are a finite number of tabs and \'adding\' a new one usually actually involves editing an existing one. Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table, and will have a <code>per_tabName</code> column which tells you what type of tab you\'re looking at. The tab you\'ll find yourself changing the most often will be the Assessment tabs for example, whose type is \'assessment\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Editing an Existing Tab</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Each tab is stored in the <code>nh_userPermission</code> table. You should locate the one you want to change and use its ID to make a patch which updates this row. From this table, you can change the tab\'s name and display order. The following is an example of a patch which changes the order. TYhese kinds of patches should be stored in the <code>mysql/service_patches</code> directory and include the audit log query that inserts a row into <code>db_patches</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (\'20160830-NAME_OF_THE_PATCH.sql\', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), \'YOUR_MYSQL_USERNAME\', \'\');\r\n\r\nUPDATE `nh_userPermission` SET `per_order`=NEW_ORDER&nbsp;where `per_id`=PERMISSION_ID;</pre>\r\n </p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 15:58:26','2016-09-13 15:58:26',NULL),(188,39,7,'Turn On SMS For A Service','How to get a service set up with SMS','<h1>SMS Setup</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>To enable SMS for a service, all it requires is a patch, though this patch will be different, depending on whether the service is CYP or Adult.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Common Patch</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The common part of the patch is as follows, do <strong>note </strong>that some of these variables may already exist in their database, so you need to check this before writing the patch.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n# Set service ID and set global vars (note: some of these may already exist in the database so check first)\r\nSET @ser_id = 100; \r\n\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_global` (`var_name`, `var_value`, `var_type`, `ser_id`, `live`, `Notes`) \r\nSELECT \'smsDaysAdvance\', \'2\', NULL, @ser_id, 1, \'Max 26 days (less than the shortest month)\' FROM nh_service WHERE ser_id = @ser_id;\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_global` (`var_name`, `var_value`, `var_type`, `ser_id`, `live`, `Notes`) \r\nSELECT \'smsDaysAdvanceQueue\', \'3\', NULL, @ser_id, 1, NULL FROM nh_service WHERE ser_id = @ser_id;\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_global` (`var_name`, `var_value`, `var_type`, `ser_id`, `live`, `Notes`) \r\nSELECT \'smsMasterswitch\', \'1\', NULL, @ser_id, 1, \'\' FROM nh_service WHERE ser_id = @ser_id;\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_global` (`var_name`, `var_value`, `var_type`, `ser_id`, `live`, `Notes`) \r\nSELECT \'smsTime\', \'12\', NULL, @ser_id, 1, \'\' FROM nh_service WHERE ser_id = @ser_id;\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h2>Adult Service</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>If the service is an <strong>Adult Service </strong>then you need to add the following to the patch, to provide them with SMS templates that use Adult MDS values:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n# Insert some default templates that are disabled\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_sms_templates` (`sms_type`, `mds_refId`, `type`, `ser_id`, `message_template`, `live`) \r\nSELECT 3, 116, \'Face-to-face\', ser_id, \'You have a group appointment at [--------LOCATION--------] on [-------DATE-------] at [-TIME-]\', 0 FROM nh_service WHERE ser_id = @ser_id;\r\nINSERT INTO `nh_sms_templates` (`sms_type`, `mds_refId`, `type`, `ser_id`, `message_template`, `live`) \r\nSELECT 3, 117, \'Telephone\', 