de>superuserhull</code>. You can find the password in Keepass under <code>Projects &gt; IAPTus &gt; Websites &gt; Demo</code>.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the \'Care Pathway (Mayden Only)\' link under the Superuser menu.</li>\r\n	<li>Scroll to the \'Care Pathway Sync Tool\' section of the page, which will be close to the bottom. Ensure that the dropdown says \'LIVE\' and then click \'Export\'.</li>\r\n	<li>Open the downloaded file in a text editor and add the following insert statement to the top, to log the patch running:<br />\r\n	<ul><li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre># Changing \'PATCH_FILENAME_HERE\' to the name you will save this patch under and&nbsp;\'DB_USERNAME_HERE\' to your database username\r\n	INSERT INTO db_patches (filename, startDate, endDate, user, logFile) VALUES (\'PATCH_FILENAME_HERE.sql\', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), \'DB_USERNAME_HERE\', \'\');</pre></li></ul></li>\r\n	<li>Check the patch file and make sure the value of <strong>id </strong>column in <strong>nh_stage</strong> table and<strong> id, stage_from</strong> and <strong>stage_to</strong> columns in <strong>nh_stage_process</strong> table are always less than <strong>100,000</strong>. Double check that the ser_id values in the patch match the ser_id in the nh_service table of the live database to confirm you have picked up the right care pathway from demo.</li>\r\n	<li>Download the nh_stage_process and nh_stage table from the live customer\'s database.  Import them into a local database.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the Care Pathway patch (leaving out the last four queries where tables get dropped and renamed) on your local database server, in the same database as the customer\'s imported tables.</li>\r\n	<li>Run the following query on your local database:\r\n	<ul><li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>\r\nSELECT * \r\nFROM nh_stage_process\r\nLEFT JOIN nh_stage_process_tempVersion ON nh_stage_process.`id` = nh_stage_process_tempVersion.`id`\r\nWHERE nh_stage_process.stage_from != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_from\r\nOR nh_stage_process.stage_to != nh_stage_process_tempVersion.stage_to</pre></li></ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>If any results are returned, new process IDs that link stage_from and stage_to together no longer hold the same stages as they did on the live site.  This will lead to data corruption.  If rows are returned DO NOT DEPLOY THE CARE PATHWAY.  Instead revert the broken Care Pathway on the demo site to a previously stable version.</li>\r\n	<li>Save the patch in the <code>/mysql/service_patches</code> folder.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The patch filename should be the current timestamp with no delimiter, followed by the service name, followed by a brief description of the patch (all separated by dashes), for example:<br />\r\n	<code>20160505-hull-care-pathway-to-go-live.sql</code></li>\r\n	<li>Don\'t forget to make a note on Jira that the patch will need to be run manually</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:03:55','2016-09-13 16:03:55',NULL),(198,48,29,'Manually Removing Care Pathway Links','How to remove a link from a care pathway so it no longer appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually remove links from care pathways. This must be done on the Demo site and the link itself must <strong>not </strong>be deleted - only archived/\'olded\'. To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n \r\n <hr />\r\n <p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs deleting. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be removed, making note of the ID for the \'from\' stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the \'to\' stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Next, use these IDs to find the link in the nh_stage_process table and change the live column from <code>1</code> to <code>0</code>:</p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>UPDATE nh_stage_process SET live=0 WHERE stage_from=STAGE_FROM_ID AND stage_to=STAGE_TO_ID;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Finally, you need to set the link in the XML to archived too. You can find the XML in the nh_diagram table. Open the XML in a text editor and locate the link which needs archiving. You will be able to find it by removing the service id and \'00\' from the beginning of the STAGE_FROM ID and STAGE_TO_ID and looking for the link with a source and target with this number in it. For example:</p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>SERVICE_ID = 160</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>STAGE_FROM_ID = 1600022</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>STAGE_TO_ID = 1600044</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;294&quot; name=&quot;line294&quot; direction=&quot;end&quot; source=&quot;rectangle22&quot; target=&quot;rectangle44&quot; xCoords=&quot;72,1823&quot; yCoords=&quot;42,473&quot; hidden=&quot;1&quot; archived=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>To archive the link, simply replace the <code>archived=&quot;0&quot;</code> part with <code>archived=&quot;1&quot;:</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;294&quot; name=&quot;line294&quot; direction=&quot;end&quot; source=&quot;rectangle22&quot; target=&quot;rectangle44&quot; xCoords=&quot;72,1823&quot; yCoords=&quot;42,473&quot; hidden=&quot;1&quot; archived=&quot;1&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Finally, you need to check that it is no longer possible travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus. When you have a patient in the \'stage from\' stage, it should not be possible to process the patient onto the \'to stage\' as you removed the link.</p>\r\n ',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:04:56','2016-09-13 16:04:56',NULL),(199,48,29,'Manually Removing Care Pathway Links','How to remove a link from a care pathway so it no longer appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually remove links from care pathways. This must be done on the Demo site and the link itself must <strong>not </strong>be deleted - only archived/\'olded\'. To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n \r\n <hr />\r\n <p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs deleting. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be removed, making note of the ID for the \'from\' stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the \'to\' stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Next, use these IDs to find the link in the nh_stage_process table and change the live column from <code>1</code> to <code>0</code>:</p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>UPDATE nh_stage_process SET live=0 WHERE stage_from=STAGE_FROM_ID AND stage_to=STAGE_TO_ID;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Finally, you need to set the link in the XML to archived too. You can find the XML in the nh_diagram table. Open the XML in a text editor and locate the link which needs archiving. You will be able to find it by removing the service id and \'00\' from the beginning of the STAGE_FROM ID and STAGE_TO_ID and looking for the link with a source and target with this number in it. For example:</p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>SERVICE_ID = 160</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>STAGE_FROM_ID = 1600022</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>STAGE_TO_ID = 1600044</code></p>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n <p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;294&quot; name=&quot;line294&quot; direction=&quot;end&quot; source=&quot;rectangle22&quot; target=&quot;rectangle44&quot; xCoords=&quot;72,1823&quot; yCoords=&quot;42,473&quot; hidden=&quot;1&quot; archived=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>To archive the link, simply replace the <code>archived=&quot;0&quot;</code> part with <code>archived=&quot;1&quot;:</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;294&quot; name=&quot;line294&quot; direction=&quot;end&quot; source=&quot;rectangle22&quot; target=&quot;rectangle44&quot; xCoords=&quot;72,1823&quot; yCoords=&quot;42,473&quot; hidden=&quot;1&quot; archived=&quot;1&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n \r\n <p> </p>\r\n \r\n <p>Finally, you need to check that it is no longer possible travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus. When you have a patient in the \'stage from\' stage, it should not be possible to process the patient onto the \'to stage\' as you removed the link.</p>\r\n ',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:05:16','2016-09-13 16:05:16',NULL),(200,49,29,'Manually Adding Care Pathway Links','How to add a link from a care pathway so it appears on the care pathway tools','<p>Where care pathway diagrams are too large to load in the care pathway diagram tool, it may be necessary manually add links to care pathways. This must be done on the Demo. To do so, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To start, you will need the IDs of the care pathway stages for which the link needs adding. You should locate the stages in the nh_stage table for which the link between needs to be added, making note of the ID for the \'from\' stage (where the patient would start out) and the ID for the \'to\' stage (where the patient could progress to). Make sure you have selected the stage for the correct service using the ser_id column.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will also need to find your next LINK_ID - this should be the next autoincrement value in the nh_stage_process table, e.g. if the highest existing id is 2000, your link ID will be 2001 </p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, you need to write the XML for your new link:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;LINK_ID&quot; name=&quot;lineLINK_ID&quot; direction=&quot;down&quot; source=&quot;rectangleSTAGE_FROM_ID&quot; target=&quot;rectangleSTAGE_TO_ID&quot; xCoords=&quot;0,0&quot; yCoords=&quot;0,0&quot; hidden=&quot;0&quot; archived=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><code>&lt;link id=&quot;200&quot; name=&quot;line200&quot; direction=&quot;down&quot; source=&quot;rectangle22&quot; target=&quot;rectangle44&quot; xCoords=&quot;0,0&quot; yCoords=&quot;0,0&quot; hidden=&quot;0&quot; archived=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These links then need to be added to the XML file for this service in the latest non-auto-saved nh_diagram row. It should be appended to the section with the other links in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p>This adds the links to the care pathway diagram tool. To carry these changes over to the iaptus care pathway section, you should export the SQL from the Mayden Care Pathway Tool (as you would when putting a care pathway live) and run the resulting SQL on demo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, you need to check that it is now possible to travel between the two stages in the Care Pathway section on iaptus using your link. When you have a patient in the \'stage from\' stage, it should now be possible to process the patient onto the \'to stage\' as you removed the link.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:06:02','2016-09-13 16:06:02',NULL),(201,55,29,'Adding a Step to a Care Pathway','How to add a step to a care pathway','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Access to demo</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To add a step which exists on demo to a service\'s care pathway, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Locate the step you want to add for a service in the IAPTus_Demo.nh_pathway_service table. You will need to copy this row and insert it into the nh_pathway_service table in the service\'s database:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li class=\"no-bullet\"><code>INSERT INTO `nh_pathway_service` (`pathway_service_id`, `code`, `title`, `step`, `prefix`)&nbsp;VALUES&nbsp;(data, from, the , demo, database);</code></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Find the latest non-auto-saved care pathway in IAPTus_Demo.nh_diagram and grab the XML from it.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the id of step from <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>to the list of comma separated values in the \'carepathway service\' tag</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the all of the XML blocks for the last step in the care pathway (e.g. all nodes for IAPT4) and paste them in below. You will need to update each node of these copied blocks according to the following:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>node_id: this needs to be updated with an incrementing number</li>\r\n		<li>level: this needs to be updated with the value of the \'step\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>serviceid: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'pathway_service_id\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>servicecode: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'code\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>other: any references to the original stage you copied in your pasted nodes need to be updated to the new stage, e.g. \'IAPT4 Refer On\' should become \'NEW_STAGE_CODE Refer On\' (where NEW_STAGE_CODE is the code of the new stage you are adding)</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Next, you need to add links from this new step onwards. Each link that the step you <em>copied </em>has, your new stage needs to have also. You should be able find the links for the copied step by doing a find on the node id. You may see multiple \'link\' tags containing \'source=\"rectangleNODE_ID\"\' or target=\"rectangleNODE_ID\" (where NODE_ID is the value in the \'id\' property of the node). Each of these needs copying and the NODE_ID replacing to reflect the new node ids. You need to paste the new links into the XML below the existing links.</li>\r\n	<li>Once the new XML is in place, you should update the row in the nh_diagram table with it and try to load it into the care pathway tool.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:06:46','2016-09-13 16:06:46',NULL),(202,55,29,'Adding a Step to a Care Pathway','How to add a step to a care pathway','<p>You will need:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Access to demo</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>To add a step which exists on demo to a service\'s care pathway, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Locate the step you want to add for a service in the IAPTus_Demo.nh_pathway_service table. You will need to copy this row and insert it into the nh_pathway_service table in the service\'s database:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li class=\"no-bullet\"><pre>INSERT INTO `nh_pathway_service` (`pathway_service_id`, `code`, `title`, `step`, `prefix`)&nbsp;VALUES&nbsp;(data, from, the , demo, database);</pre></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Find the latest non-auto-saved care pathway in IAPTus_Demo.nh_diagram and grab the XML from it.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the id of step from <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>to the list of comma separated values in the \'carepathway service\' tag</li>\r\n	<li>Copy the all of the XML blocks for the last step in the care pathway (e.g. all nodes for IAPT4) and paste them in below. You will need to update each node of these copied blocks according to the following:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>node_id: this needs to be updated with an incrementing number</li>\r\n		<li>level: this needs to be updated with the value of the \'step\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>serviceid: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'pathway_service_id\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>servicecode: this needs to be replaced with the value of the \'code\' column from the <code>nh_pathway_service&nbsp;</code>row you retrieved</li>\r\n		<li>other: any references to the original stage you copied in your pasted nodes need to be updated to the new stage, e.g. \'IAPT4 Refer On\' should become \'NEW_STAGE_CODE Refer On\' (where NEW_STAGE_CODE is the code of the new stage you are adding)</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Next, you need to add links from this new step onwards. Each link that the step you <em>copied </em>has, your new stage needs to have also. You should be able find the links for the copied step by doing a find on the node id. You may see multiple \'link\' tags containing \'source=\"rectangleNODE_ID\"\' or target=\"rectangleNODE_ID\" (where NODE_ID is the value in the \'id\' property of the node). Each of these needs copying and the NODE_ID replacing to reflect the new node ids. You need to paste the new links into the XML below the existing links.</li>\r\n	<li>Once the new XML is in place, you should update the row in the nh_diagram table with it and try to load it into the care pathway tool.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:08:42','2016-09-13 16:08:42',NULL),(203,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n	<li>Rename local copy demo database to \"<code>iaptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new empty local database called  \"<code>iaptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n	<li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n	<li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code> by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n	<li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n	<li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n	<li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables. </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>&lt;!--?php&lt;br /--&gt; require(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc\');&lt;br /&gt;\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc\');&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndefine(\'SCORING_CLASS_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/\'); define(\'MYSQL_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/\');&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndefine(\'IAPTUS_PATH\', \'/iaptus/trunk/html\');&lt;br /&gt;\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)&lt;br /&gt;\r\n{&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(\'/var/www/html/\', \'\', $trace[0][\'file\']).\' Line: \'.$trace[0][\'line\'].\' Msg: \'.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;\r\nerror_log(\'MySQL Error: \'.$report);&lt;br /&gt;\r\ndie(\'An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files\');&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }&lt;br /&gt;\r\n}</pre></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:09:29','2016-09-13 16:09:29',NULL),(204,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n    <li>Rename local copy demo database to \"<code>iaptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new empty local database called  \"<code>iaptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n    <li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n    <li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n    <li>Go to file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code> by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n    <li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n    <li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n    <li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables. </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>require(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc\');\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc\');\r\ndefine(\'SCORING_CLASS_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/\'); define(\'MYSQL_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/\');\r\ndefine(\'IAPTUS_PATH\', \'/iaptus/trunk/html\');\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)\r\n{\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(\'/var/www/html/\', \'\', $trace[0][\'file\']).\' Line: \'.$trace[0][\'line\'].\' Msg: \'.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\r\nerror_log(\'MySQL Error: \'.$report);\r\ndie(\'An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files\');\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }\r\n}</pre></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:10:22','2016-09-13 16:10:22',NULL),(205,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain etc see Dev-Ops->iaptus->Setup new IAPTus live sites.)','<p><em>NOTE - the script discussed in this article is a legacy script that has been proposed for refactoring. The following explanation is correct at the time of writing in August 2016.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Create New Single Service Database to go Live</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>When a client has approved their demo site developers need to get the relevant data from the demo database for that service and create an iaptus single service live database to be copied to the live server</strong>. Relevant entries for the global database relating to the new service also need to be run on the live global databases. This is all done using scripts located in <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools</code> folder that are run locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3> </h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Running the copy demo to live script</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n    <li>Export whole iaptus demo database from the demo server as mysqldump and then import locally to Vagrant box.</li>\r\n    <li>Rename local copy demo database to \"<code>iaptus_demo_bak&quot;.</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new empty local database called  \"<code>iaptus_new_client&quot;</code></li>\r\n    <li>Checkout up to date copy of the iaptus codebase (master) and go to the file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data_example.inc</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc</code> by copying db_data_example.inc</li>\r\n    <li>Edit the db_data_example.inc file so that it contains valid database details to create the $dbDemoBak and $dbNewClient connections to local databases iaptus_demo_bak and iaptus_new_client (see above)</li>\r\n    <li>Go to file at <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup_example.php</code></li>\r\n    <li>Create new file <code>iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/inc/setup.php</code> by copying setup_example.php</li>\r\n    <li>Edit setup.php so that it looks like setup.php below</li>\r\n    <li>In your browser go to your vagrant iaptus URL and append the path to the following file: iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/html/new_client.php. You should see a page of links to various New Client Setup tools.</li>\r\n    <li>Click the link labelled 2. New Client Setup. You should then get choices at the bottom. Check target and source databases, choose IAPT or CYP as appropriate and choose the appropriate service from the drop down list. Click Setup button. The database script should then put all the appropriate data into the iaptus_new_client database and you should also be given some SQL insert statements to be run on the Global iaptus databases for service specific entries from the demo global database tables. </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>setup.php</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><pre>&lt;?php\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/includes/iaptusdevelopment/db_data_old_style.inc\');\r\nrequire(\'/var/www/html/iaptus/tools/newClientSetupTools/db_data.inc\');\r\ndefine(\'SCORING_CLASS_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/html/forms/scoring/\'); define(\'MYSQL_PATH\', \'/var/www/html/iaptus/iaptus/tools/importTool/mysql/\');\r\ndefine(\'IAPTUS_PATH\', \'/iaptus/trunk/html\');\r\nfunction checkDBError(&amp;$DBObject)\r\n{\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; if (PEAR::isError($DBObject))\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; {\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $trace=debug_backtrace();\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $report=str_replace(\'/var/www/html/\', \'\', $trace[0][\'file\']).\' Line: \'.$trace[0][\'line\'].\' Msg: \'.$DBObject-&gt;getDebugInfo(); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\r\n        error_log(\'MySQL Error: \'.$report);\r\n        die(\'An unexpected database error occured, please ask an admin to check the log files\');\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; }\r\n}</pre></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:10:47','2016-09-13 16:10:47',NULL),(206,54,17,'Copy New Service From Demo DB to Live DB','Information about the tools folder scripts that are used when copying the relevant data for a new service from the demo database (which has all services) to a live database (with just the data for the new service which is going live). (For information about the Dev-Ops system team work in setting up a new database on the live server and registering the new domain 