ll the config files are in /etc/apcupsd/. The /etc/apcupsd/hosts.conf file lists the various devices you see on power.may so this is were you could add/update devices if necessary.  To actually setup a new ups on the monitoring takes more work, you need to attach it to something (you\'ll note the little old Samsung notebooks in the cupboard, they are setup with an ip and running centos with apcupsd, then connected via usb to the UPS.','<p>All the UPS monitoring is done via apcupsd service that runs on fileserver.may. You can ssh to the fileserver and do the usual service stuff: service apcupsd restart etc. All the config files are in /etc/apcupsd/. The /etc/apcupsd/hosts.conf file lists the various devices you see on power.may so this is were you could add/update devices if necessary.  To actually setup a new ups on the monitoring takes more work, you need to attach it to something (you\'ll note the little old Samsung notebooks in the cupboard, they are setup with an ip and running centos with apcupsd, then connected via usb to the UPS.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>If UPS reports \'No communications\'</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>After checking both the UPS is on and the attached device is working,  try unplugging the usb data cable between UPS & device, then re-plug.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If it still fails try a self test - press button front of UPS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Set up SNMP on a centos server </h3>\r\n\r\n<p># install packages</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nyum install net-snmp net-snmp-utils net-snmp-devel </pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# create user</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnet-snmp-config --create-snmpv3-user -A SHA -a \'PASSWORD\' -x AES -X \'PASSWORD\' -ro maydensnmp</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Autostart SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nchkconfig snmpd on\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>#or centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl enable snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Backup snmpd.conf first</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\ncp /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf.ori</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# then append the config</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nnano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf</pre>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<pre>rocommunity public5T88kl prtg.may:161\r\nrocommunity public5T88kl 127.0.0.1:161\r\nincludeAllDisks 10%\r\ndisk&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5%\r\nsyslocation Bat. C2\r\nsyscontact system@mayden.co.uk\r\nrouser maydensnmp priv</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Start SNMP</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nservice snmpd start\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p># centos7</p>\r\n\r\n<p>systemctl start snmpd.service</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# Verify it works on localhost</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nsnmpwalk -v 3 -l authPriv -a sha -A \'PASSWORD\' -x AES -X \'PASSWORD\' -u maydensnmp localhost | less</pre>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n# SNMP iptables rules (if required)</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\niptables -A INPUT -p udp -m udp -s 0/0 --dport 161:162 -j ACCEPT</pre>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Add device and sensors to PRTG</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>\'Add device\' at bottom of device view > select a group</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add name & DNS name (keep them the same if possible)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set sensor management to: Automatic device id (standard) > Continue</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leave it 5 minutes to scan the device, it will add a load of sensors, everything it can find, then trim them back to what you need.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-13 16:13:03','2016-09-13 16:13:03',NULL),(208,40,18,'UPS Monitoring','All the UPS monitoring is done via apcupsd service that runs on fileserver.may. You can ssh to the fileserver and do the usual service stuff: service apcupsd restart etc. All the config files are in /etc/apcupsd/. The /etc/apcupsd/hosts.conf file lists the various devices you see on power.may so this is were you could add/update devices if necessary.  To actually setup a new ups on the monitoring takes more work, you need to attach it to something (you\'ll note the little old Samsung notebooks in the cupboard, they are setup with an ip and running centos with apcupsd, then connected via usb to the UPS.','<p>All the UPS monitoring is 