xmlfeed.php?type=sms&amp;service=26&amp;dateFrom=2011-01-01&amp;dateTo=2012-01-01&amp;byDay=1&amp;byMonth=1&amp;idinloop=1&amp;IQLU6C0U4QCHLZEEC56XGKMEQ6OOXWFO1N4N9P872TRH1GB2X590EHX698RP=LAJG72RA2CA51HQIZRI0MN4YE5ZNPSYBXSE0IBLGIEW31HW8VT2B96L1DTHK\" target=\"_blank\">service-dateFrom-dateTo-byDay-byMonth-idInLoop-</a></p>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-22 13:23:16','2016-09-22 13:23:16',NULL),(292,82,32,'SMS Statuses','An explanation of what statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from AQL','<p>This is taken directly from AQL\'s site and explains what each of the statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMS delivery reports are acknowledgements from the handsets that the message has been received by the phone. This is not the same as being *READ* by the recipient and&nbsp;though some phones may receive the message, they may choose not to display it depending on the settings on the phone.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Statuses</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Sending</strong>: the message has been sent to the mobile networks - ie. it has left the AQL&nbsp;platform and is now in the hands of the mobile network</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Buffered</strong>: the&nbsp;message is on the network and awaiting delivery to the handset. Buffered will usually appear when there is either network or handset congestion - for example:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>the network provider is busy</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for delivery report from the handset</li>\r\n		<li>the handset\'s memory is full</li>\r\n		<li>the handset is switched off</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for the handset to accept the message.</li>\r\n		<li>bad reception or network coverage</li>\r\n		<li>out of service area</li>\r\n		<li>handset is not registered properly to a mast</li>\r\n		<li>The buffer memory (temporary holding memory) of the handset is corrupted</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Delivered&nbsp;</strong>to handset: handset has acknowledged the message. Note - the time of the delivery report = time for the message to be sent, PLUS the time for the delivery report to get back to AQL. This means that a delivery report taking 10 seconds means the message was probably delivered in about 5 seconds.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Rejected</strong>:&nbsp;message not delivered. This status could be caused by bad reception or out of service area. A few phone networks do reject sms if the phone is unreachable without further attempts. If you are using non-privileged route such as standard or economy route, \"Failed\" status will be returned if the mobile network is too busy processing data via privileged route. We would strongly suggest customer to route via our premium uk or global route because more often than not unprivileged-route ended up as failed.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Binary data not shown</strong>:&nbsp;the message is not text message. It could be a wap-push message, mms message, ringtones, images, vcard, the message being&nbsp;split up into different packets etc</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Invalid Number</strong>:&nbsp;means that the destination number is not a valid number.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-22 13:27:40','2016-09-22 13:27:40',NULL),(293,82,11,'SMS Statuses','An explanation of what statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from AQL','<p>This is taken directly from AQL\'s site and explains what each of the statuses mean when viewing a CSV which has been downloaded from them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMS delivery reports are acknowledgements from the handsets that the message has been received by the phone. This is not the same as being *READ* by the recipient and&nbsp;though some phones may receive the message, they may choose not to display it depending on the settings on the phone.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Statuses</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Sending</strong>: the message has been sent to the mobile networks - ie. it has left the AQL&nbsp;platform and is now in the hands of the mobile network</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Buffered</strong>: the&nbsp;message is on the network and awaiting delivery to the handset. Buffered will usually appear when there is either network or handset congestion - for example:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>the network provider is busy</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for delivery report from the handset</li>\r\n		<li>the handset\'s memory is full</li>\r\n		<li>the handset is switched off</li>\r\n		<li>the network is waiting for the handset to accept the message.</li>\r\n		<li>bad reception or network coverage</li>\r\n		<li>out of service area</li>\r\n		<li>handset is not registered properly to a mast</li>\r\n		<li>The buffer memory (temporary holding memory) of the handset is corrupted</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Delivered&nbsp;</strong>to handset: handset has acknowledged the message. Note - the time of the delivery report = time for the message to be sent, PLUS the time for the delivery report to get back to AQL. This means that a delivery report taking 10 seconds means the message was probably delivered in about 5 seconds.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Rejected</strong>:&nbsp;message not delivered. This status could be caused by bad reception or out of service area. A few phone networks do reject sms if the phone is unreachable without further attempts. If you are using non-privileged route such as standard or economy route, \"Failed\" status will be returned if the mobile network is too busy processing data via privileged route. We would strongly suggest customer to route via our premium uk or global route because more often than not unprivileged-route ended up as failed.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Binary data not shown</strong>:&nbsp;the message is not text message. It could be a wap-push message, mms message, ringtones, images, vcard, the message being&nbsp;split up into different packets etc</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Invalid Number</strong>:&nbsp;means that the destination number is not a valid number.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-22 13:29:35','2016-09-22 13:29:35',NULL),(294,66,7,'Add Field to Group Sessions','How to add a field to group sessions for a service','<p>To start with, you need to know whether the field you need to add to group session exists in the nh_fields table.&nbsp;If the field&nbsp;<strong>does not</strong>&nbsp;exist, you need to write a patch which adds it to the nh_fields table and arrange for it to be deployed. You cannot add it to group sessions until this has been done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To add an&nbsp;<strong>existing</strong>&nbsp;field to group sessions, follow these steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Write a patch which adds the field to the nh_fieldsSer table. Check the notes for help replacing the placeholders in this query:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<pre>\r\nINSERT INTO nh_fieldsSer table (fieldId, priority, type, course_order, ser_id, live) VALUES (FIELD_ID_HERE, PRIORITY_HERE, TYPE_HERE, COURSE_ORDER_HERE, SERVICE_ID_HERE, 1);</pre>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Add the fieldId into nh_fieldsSer table, set priority, course_order = \'position in which the field appears on the front end\'.</li>\r\n	<li>Add the field to the groups template.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Replace the following placeholders in the query above with:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>FIELD_ID_HERE: id of the field you want to add to group sessions</li>\r\n	<li>PRIORITY_HERE:&nbsp;<strong>1</strong> if always&nbsp;mandatory, <strong>2</strong> if manadtory unless \'allow less than minimum dataset\' is ticked, <strong>3</strong> if always optional or <strong>4</strong> if always mandatory for MDS</li>\r\n	<li>TYPE_HERE:&nbsp;<strong>0</strong>&nbsp;for not dataset specific,&nbsp;<strong>1</strong>&nbsp;for IAPT dataset,&nbsp;<strong>2</strong>&nbsp;for Employment&nbsp;dataset, <strong>4</strong>&nbsp;for CYP dataset</li>\r\n	<li>COURSE_ORDER_HERE:&nbsp;the number of the position that the field appears on the iaptus front end</li>\r\n	<li>SERVICE_ID_HERE: id of the service you want to add the field for</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n',1,1,'2016-09-22 13:46:16','2016-09-22 13:46:16',NULL);
